description: Warrumbungle National Park, 28.8km west of Coonabarabran.
comments: Lower bottom slope of the range. 3 degree slope but 5-6 degrees at SW corner. NW aspect. Mostly cobbles of metamorphosed sandstone origin. Some pockets of very low outcrop as well. Burnt in 2013 but not as severe as further up ridge- not as much crown burn. Pig trap in the middle of the plot. Old concrete block ( amenity block from old campground?) and old disused track just creeps in on western edge. Introduced plant effect- check with Herbarium Ids. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- SW corner rises up onto slope of ridge with ironbarks. Northern edge is close to the road and western edge is turn around area for walking trail. 10m from northern edge to road. 10m from western edge to turnaround area.
location_description: Warrumbungles National Park, 28.8km west of Coonabarabran

description: Warrumbungle National Park. 893m north west of Visitors Centre, 27.3km west of Coonabarabran.
comments: The Landform element is a hill slope with a pattern of hills. South west corner is on the ridge crest with the rest of the site slope down in northeast direction at 6-7 degrees, levelling off at the northeast corner. There are outcrops present and cobbles and some gravels and boulder. Lithology metamorphosed sandstone. Site was burnt in 2013, most of the Eucalypts are still alive but a majority of the Callitris endlicheri are dead. Regeneration of the Acacia buxifolia and Acacia harpophylla has probably happened since the fire. Heavily impacted by goats and some roos, most of the grasses have been heavily grazed. Introduced plant species impact is low with Heliotropium amplexicaule and Urtica incisa present. Vegetation community is confined to the plot. Site gets more dense in southwest corner with Acacia harpophylla and some Eucalyptus dealbata on ridge line.
location_description: Warrumbungle National Park, 893m north west of visitors centre. 27.3km west of Coonabarrabran

description: Pilliga State Conservation Area. 56.8km north east of Baradine.
comments: Site is flat. No surface strew or lithology apparent, mostly quite sandy. A fair amount of dead course wood debris. Long unburnt. Grazing impact minimal, mostly kangaroos and goats. Community extends 50m from plot in all directions. Introduced plant impact is low, some Opuntia sp. present and possibly some introduced forbs. Some of the older trees, Eucalyptus crebra have been cut, maybe some selective logging previously.
location_description: Pilliga state conservation area, 56.8km north east of Barradine

description: Broken Hill Town Common? 7.5km north north west of Broken Hill
comments: Toe slope of a low rise. Sloping to the south west by 2 degrees. Rise on north eastern edge. Minimal surface strew- some very fine gravels but lots of cryptogam crust. Introduced plant effect is minimal- Conyza bonariensis present but very low cover.  Homogeneity- confined to site- more Maireana spp. on northern edge. Road is 60m north from the site. Plot is marked- SW corner is marked with fiberglass pole centre with a star picket.
location_description: Introduced plant effect is minimal- Conyza bonariensis present but very low cover.  Homogeneity- confined to site- more Maireana spp. on northern edge. Plot is marked- SW corner is marked with fiberglass pole centre with a star picket.

description: Broken Hill Town Common?, 4.5km north west of Broken Hill
comments: Plot is on a plain between low rises. Slope to the south east rising more towards the north west corner where there is a low rise. 3 degree slope. Drainage line though the centre of the site running east but overall slope is to the south east. Some gravels through the site- mostly quartzite but some limestone gravels. Plot is within the regeneration reserve but some dirt bike tracks around ( but not in) the site- 50m away. 200m from main sealed road. Plot not marked. Minimal impact of introduced plant species,  Sonchus oleraceus present.
location_description: Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot- continues to the east but to the south is a limestone rise with Acacia aneura.Lots of Cryptogam.

description: 100m west of Yancowinna Creek, 47km east of Broken Hill
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is low chenapod shrubland damoniated by Maireana aphylla, Maireana georgei, Atriplex vesicaria, Sclerolaena ventricasa and the Burr medic. The rest of the site is made up of other Sclerolaena and Maireana species, Tiny grass, Abutilon, Chenopodium, Sida intrcicata and other grasses and forbs. The upper shrub layer is a maximum of 50cm. The dominant Mairenana species average 40cm, and the Atriplex, Sclerolaena species average 20cm and the small grass and forbs average 5-10cm.
There has been rain in the past 6 week, it is dry underfoot but all of the plants are green and showing signs of active growth. The Sclerolaena’s, Atriplex and Maireanas are all fruiting. The Medicado, Sida, Pimelea are all flowering. Some of the grasses such as the Austrostipa and Rhytidasperma have started to dry off and are setting seed.
The site is a plain on a plain, with a 1 degree slope from the North to the South. There are some gilgai’s that are cracking. There is small amount of scattered gibber throughout the site but would be less than 5% of the site.
In terms of introduced species, there are a few scattered including Thistle and Medicargo. There is evidence of grazing from sheep on the site with some of the more palatable species showing damage especially on the Minuria cunninghamii and some of the Maireana species. No recent fires to note. The closest infrastructure is a track 20m from the SE corner, to the West is a water point 1km away. The site is homogenous, however it doesn’t extend to the South due to the road, but does extend to the North and East approximately 100m
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------

description: As previous
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a plain. Some gilgai features. No outcrop. Some small quartzite gravel (20-30mm diameter). Slight (1 degree) slope from NW to SE.

Introduced species impact is moderate. Ward’s weed is extensive across the site and there are potentially some invasive Sonchus spp. present.
Grazing impact is minimal. E. maculata and some grasses grazed, likely by goats or kangaroos. No evidence of fire. Nearest infrastructure is the Barrier highway 150m from SW corner. Homogenous. Community extends 100m to the west and north from the centre.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Low impact of introduced plant species- Carrichtera annua and Eragrostis curvula low cover.
location_description: Astrebla pectinata/ Enneapogon avenaceus low open tussock grassland.

description: 6.7k east of K-Tank Station, 31.7km north east of Broken Hill.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a low chenapod shrubland dominated by Sclerolaena longicuspis, Sclerolaena divaricate, Maireana astrotricha and Wards weed. The rest of the site is made up of other Sclerolaena species, Atriplex vesicaria, tussock grasses and other forbs. The average height for the Maireana astrotricha is between 30-60cm tall, the Sclerolaena species average between 15-30cm and the forb layer averages 10cm.
There has been recent rain in the last week, at least 60mm approximately 5 days ago. Many of the gilgai’s are still damp. The Maireana astrotricha and Atriplex vesicaria have a small amount of fruit, all the Sclerolaena’s have seed and many of the forbs such as the Wards weed, Abutilon, Lotus and goodenia are all flowering.
The landform element and pattern is a hillslope on a rise, the slope is approximately 4% sloping down to a dam to the S-SW of the site. There is lots of gibber across the site, mostly smaller gravel but also a few rocks to 12-15cm.
In terms of introduced species, there is a significant amount of wards weed in the site and was collected as a dominant species. Grazing is low with a fence close by to stop cattle, with evidence of kangaroo. Possible history of previous grazing due to the size of the dam. There is no evidence of recent fire. The nearest infrastructure the Barrier highway 100m to the North, but also many fence lines around the site. The dam is approximately 1km to the South. The site is homogenous but doesn’t extend to the North due to the rise, but extends 150m to the South, East and West.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Minimal impact of introduce species; some Carrichtera annua, Eragrostis curvula, Sonchus oleraceus and Malvastrum americanum present.
location_description: Enneapogon avenaceus low open tussock grassland to Sclerolaena sp. sparse Chenopod shrubland.

description: rocky wasteland
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element is a plain, pattern is a plain. Gentle slope (1-2 degrees) to NE. Lithology, some exposed phylite. Gravel surface strew mostly of quartz. Grazing impact is high, all the Maireana spp. are grazed and tussock grass chewed down to the base. Feral goats present (large heard seen near plot >40 head). Sheep and kangaroo grazing also occurring. Station destocking sheep. Introduced plant impact is minimal, no introduce plant recorded. Site is homogenous and community extends 200m north, east, south and 60m west. Nearest infrastructure is the fence line 300-400m SW of site. Informal vehicle track to site. Site is long unburnt no evidence of past fire.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
High impact of introduced plant species- Salvia verbenaca extremely high cover.
location_description: Atriplex vesicaria / Sclerolaena sp. low sparse Chenopod shrubland.

description: Fowlers Gap Research Station, 7,3km north west of homestead. 105km north north west of Broken Hill. 9.7km west of Silver City highway.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is plain on a plain. 1-degree slope to the north east. Surface strew comprised of cobble and pebble size is very common across the site. Geology of surface strew is quartzite, quartz and conglomerate, and soil is cracking clay on the surface.
Minimal or no introduced plant impact. Evidence of kangaroos, goats and sheep, with dung observed on the site, with some species e.g. Tripogonella loliiformis grazed back to butts. Other palatable species such as Astrebla sp. have minimal sign of grazing since the last rain. The research station is currently in the process of destocking. Long unburnt with no evidence of past fire. Nearest infrastructure is the paddock fence line and access track approximately south east 30m from the SE corner. Site is homogenous, extending from the centre 150m to the east, 200m to the south, and at least 300m to the north and west.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Atriplex vesicaria / Sclerolaena sp. low sparse chenopod shrubland.

Strew is a mix of gravels and cobbles. Low impact of introduced plant species- Schismus barbatus low cover.

description: Fowlers Gap Arid Zone Research Station, Eucalyptus camaldulensis swamp
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Flat site. Long unburnt. Site is grazed, cattle scats in the sit but effect is low. Minimal introduced plant species- possible a Brassica species. No surface strew. Floodplain of Strzelecki creek – flood out on plain. 3km between dunes where Strzelecki creek flows north to cooper creek. Community is homogenous but site is heterogenous at a sub hectare level. 80m from centre is the same community. 50m north of plot is Strzelecki track.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Swamp on an alluvial plain. Plot sits at the end of a man-made dam. It is likely that much of the woodland has developed since the creation of the dam. Plot is sloping 2 degrees broadly to the south (170 degrees)  Also rises up at the north east corner where it is just out of the swamp. Minimal surface strew at north east corner on rise. Sandstone below the surface. Some cobbles in stream bank and channel, some quartzite and sandstone as in Pit. Modearate impact of introduced plant species- Sisymbrium erysimoides, Leontodon rhagadioloides and Centaurea melitensis low cover.
visit_notes: Unknown substrate is water.
location_description: Introduced plant effect is high- ground stratum is dominated by introduced forbs.  Homogeneity- Community is contained to the plot. Grazing effect is low- sheep and goats but minimal feed for stock. Long unburnt. Likely unburnt since creation of the dam- Surrounded by much more open country.

description: Sturt National Park, 4.8km north east of Mt wood shearers quarters
comments: Plot is on low rocky rise 20m up from surrounding plains. 5 degree slope to the north east- flatter on western edge but getting steeper to the north east. Embedded boulders/outcrop and lots of cobbles and gravels of sandstone possibly metamorphosed. Flecks of ironstone and quartz through the site. Minimal introduced plant species noted at visit. Grazing effect is from low to moderate kangaroos- no goats noted but likely present. Long unburnt- very sparse ground cover. Homogeneity- community extends 40m west and north. Eastern edge is 20m to road.
visit_notes: only SW corner and centre marked
location_description: Sturt National Park, 4.8km north east of Mt wood shearers quarters

description: Sturt National Park, 20.4km north west of Mount Wood shearers quarters. 21.6km north east of Tibooburra
comments: Bed of 12 Mile Creek. Minimal surface strew- some alluvial wash in the creek. Most of the Chenopodium auricomum have been grazed by Kangaroos. 20m from south west corner is old bore and tank so would have been more heavily grazed in the past. Plot is largely flat with deeper channel of the creek flowing eastward. Community is confined to plot- south west corner rise up out of main swampy area. A shallow channel runs north close to the south west corner- deeper main bed of creek is north of that. North east corner just comes up on to sandier ridge in middle of channel which is  sparser.
location_description: Sturt National Park, 20.4km north west of Mount wood shearers quarters. 21.6km north east of Tibooburra.

description: Sturt National Park, 5km north north east of Mt King homestead. 26.8km north west of Tibooburra.
comments: Plot sits in the channel of Cannina Creek. Slightly deeper channel runs east to west along southern boundary. Site is mostly flat with a 1 degree slope to the east with some undulations due to deposited material. Minimal surface strew. Grazing effect is severe- Kangaroos and cattle- all of the Chenopodium have had leaves eaten away. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species effect is low at present but difficult to tell due to dryness and grazing. Homogeneity- Vegetation community is confined to the plot- either side of the plot is more open plains. North east corner is 20m in from jump up loops track moving away from the track into the plot.
location_description: Sturt National Park, 5km north north east of Mt King homestead. 26.8km north west of Tibooburra.

description: Sturt National Park,  21.5km North north west of Mount King homestead. 43 km north west of Tibooburra
location_description: Sturt National Park,  21.5km North north west of Mount King homestead. 43 km north west of Tibooburra

description: Yathong Nature Reserve, 4.5km north west of Park office. 99km due north of Hillston
comments: Plot is flat in very broad creek channel that flows towards the north west.
visit_notes: Fresh rabbit diggings in SE corner of plot with a 10m. radius.Tall standing dead annual Forbes possibly weedy, also a lot of medicago and potentially ward weed.Less common horehound around bases of trees.Grazing pressure is high, mainly from Kangaroos but also from goats and there is a large rabbit warren close to centre of the plot. Long unburnt- 1980s or before ( pers com with Rangers).
location_description: Yathong Nature Reserve, 4.5km north west of Park office. 99km due north of Hillston

description: Yathong Nature Reserve, 9.3km east north east of ranger station. 98km north of Hillston
comments: Footslope of low hills. Minimal surface strew- some sandstone gravels and pebbles. No rock outcrop. Very gentle slope to the north- drainage line ( old track? outside the plot to the north east.
location_description: plot sits in broad valley of Callitris glaucophylla which extends 20m beyond plot in all directions. 20m from park access track to the north.  Long unburnt- no scarring on any trees. Introduced plant effect is low at present. Possibly some annuals but very dry.  Grazing effect is low -Goats and Kangaroos. Eucalypts fruiting

description: Mallee Cliffs National Park. 10.5km north west of old station homestead. 36.7km west of Mildura
comments: Small plain surrounded by dunes.  Contour bank to the north, immediately adjacent to and just off the plot. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichtera annua high cover.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measures.Site is homogenous, extends >200m to Mallee on dunes.
location_description: Austrostipa sp grassland to Carrichtera annua, Erodium crinitum, Euphorbia dallachyana mixed species forbland with scattered chenopod low shrubs on small plain surrounded by dunes.  Carrichtera annua is a prominent weed. Site was previously grazed.  Some evidence of rabbits. No evidence of fire.

description: Mallee Cliffs National Park on Central Fire Trail, 30km east of Mildura.
comments: Site on the slope of low relic dune. Sloping gently to the south east. Very long unburnt- at least 1970s since fire possibly longer. Grazing effect low- rabbits in park but no evidence within the plot. Introduced plant effect low- some Carrichtera annua creeping in on the crest of the dune in the north western edge of the plot where it opens up more but cover is low. Lots of Cryptogam crust and leaf litter.
location_description: Mallee Cliffs NP on Central Fire Trail, 30kms east of Mildura. Mallee woodland with Triodia understorey

description: Mallee Cliffs National Park. 5.7km west of Mallee cliffs homestead ruins, 40.8km west of Mildura.
comments: Swale between dunes. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Carrichtera annua moderate cover.
visit_notes:
Insufficient canopy height and overall density of shrubs precluded basal wedge measures.
Site is homogenous (70m to nearest Mallee community to the south and 200m to north, west and east.
location_description: No evidence of fire. Fire history shows no fire since 1974. Rabbit droppings and digging were evident and common. One Eucalyptus dumosa (Mallee) on southern margin. Weeds present, notably Carrichtera annua.

description: Mallee Cliffs National Park, Dead Horse Fire Trail, 37kms east of Mildura.
comments: A sandplain fringed by relic dunes some distance away. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichterea annua high cover and some Sonchus sp.
location_description: Belah woodland.Lots of Cryptogam crust and some mosses. Very long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees. Some fallen branches and litter but unburnt since 1970s. Some isolated very old stumps cut for timber. Introduced plant effect moderate- Carrichtera annua dominant in ground layer as well as some other exotic forbs. Grazing effect is moderate- evidence of Kangaroos and Emus as well as rabbits. Homogeneity.- community extends 100m to the south but bisected by track. West borders Mallee 30m from site where there is Mallee on relic dune. East 100m but bisected by track. 50m to the north.Dead Horse Fire Trail, Mallee Cliffs National Park, 37kms east of Mildura.

description: Mungo National Park about 130kms NE of Mildura
comments: Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Medicago minima, Carrichtera annua, Sisymbrium sp. present.

description: Mungo National Park, 130kms north east of Mildura
comments: Sandplain sloping to a very low dune in north east corner. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Very long unburnt, very little standing dead litter. Grazing effect is moderate to severe- much rabbit damage as well as high numbers of kangaroos through the park.  Introduced plant effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua in some denser pockets but not really dominant in cover. Homogeneity- east another 100m but bisected by track, west 100m, south only 20m till it opens up. Northern edge is an Alectryon oleifolius subsp. canescens swamp. Lots of cryptogam possibly because of recent rain.

description: Tarawi Nature Reserve, 6.7km north of Ranger station. 131km west of Pooncarie.
comments: Eucalyptus socialis, E. dumosa and Callitris verrucosa Mallee low woodland with mid layer of Acacia colletioides and Beyaria opaca and a ground layer of Triodia scariosa on a dune crest.
location_description: Eucalyptus socialis, E. dumosa and Callitris verrucosa Mallee low woodland with mid layer of Acacia colletioides and Beyaria opaca and a ground layer of Triodia scariosa on a dune crest. No evidence of weeds. Some evidence of rabbits- scats and digging.

description: Tarawi Nature Reserve, 8km west of homestead near southeast corner of Canopus and West Fire Trails, about 100kms northwest of Wentworth.
comments: Flat sand plain with calcrete underneath.Some limestone nodules or Calcretions- nothing bigger than 5 cms. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
visit_notes: Rock with Cryptogam cover called Crypotogam in point intercept. Homogeneity- community is more or less confined to the plot.
location_description: Long unburnt. Closer to the track outside the plot has possibly been burnt as a fire break. Just creeps into the north east corner. Grazing effect- some rabbits and kangaroos but effect low. Introduced plant effect low- some Medicago sp. and Brassica sp. but minimal cover. Some recruitment in Dodonaea   To the north, south and west borders a Casuarina pauper community and to the east opens up into an Olearia shrubland. Lots of Cryptogam possibly as result of recent rain.

description: Tarawi Nature Reserve, 8.5 km west of Ranger station. 140km west of Pooncarie
comments: Casuarina pauper and Alectryon oleifolius subsp. canescens woodland with mid-stratum of  Maireana sedifolia and scattered Eremophila sturtii. Ground stratum is mostly bare.
location_description: Casuarina pauper and Alectryon oleifolius subsp. canescens woodland with mid-stratum of  Maireana sedifolia and scattered Eremophila sturtii. Ground stratum is mostly bare. Plot is homogenous (>100m) but shows long standing rabbit damage and has some areas where warrens have been ripped in the past. No evidence of fire. No evidence of weeds.

description: Tarawi Nature Reserve, near Cane grass Tank. 100km north west of Wentworth.
comments: Drainage depression on sand plain. Plot is more or less in a bowl with dunes at southern and northern edges. On the southern boundary is a very low sandy rise with Dodonaea along it. Some recruitment of Dodonaea from here into the site. High impact of introduced plant species- Salvia verbenaca high cover.
visit_notes: Co-located on Park site 44. Fungi collected by Jasmin Packer.
location_description:
Drainage depression on sand plain. Plot is more or less in a bowl with dunes at southern and northern edges. On the southern boundary is a very low sandy rise with Dodonaea along it. Some recruitment of Dodonaea from here into the site.
Introduced plant effect is severe- dominated by Salvia verbenaca and Medicago sp and other introduced forbs. Grazing effect is high- goats, kangaroos and rabbits. Big rabbit warren on western edge. Fire impact difficult to tell- some Dodonaea viscosa dead but not sure if from fire or round up ( site may have been sprayed for weeds in the past) No scorch marks on shrubs. Homogeneity- community continues to the south 30m on other side of low rise. On the northern edge Eucalyptus porosa comes close to plot edge. To the east is more wooded. Continues 40m to the west along drainage depression. Some isolated limestone cobbles and gravels. Star picket in site from NSW parks monitoring.

description: Tarawi Nature Reserve, 13.4km west of Ranger station. 145km west of Pooncarie
comments: Eucalyptus dumosa Mallee low woodland with Eucalyptus gracilis and Eucalyptus socialis. Mixed species sparse mid stratum. Ground stratum is dominated by Triodia scariosa. Adjacent to David Keith site. ( Centre for Ecosystem Science UNSW)
visit_notes: Insufficient woody trees for basal wedge measures
location_description: Eucalyptus dumosa Mallee low woodland with Eucalyptus gracilis and Eucalyptus socialis. Mixed species sparse mid stratum. Ground stratum is dominated by Triodia scariosa. Trees are regrowth after fire in 2005. No evidence of weeds. Adjacent to David Keith site. Site is homogenous >200m.

description: Playa Lake, Scotia Sanctuary. About 100km north west of Wentworth.
comments: Low samphire shrubland at Playa Lake, Scotia Sanctuary.Playa lake surrounded by lunette dunes. Southern third has sandy wash, remainder is clay. Centre point only point marked with picket.
location_description: Playa lake surrounded by lunette dunes. Southern third has sandy wash, remainder is clay. Homogeneity- southern end of plot is the edge of the samphire community. East and north community continues another 100m, west 50m. Long unburnt. Grazing effect is minimal, some evidence of kangaroos. Introduced plant effect, nil.  Centre point only point marked with picket.

description: Scotia Sanctuary. 6.2km south west of park head quarters. 137km west north west of Pooncarie
comments: Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Eucalyptus dumosa and E. gracilis low open Mallee woodland with mid stratum of Beyeria opaca and Chenopodium curvispicatum and ground stratum of Triodia scariosa, on dune. Site is homogenous (50m south and 100m north). Trees are regrowth following fire in 2011. Adjacent to David Keith site.( Centre for Ecosystem Science UNSW) Evidence of rabbits- warrens on site. Recent rain left standing water in lower parts of site hence some ephemeral aquatic plants collected.

description: Scotia Sanctuary. 8kms north of homestead 131 kms northwest of Wentworth.
comments: Within fenced Scotia sanctuary, dune field with the plot on a gentle dune slope. Slope 2 degrees to the north. Very Long unburnt- 30-40 years. Grazing effect is moderate but lots of fauna diggings. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Cirsium vulgare present.
location_description: Dune field with the plot on a gentle dune slope. Slope 2 degrees to the north.  Very Long unburnt- 30-40 years. Grazing effect is moderate but lots of fauna diggings. ( site is inside enclosure at Scotia sanctuary) Introduced plant effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community continues 100m to south and west. To the east is a cleared line along road but community continues 30m beyond that. 40m to the north. Unburnt. Within fenced Scotia sanctuary.Mallee Triodia unburnt 8kms north of Scotia Homestaed and 131 kms northwest of Wentworth

description: Scotia Sanctuary on West Fire Trail about 2kms north of Adams Dam and 135kms northwest of Wentworth.
comments: Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cirsium vulgare present.
location_description: Casuarina cristata woodland in Scotia Sanctuary on West Fire Trail about 2kms north of Adams Dam and 135kms northwest of Wentworth.

description: Scotia Sanctuary. 10.4km south west of ranger station. 138km west north west of Pooncarie
comments: Plain within sand plain with a gentle slope to the north east. Long unburnt- no evidence of fire in site or surrounding Mallee. Introduced plant species effect is high- Salvia herb is dominant through ground layer but much more native species than similar site on Tarawi (NSAMDD0010). Grazing effect is low at present- scratching at the bottom of shrubs from kangaroos. Would have been heavily impacted in the past- close to an old dam. Possibly cleared. Lots of calcareous gravel through the site.
location_description: Scotia Sanctuary. 10.4km south west of ranger station. 138km west north west of Pooncarie

description: Langtree Nature Reserve. 21km south south west of Hillston
comments: No evidence of fire. Evidence of browsing / grazing by goats and rabbits.  Site is homogeneous <70m with tracks immediately west and north of plot. Low impact of introduced plant species- Brassica fruticulosa low cover.
location_description: Casuarina pauper woodland with scattered shrubs and bare ground stratum. No evidence of fire. Evidence of browsing / grazing by goats and rabbits.  Site is homogeneous <70m with tracks immediately west and north of plot.

description: Loughnan Nature Reserve, 25kms southeast of Hillston, NSW
comments: Plain. Site is flat. Grazing effect moderate- some rabbits as well as goats. Weed impact low- possibly Brassica sp and Erodium sp. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees. No surface strew or outcrop.
location_description: Laughnan Nature Reserve about 25kms southeast of Hillston, NSW

description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 840m north west of Lysmoyle homestead ruins, 35.6km north east of Hillston
comments: Grazing is evident - rabbits common (active warrens present), Macropods and goats. The site appears long unburnt, evidence is no scorch marks on the single Hakea tree present.  Evidence of past logging, with presence of stumps of small trees / large shrubs. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Echium plantagineum moderate cover, Medicago minima also present.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measures.
location_description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 840m north west of Lysmoyle Homestead ruins, 35.6km north east of Hillstone.

description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 1km south west of old Nombinnie homestead. 35km north east of Hillston and .
comments: Plot is in a large drainage depression / swamp. Site gently undulating but more or less flat. Grazing effect is high- kangaroos, goats with cattle scats and tracks also noted. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and very little ground cover to carry a fire. Homogeneity- plot is on the northern edge of the E. largiflorens community. Opens up into a grassland to the north. Continues 1km to the south from the plot. Minimal surface strew- some leaf litter. Introduced plant effect is low- some Brassica sp. under the trees and Medicago minima through the site.
location_description: Nombinnie NP about 35kms northeast of Hillston and 1km southwest of old Nombinnie homestead. Eucalyptus largiflorens on drainage depression.

description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 1.2 km east south east of Lysmoyle homestead ruins, 35.4km north east of Hillston.
comments: Eucalyptus populnea open woodland with sparse shrub layer. Bare ground and cryptogam prominent. Echium plantagineum common. Rabbit warrens present, have been ripped. Some evidence of rabbit digging still present. No evidence of recent fire. Site homogenous >100m.
location_description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 1.2 km east south east of Lysmoyle homestead ruins, 35.4km north east of Hillston.

description: Nombinnie Nature Reserve. 35km north east of Hillston
comments: Plain. Flat with a 0.5 degree  to the south. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and mid layer thick. Introduced plant effect is low- none noted. Grazing effect low- minimal feed. Kangaroo pads but also possibly deer ( sited near plot) and goats. Very fine sandy gravel at surface.
visit_notes: Transect W5 to E5 points 75 to 100 not recorded
location_description: Nombinnie conservation reserve. 5.9km south east of Lysmoyle homestead ruins, 35.3km north east of Hillston.

description: Kajuligah Nature Reserve. 12 km south of Kajuligah homestead, 40km north east of Ivanhoe.
comments: Rabbit warrens common but not active. Some evidence on site of old fire scars, nothing recent. Flogged. Evidence of more recent fire close to but not on the site. Homogenous to 80m. High impact of introduced plant species- Carrichterea annua high cover.
location_description: Kajuligah Nature Reserve. 12 km south of Kajuligah homestead, 40km north east of Ivanhoe

description: Kajuligah Nature Reserve. About 39kms northeast of Ivanhoe
comments: Very shallow drainage depression- more Casuarina pauper on surrounding low ridges. Lots of cryptogam crust. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. To the north west grades into more dense Acacia aneura with very little understory. To the east community continues another 50m and to the north and south borders it borders on a more open Eremophila longifolia community.  Fire- very long unburnt. No scarring on trees and very little dead shrubs. Grazing effect is low- some cattle pads but quite old. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Medicago minima dominant in ground stratum but cover low at present.
location_description: Mulga tall shrubland on Kajuligah NR about 39kms northeast of Ivanhoe

description: Paroo Darling National Park. 300m north west of Coonavitra homestead, 84km west of Wilcannia
comments: Eucalyptus populnea woodland in terminal drainage depression. Homogeneous (<80m), surrounded by sand ridges. Small dam in depression immediately to south of site, in same community. Heavy grazing by Macropods. No evidence of fire. Weeds common e.g. Marrubium vulgare, Oxalis sp. and Salvia verbenacea. Evidence of past logging.
location_description: Paroo Darling National Park. 300m north west of Coonavitra homestead, 84km west of Willcania

description: Paroo Darling National Park, About 80kms east of Wilcannia. Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP. Acacia victoriae shrubland.
comments: Plain. To the north of the site is dune with Alectryon and Casuarina pauper. Grazing effect is severe- rabbits mainly ( 2 large warrens in the site) but also goats and kangaroos. Fire-has had a hot fire recently. previous to that, 10 years. Lots of coarse woody debris that would likely have been Alectryon oleifolius but none present in site now. Calcareous sandstone concretions- formed in root tunnels after fire. Mostly gravels with some larger pebbles. Homogeneity- community continues 60m to the west, north and east is track and then dune slope. Introduced plant effect is severe- ground layer dominated by Medicago minima with Marrubium vulgare also present. Community is transitional- likely to have been Alectryon woodland in the past but no sign of Alectryon regenerating.
location_description: About 80kms east of Wilcannia. Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP. Acacia victoriae shrubland.

description: Paroo Darling National Park, About 42kms east of Wilcannia on northern boundary of Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP.
comments: Acacia aneura low woodland on rocky hill slope, with sparse mid-layer of Eremophila longifolia and Senna artemisioides subsp. artemisioides. Ground layer bare and rocky with scattered short grasses and forbs. No sign of recent fire, no weeds. Some evidence of minor grazing by goats and Macropods. Mistletoe common on Acacia aneura. Scar on northern edge of plot from scrape for road building. Site is homogenous >80m but with road close to northern edge.
location_description: About 42kms east of Wilcannia on northern boundary of Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP. Mulga shrubland on rocky hill.

description: Paroo Darling National Park, About 40 kms east of Wilcannia. On north boundary of Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP.
comments: Sand plain. To the south of the site is low range of hills but site is flat. To the north of the site is a deep erosion gully to 1m deep. Introduced plant effect low- some Medicago but cover low. Long unburnt- no burn marks or dead shrubs. Some old fallen timber.  Minimal surface strew. Grazing effect is moderate- kangaroos and rabbits. Homogeneity- continues 100m on other side of drainage channel on northern edge. To south opens up into Chenopod shrubland. Community continues 30m further to the east and west.
visit_notes: Dodonaea shrubland.
location_description: 40 kms east of Wilcannia. On north boundary of Coonavitra section of Paroo Darling NP. Dodonaea shrubland.

description: Paroo Darling National  Park. 6km south west of Tilpilly homestead. 98.5km west north west of Wilcannia
comments: Site is homogenous >80m. No evidence of fire, feral animals, grazing.   Minimal impact of introduced plant species - Medicago minima present. Scattering of limestone strew restricted to southern edge of plot.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measures.
location_description: Paroo Darling National  Park. 6km south west of Tilpilly homestead. 98.5km west north west of Willcania

description: Paroo Darling National Park, About 60kms east of Wilcannia on Tilpilly section of Paroo Darling NP. About 5kms west of Tilpilly homestead.
comments: Drainage depression- plot is on edge of larger swamp which borders site on north west corner. Some gentle undulation through the site.  Grazing effect is low but evidence of goats- pads through the site. Very long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees. Introduced plant effect is low- lots of Medicago seed and possibly Salvia verbenacea but currently low cover due to lack of rain. Minimal surface strew. Some scattered calcareous coarse fragments particularly towards south eastern corner of the site, minimal cover. Homogeneity- community is confined to the site. To the south borders a Dodonaea viscosa shrubland, north is lake bed/ swamp, north east and south west community continues 50m beyond plot.
location_description: 60km. east of Wilcannia on Tilpilly section of Paroo Darling NP. About 5kms west of Tilpilly homestead.

description: Yathong Nature Reserve, 99km north north west of Hillston
comments: Plot sits in broad swale rising very gently to the south east. Leaf litter under the trees but bulk of bare ground is made up of cryptogam crust. Grazing pressure less than previous site ( NSACOP0002)- kangaroos, goats, rabbits and echidnas. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees- older trees have fallen. Coarse woody debris where trees have fallen. ( check with NPWS if has been chained in past). Introduced plant species effect is low at time of visit- very dry. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot SE corner gets into more sandy Triodia sp. community.
location_description: Yathong Nature Reserve, 99km north north west of Hillston

description: Yathong Nature Reserve, approx 2km south of old Glenlea homestead. Aprox 50km north north west of Hillston
comments: Plot sits on low rise, 10-20cms above surrounding landscape. Ironstone cobbles and gravels with some scattered (iron rich) sandstone Grazing effect is moderate- kangaroos and goats but still heads on grasses and Atriplex stipitata are still intact. Introduced plant effect is low at present as forbs have dried out. Medicago minima, Salvia verbenaca and Centaurea melitensis present but cover low. Most cover still extant is native. Long unburnt- no cover to carry fire. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. 200m back to old Glen lea access track ( rarely used)
visit_notes: Annual forb is Einadia nutans
location_description: Yathong Nature Reserve, approx 2km south of old Glenlea homestead. Aprox 50km north north west of Hillston

description: Naree Reserve, 7.3km south west of Ranger station. 130km north west of Burke
comments: Plot sits on broad, flat plain. Sandy at the surface but clay below the surface. Minimal surface strew- litter- broken twigs etc from goats. Lots of cryptogam crust. Long unburnt- minimal ground cover and shrubs well-spaced to carry fire. Introduced plant species effect is low at present- most grasses and annual are dry. Silene sp. possibly present. Homogeneity- 20m beyond plot is the same community. difficult to tell how far community extends beyond this due to thickness of vegetation. North west corner is 30m in from Burke/Hungerford road which runs slightly south west away from the north west corner.
location_description: Narree Reserve, 7.3km south west of Ranger station. 130km north west of Burke

description: Naree Reserve, 2.5km south west of homestead. 141km north west of Burke
comments: Flat plot on broad plain. Minimal surface strew. Sandy at surface but hard underneath. Grazing effect is low- Goats and Kangaroos. In semi fenced enclosure but still roos present. Introduced plant effect is currently low- Medicago and other forbs may be present. Cenchrus ciliaris present but cover low at present. Plot hasn’t had whole sale clearing as at site NSAMUL0003. Long unburnt. Community is confined to the plot- extends slightly beyond plot but north eastern corner is 10m from track heading away in a south westerly direction.
location_description: Narree Reserve, 2.5km south west of homestead. 141km north west of Burke

description: Naree Reserve, 636m north of Homestead. 132km north west of Burke
comments: Linear drainage depression. Plot is broadly flat but has gently undulating ridges. Patchy at a subsite level. Eucalyptus populnea is on raised section, some pan sections that have more bare ground. Sandier sections have more of the Eremophila sturtii and Senna artemisioides subsp. petiolaris. Minimal surface strew. Lots of leaf litter under Eucalyptus populnea but largely bare in pan sections. Plot has not been cleared as at site NSAMUL0004. Introduced plant species effect is low. Grazing effect is low- kangaroos and goats. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- NE corner is 50m from powerline access track. Community is confined to the plot.
location_description: Naree Reserve, 636m north of Homestead. 132km north west of Burke

description: Naree Reserve, 2.6km north east of homestead
comments: Plot sits on broad plain. Plot has been cleared at least 3 times- initially by hand around the 1920’s then with a chain saw post WW2 and then with a bulldozer in the 70s or 80s. Hasn’t been burnt. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Grazing effect is moderate – goats and roos but minimal feed at time of visit due to lack of rain. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Sits in linear grove. South east corner is 15m from reserve access track.
location_description: Narree Reserve, 2.6km north east of homestead

description: Mount Kaputar National Park,35.8km east north east of Narrabri
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a Eucalyptus pauciflora, Eucalyptus viminalis and Eucalyptus laevopinea woodland, with a mid-story of young Eucalypts. The ground layer is made up of a variety of grasses, forbs and weedy  species including Geranium sp., Poa labillardierei, Hydrocotyle, Swainsona, White paper daisy and Long leaved lomandra. 
The sites land form and element hasn’t changed since the previous visit, still a hill slope and the element mountains. There is a volcanic plug to the South west of the site. There is a drainage line throughout the northern edge of the site and curves over towards the south west corner. 
The site was burnt in 2019 in a wildfire, so it has burnt since our previous visit. Some of the trees have been killed off completely, however many are shooting epicormic growth. A large part of the canopy is intact suggesting the fire was a low intensity. 
In terms of climate and response, there was a good summer rain so the site is very green. Recent rain in the past few days. The vegetation response is fruiting and flowering, including Erodium and paper daisies. The eucalypts are not fruiting or flowering. The grasses have seed heads. Less grass cover compared to the previous visit, with more forbs visible. Increased weedy species since last visit.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is long unburnt ~50years, no evidence of scarring on any of the Eucalyptus species. The site is only marked at the South West corner and centre point. Grazing impact is low, evidence of pigs and kangaroos through site. Distance from infrastructure, North East corner is 20m down the slope from the road and running away from the plot. Homogeneity is confined to plot. Complicated slope and aspect. Slopes down from the road into a slight ditch at the North West corner, but also curving over the slope at the South East corner and the North East corner is sloping down into a ditch. No discernible slope to site.
location_description: Mount Kaputar National Park,35.8km east north east of Narrabri

description: Mount Kaputar National Park. 35.8km east north east of Narrabri.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Previously burnt in a control burn (2016/17), but remains unburnt in the most recent fires. There are many more species in the regrowth, which were not collected the first time.
The physical description hasn’t changed.
The site is Eucalyptus pauciflora open woodland, with Eucalyptus viminalis scattered through the site. The mid-story is quite sparse with some regrowth of the Eucalypts and the Red-stemmed shrub, and the ground layer is very diverse with lots of forbs and Poa labillardierei.
The site is wet, there have been decent rains in the past few days so the soil is still damp. The vegetation response is fruiting and flowering. There are fruit on the Eucalyptus pauciflora, and many of the forbs are flowering, Lomandra has fruit and the Poa species have seed heads.
More introduced species recorded on this visit. There is Black thistle scattered throughout the site, as well as a few weedy forbs.
Grazing in the site is low, but evidence of kangaroos throughout the site.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
The landform element is a hill slope with a pattern of mountains. The plot has a slope to the south at 5 degrees even throughout the site. A lot of surface strew visible in the site due to fire burning off the grasses. A lot of basalt gravel and cobbles and some larger boulder possible shale or outcrop. VERY recently burnt, 8 weeks ago Feb 2018. Most of the upper canopy is still alive but most of the younger snow gum have died or have been scorched and are reshooting. The majority of the lower stratum has been burnt with some small patches of grasses unburnt. Minimal grazing impact by pigs and roos. Introduced plant species impact is low, some Scotch thistle is present but other introduced plants may have been burnt out. Community is confined to plot. 30m from Western edge of plot is track to Governors lookout where fire has stopped. Southeast corner is 15m in from the road moving away toward the southwest corner which is 40m away from the road to the south and east.
location_description: Mount Kaputar Nationwide Park, 35.8km east north east of Narrabri

description: as per last visit
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a hillslope on rises. Extensive granite outcrop and granite strew throughout the site. There is a drainage line running through the site from the southeast to the northeast, with a major creekline just to the northeast of the site.
 
Grazing impacts are low, with little impact from kangaroos.
 
Nearest infrastructure is Blatherarm Road, running parallel to the western boundary of the site approximately 170m to the west. The Blatherarm campground is 150m west northwest of the northwest corner.




-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Extensive granite sheets through site some with cryptogam and some large boulders and cobbles of granite. Evidence of historic mining. Long unburnt with evidence of previous fire i.e. dead burnt timber. Community is confined to plot. North East corner close to a creek with ferns and still has water running through it. There is a shallow drainage line that runs North West through the site. Introduced plant species minimal. Evidence of grazing minimal, pigs and kangaroos present. Distance to infrastructure North east is 20m in from the Blatherarm campground.
visit_notes:
For Basal South collection E. prava and stringbark not collected.
Also the two smooth barked Eucalypts grouped together and two stringbark Eucalypts grouped together.

	6762900
location_description: Torrington State Conservation Area, 23.4km north east of Emmaville

description:
Newholme Farm,  Mount Duval. 11.8km north north west of Armidale. 21.4km south south west of Guyra.
Marker point number 688352 for 200m grid plot of University of New England located 50m NW / 135° of SW corner.
comments: Landform element is a hillcrest and pattern is a mountain. Site is undulating but with a general slope toward NW at 2 degrees. Outcrop is present through the site as are boulders, with lithology of adamellite. Site long unburnt. No recorded fire at site. Grazing impact is minimal, some kangaroo and wallaby. Introduced plant impact is minimal, some Hypochaeris observed. Site is homogenous, the community extends beyond plot but contained to the summit of MT. Duvall. Nearest infrastructure is a fire track 10m from SW corner. Marker point number 688352 for 200m grid plot of University of New England located 50m NW of SW corner.
visit_notes: Bulk Density - 0.20 - 0.30m depth not collected.
location_description:
Mt Duval. 11.8km NNW, Armidale. 21.4km SSW, Guyra. Marker point number 688352 for 200m grid plot of University of New England located 50m NW / 135° of SW corner.
Surface strew throughout site (adamellite), organic top layer, Charcoal at 25-40cm.

description: Newholme Farm, Mount Duval. 2.2km west of Newholme Homstead. 13.6km north west of Armidale
comments: Landform element is a hillslope and pattern is a mountain. Site slopes in a WNW starting at a 2 degrees and steeping to 4/5degrees near Western edge. Outcrop is present through the site as are some boulders, with a lithology of adamellite. Introduced plant impact in minimal, some Hypochaeris sp. present. Grazing impact low-moderate, most likely from kangaroos. Site is homogenous and the community extends North, South, West 100m and transitions to a E. blakelyi woodland in the East. Nearest infrastructure is Mt Duval Fire Track 15m East of SE corner. Site is long unburnt; no records of site being burnt. There are some evidence of past fire by NW corner, with an old E. laevopinea with fire scars and a dead tree with fire scars.
visit_notes:

EW4 pt 5,7,59,60,81 cryptogram on rock. Pt 65,75 cryptogram on outcrop.
WE5 pt 30,60 cryptogram on outcrop.

Tree trunk is unknown at pt 40.

description: Newholme Farm. 11.6km north north west of Armidale. 12.6km south south west of Guyra.
comments: Landform element is a hillslope and pattern is a hill. Site slopes 4 degrees to southeast toward creek. Outcrop and boulders are present through the site, with lithology of adamellite. Large boulders are covered in lichen. Community confined to plot as Bursaria starts to thicken up along the southern edge. Some clearing suspected. Nearest infrastructure is fence on other side of creek, 15m from southern edge. Site corresponds to location of wet acoustic recorder (University of New England).
visit_notes: only true Eucalyptus blakelyi on SN1 and WE1. All other blakelyi entered as shaggy eucalyptus
location_description: Plot is near acoustic monitoring site (University of New England).  Damarseq Dam is 1.3km to the southwest of the plot. 11.6km NNW, Armidale. 12.6km SSW, Guyra

description: Goobang National Park, 45.9km north north east of Parkes
comments: Plot sits in a broad valley/ Drainage depression between ranges. To the west is low rise.  Gentle slope to the south 2 degrees. Creek through the site- quite deep in places ( 2-3m deep in water holes) Rest of the site is floodplain of creek- no real change in vegetation along the creek. Some sandstone cobbles in the creek channel. Long unburnt- some trees show evidence of fire but no scarring on trunks. Grazing is only from Kangaroos. Younger Eucalyptus on east of the site and west outside of the site have leaf die off- probably because of the dry.  Most of the older Eucalypts seem ok. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Park access track running north to south 10m west of the plot.
location_description: Goobang National Park, 45.9km north north east of Parkes

description: Goobang National Park, 36.2km north east of Parkes
comments: Aspect 2 degrees to South. Steeper through the middle of site on a river terrace. South east corner is at the high bank of the creek moving further away towards the southwest corner out of the site. Surface strew not apparent but just under the surface sandstone and alluvial wash. Long unburnt, no evidence of fire. Evidence of past logging cut with possibly saw or axe. Grazing mostly Kangaroos, low impact. Minimal introduced species but potentially annual weedy species may occur. Vegetation community confined to the plot.
visit_notes:
Point intercept S1-N1 transect 11 Unknown = Cryptogam on rock
In Basal wedge Callitris endlicheri was lumped with Callitris glaucophylla.
location_description: Goobang National Park, 36.2km north east of Parkes

description: 24km east north east of Capertee. 45km north east of Lithgow. April Mills Place.
comments: Hillslope/Talus on the western side of the Blue Mountains. Plot sits below the sharp rise up to the main escarpment and above the floor of Capertee Valley. Mix of cobbles and gravels with some larger boulders and some low sandstone outcrops. Average of an 8 degree slope to the north west . A Creek line runs along the northern boundary and a shallower drainage line runs through the centre of the plot in the direction of the slope. Grazing effect is high- anecdotal evidence of goats from landowner as well as Macropods. Introduced plant species effect is low- some Opuntia but more concentrated further down the slope outside the site. Also possibly some grass species but cover is quite low. Fire- long unburnt. No scarring on Callitris or any of the other trees. Homogeneity- eastern edge fronts on to steeper terrain and the northern edge borders a creek line with corresponding changes in vegetation.
location_description: April Mills Place. 24km east north east of Capertee. 45km north east of Lithgow

description: Ku-Ring-Gai Chase National Park, 1.4km north east of entrance gate. 22.6km north north west of Sydney
comments: Plot is on  hill slope close to the crest among low hills.  Some sandstone surface strew- mostly cobbles as well as some outcrop at the south eastern corner. Plot has been burnt within last 5 to ten years- scorch marks on trees and dense regeneration. Grazing effect is minimal- kangaroos.  Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- vegetation community is more or less confined to the plot as the south west corner borders on a line cleared for powerlines. Eastern edge also borders walking track.
visit_notes: Transects S5-N5 and N4-S4 need numbers swapped
location_description: Ku-Ring-Gai Chase National Park, 1.4km north east of entrance gate. 22.6km north north west of Sydney

description: Bowen Mountain, Blue Mountains National Park
comments: Western edge of the site is on a ridge with the slope increasing eastwards through the plot. 3 degrees slope- steeper towards the bottom of the plot going down off the ridge. Some gravel- more where the track comes through. Some sandstone outcrops. Minimal grazing. Has been burnt- scarring even on younger trees to moderate height. Introduced plant species effect is low- some weedy grasses on edge of track. Homogeneity- track runs south to north from the 10m mark on the southern edge veering north west and existing the plot at the 90m mark on the western boundary. Vegetation community is contained because of this. Minimal impact of introduced plant species - Hypochaeris radicata present.
visit_notes:
Eucalyptus piperita and Eucalyptus consideniana
combined in basal wedge.
Metagenomics for Subsite 4 Barcode: AUG007254 was accessed 3/10/2023 for sampling - bag was mouldy
location_description: Bowen Mountain, Blue Mountains National Park

description: Patterson Range Fire Trail, Blue mountains National Park. 4.8km south east of Bilpin.70.5km north west of Sydney
comments: Plot on sandstone ridge. Flat towards the south west corner but slope increasing down to the north east corner where it drops off a small escarpment. Some gravels and exposed ground as well as some sandstone outcrop. Grazing effect is minimal. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Southern edge of the plot close to turn around bay has had some disturbance in the past- possibly scarped for gravel for the carpark. A very old overgrown track runs norther to south at the 30m mark.  10+ years since last fire- old Scarring on trees. Site also selectively logged in the past- some very old cut stumps. Homogeneity- south west corner is close to track. Plot is homogeneous but difficult to tell how far vegetation community extends beyond plot due to thickness of vegetation
location_description: Patterson Range Fire Trail, Blue Mountains National Park. 4.8km south east of Bilpin.70.5km north west of Sydney

description: Lawson, Blue Mountains National Park. 2.8km north east of Lawson. 13.5km east north east of Katoomba
comments: Sloping plot on northern edge of ridge. 5 degree slope to the north east. Some disturbance in the site- evidence of an old campsite with rubbish. Minimal surface strew- lots of leaf litter. Fire in last 10+ years- lots of regrowth in understory- more severe down to northern edge of plot with scorch marks on trees. Grazing effect is minimal- main disturbance is human.  Homogeneity- vegetation community is contained to the plot. South east corner is on edge of track and north edge borders on edge of drop off into creek line.
location_description: Lawson, Blue Mountains National Park. 2.8km north east of Lawson. 13.5km east north east of Katoomba.

description: Evans Lookout, Blue Mountains National Park, 3.5km south east of Blackheath. 7.3km north of Katoomba
comments: Evans lookout. 6 degree slope to the north west but steeper to the south east corner. High scorch marks on Eucalyptus sieberi? but none on snow gums. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Some sandstone cobbles, also some conglomerate. Homogeneity-  south east corner borders a track. Difficult to tell extent of community beyond the plot due to thickness of vegetation.
location_description: Evans Lookout, Blue Mountains National Park 3.5km south east of Blackheath. 7.3km north of Katoomba

description: Wollemi National Park,  4.5km south west of Galah Mountain. 20.6 km north east of Lithgow
comments: Plot is on a very gentle slope on the top of the Newnes Plateau. 2 degree slope to the east. Minimal surface strew- some small pockets of gravel and the odd large cobble. No outcrop. Minimal disturbance, no formal grazing. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Fire within last 10 years- scarring on most of the older trees but not on younger co-hort. Homogeneity- north eastern corner is 15m in from a track but vegetation community is consistent at least 100m from plot centre.
location_description: Wollemi National Park,  4.5km south west of Galah Mountain. 20.6 km north east of Lithgow

description: Newnes State Forest. 10.9km north east of Wallerawang. 16.8 km north of Lithgow. Plot is 400m from original BATS plot due to precipitous nature of that site.
comments: Plot is on a flat plain, part of a larger plateau with a 1 degree slope to the north west.  Minimal surface strew, a few sandstone cobbles. Lots of leaf litter. Very long unburnt, no scarring on any trees with the exception of a couple of the very old trees in the plot. Some regrowth in trees recovering from drought? Some evidence of trees having been cut in the site but very old. Grazing effect is minimal- not formally grazed. Some evidence of wombats. Homogeneity- 20m south of the site is track running parallel to the site. 100m from centre is within the same vegetation community. Plot is 400m from original BATS plot due to precipitous nature of that site.
location_description: Newnes State Forest. 10.9km north east of Wallerawang. 16.8 km north of Lithgow

description: Gardens of Stone National Park, 21.1km north north west of Wallerawang. 31.3km north west of Lithgow
comments: Hill slope among ranges of hills. 9 degree slope through the site at approx. 155 degrees.  Getting steeper up towards the north east corner. Gully running down to the south east corner ( with dominant slope). Flattening out towards south east corner. Some gravels and cobbles- sandstone. Some very slow sandstone outcropping to .5m  on very northern edge of the plot. Some sheeting/outcrop where gully  flows through the plot. Most of the outcrop is covered by Cryptogam so will not show up in point intercept. Fire- very long unburnt. Some of the box bark Eucs have some shallow scarring on the base. Many of the trees have been cut for timber ( very old) and most have coppiced from this. Burnt since the trees were cut. No formal grazing but evidence of Kangaroos and Wombats- scats through the site but no burrows. Introduced plant effect is low, present but low cover. Homogeneity- community continues up the slope. 90m from centre of the plot is the same vegetation community. Very faint old track along southern edge of the plot. South west corner is 250m in from Castlereagh highway. Corresponds to BATS Ben Bullen plot ( new site)  but not exactly where originally selected due to access difficulties.
visit_notes: Smooth trunk Eucalypt and Scribbly gum combined for basal area. Stringy bark and box bark combined for Basal area
location_description: Gardens of Stone National Park, 21.1km north north west of Wallerawang. 31.3km north west of Lithgow

description: Mt Banks, Blue Mountains National Park. 11.3km south east of Bell. 15.7km north north east of Katoomba
comments: Plot is on a hillslope with a 15 degree slope to the north west. Cobbles and gravel of sandstone origin with some quartzite. Lots of bare ground in places. Burnt in previous 2 years and prior to that within 10 years ( communication with rangers). Grazing effect is low- some macropods. Homogeneity- south east corner borders Mt Banks walking track about 15m down slope from the track. The south west corner is approx. 20m from picnic area carpark. Northern edge is a shallow creek line/gully. Introduced plant species effect is low.
location_description: Mt Banks, Blue Mountains National Park. 11.3km south east of Bell. 15.7km north north east of Katoomba

description: Kakadu National Park, 37km west of Gimbit homestead.  56.5km north east of Pine Creek
comments: Flat plot on a sandplain. Sandy- very little gravel and lots of leaf litter. Grazing effect is minimal.  Not burnt in current dry season- older scarring on E. tetrodonta and a dense layer of Sorghum plumosum?  through the ground layer. Recent fire between the south east corner of the plot and the road but not burnt into plot. Introduced species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community extends 20m beyond plot. Highway is 90m from south east corner.
visit_notes:
numbers on transects east to west4 and west to east 1 need swapping 
Note: There are restrictions on using plant,soil and metagenomic samples collected at this site. Please contact ben.sparrow@adelaide.edu.au
location_description: Kakadu National Park, 37km west of Gimbit homestead.  56.5km north east of Pine Creek

description: Kakadu National Park, 34.5km west of Gimbit homestead. 58.5km north east of Pine Creek
comments: Sandy site with a very gentle slope to the east. Minimal surface strew- sandy with lots of leaf litter. Unburnt in current dry season. At the eastern edge is evidence of a more recent fire but doesn’t come into plot. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Grazing effect is minimal- possible camel footprint in the site also horse scats and tracks. Homogeneity- community extends 95m from centre of plot.  Southern boundary is 50m from unpaved road which runs parallel to the site.
visit_notes: Note: There are restrictions on using plant,soil and metagenomic samples collected at this site. Please contact ben.sparrow@adelaide.edu.au
location_description: Kakadu National Park, 34.5km west of Gimbat homestead. 58.5km north east of Pine Creek.

description: Kakadu National park.  18km west north west of Gimbit homestead. 75km north east of pine Creek.
comments: Gentle slope through the site, plot is on a spur at the base of low hills. 3 degrees slope coming down from the range of hills at the south west corner. Slopes to both the north east and north west. Some very small outcrops of mixed sandstone and quartz. Gravels through the site are the same lithology as outcrop.   Recent low intensity fire through the site- patchy through the site with sections unburnt. Scorch marks not very high up the trees with branches largely unburnt. Grazing effect- horses present close to site ( recent cull) but minimal feed at visit due to fire. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community is contained to the  plot with the south east corner working up towards a rise and the western edge of the site to a low escarpment. Originally selected plot was moved slightly due to impenetrable terrain. South east corner is approx. 20m from park access track.
visit_notes:
Note: There are restrictions on using plant,soil and metagenomic samples collected at this site. Please contact ben.sparrow@adelaide.edu.au
Corymbia dichromophloia and  Corymbia setosa combined for basal wedge as are Eucalyptus miniata and Eucalyptus tetrodonta
location_description: Kakadu National park.  18km west north west of Gimbat homestead. 75km north east of pine Creek.

description: Pine Hill Station. 25km South East of Ti-Tree. Approximately 2.9km. west south west of flux tower.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a sandplain with no surface strew or outcrop. The vegetation community is a homogenous Corymbia opaca woodland that extends at least 100m in all directions. To the north and east the vegetation community transitions to mulga woodland but the Corymbia woodland continues another 200m to the south and west. The nearest infrastructure is a dirt road about 700m to the north. The site was burnt in October 2017 with approximately half of the site burnt on a diagonal from the north-west to the south east corner, although this scar is less pronounced now. The impact of grazing and introduced weeds is minimal.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Burnt 1+ years. Rainfall 2 weeks previous. Very flat sandplain over large area. Grazing minimal. Weeds minimal.
location_description: Pine Hill Station. 25km South East of TiTree.

description: Pine Hill Station. 25km South East of Ti-Tree. 2.7km west south west of flux tower
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a sandplain on a plain with no outcrop or surface strew apparent. The site is homogenous and continues about 30m to the west, 50m to the south and east and at least 200m to the north. The site is relatively long unburnt with no evidence of past fire. The area has been experiencing drought conditions which has resulted in the mass dieback of the acacias recorded here. The impact of introduced plant species is moderate with Cleome visosa abundant throughout the site. The impact of grazing is low with only old cow pats present.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Plain. No evidence of fire, but areas close by burnt within previous 3-4 years.  Lots of Mulga ant nests with echidnas but more likely goannas digging into mounds. No evidence of grazing. Weed impact low- some patches of Cenchrus ciliaris
location_description: Pine Hill Station. 25km South East of TiTree.

description: Pine Hill Station, 150m south-south east of flux tower. 28.8km south east of Ti-Tree.
comments: The site is a plain on a plain with no outcrop or surface strew apparent. The vegetation community is homogenous and confined to the plot, that is, it extends 75m from the centre of the plot. However, the community extends at least 400m from the south east corner to the south east. To the north east the community is mulga woodlands. The nearest infrastructure is the Ti-Tree East TERN Processes Flux Tower and the turnaround track is about 10m north of the north-east corner. The site is long unburnt (last burnt in early 2001) with no evidence of fire visible. The spinifex die-off is related to drought conditions. There is no evidence of grazing and the impact of introduced plants is minimal.
location_description: Pine Hill Station, 150m south-south east of flux tower. 28.8km south east of Ti-Tree

description: Stirling  Station, 37.8km south west of homestead. 25km north north west of Ti-tree.
comments: The site is a hill-crest on a mountain comprised of quartzite and quartzite-sandstone. Quite a lot of outcrop and pebble sized surface strew. Site slopes to the West and East, especially the SW corner (about 7 degrees). Average slope of 5 degrees to the East, more so the further East you are within the site. No evidence of invasive species or grazing. Site burned in patches 1-2 years ago, more at the Eastern (30m in) and Western (10-20m in) edges of site. Upper canopy is intact but the lower shrubs are more burnt. Nearest infrastructure is the access track about 4.5km NNW.
visit_notes:
EW1 point 24 unknown substrate
NS2 point 64 missing data
location_description: Stirling  Station, 37.8km south west of homestead. 25km north north west of Ti-tree

description: Litchfield National Park. 30km south west of Bachelor. 77.5km south south west of Darwin.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Plain on a plain. No slope or aspect. No outcrop or surface strew. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Stable flat soil surface across site with little bare soil.  Site is on broad, slightly elevated, plain, extending to the west, but to the east has gentle slope north east. Tree bark charred and charcoal on ground- surrounding areas also with burns of differing age. Site resembles vegetation/physical elements of local community south of Litchfield park road. description: Road Reserve,  56km north east of Tennent Creek
comments: Road reserve, 100m north of Barkly Hwy. ~51.2km NE of Tennant Creek, ~47.6km ESE Phillip Creek Homestead. Landform element is a plain, pattern is a sandplain. Site is flat. description: Road Reserve, 8km north north west of Tennent Creek. 235 south south east Elliott
comments: Site burnt relatively recently, within the last 5 years. There is more mature spinifex outside of the plot. Lots of mixed surface strew consisting of ironstone, quartzite and a few others deposited here. The landform is a plain and the element is a sandplain. slope and aspect 1 degree gentle slope to the south. Plot is not formally grazed as it is on the road reserve. Old cattle scat in site. Introduced plant species effect is nil. Homogeneity: Communbity is  confined to the plot, the south east corner becomes denser with Acacia. The closest infrastructure is a track 30m from the south west corner, and the Stuart highway is 60m to the south of the plot.

description: As previously
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
 

Site is a plain on a floodplain, with no discernible slope and aspect. No surface strew. Cenchrus ciliaris is the only introduced plant species observed, which has low to moderate cover. Evidence of grazing on Cenchrus ciliaris and other grass species. No evidence of past fire. Site is not homogenous, with more dense vegetation coverage in the southern one-third of the plot where there are deeper drainage gullies. The northern two-thirds are very open with less overstorey. The denser vegetation extends 90m from the boundary to the north and south of the plot, while the sparse open areas extend 150m west from the centre and 100m east from the centre of the plot. Nearest infrastructure is a station track 180m north of the northeast corner.

 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
About 40mm of rain in previous 4-5 days. Damp underneath. No recent fire. Mix of Eucalyptus coolabah with diverse understorey.  Cattle pads in site but not heavily grazed. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.
location_description: Soil pit in SW corner. Extremely hard layer at 55cm. Pit to 80cm. Auger to 1m. 5 km North of Henbury Meteorite Crater Reserve.  115 km South of Alice Springs

description: as previous visit
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Introduced plant impact is low, with a small amount of Cenchrus ciliaris observed at the southern end of the site. Grazing impact is high due to the close proximity of the stock watering point. All Maireanas have been modified by grazing, as has Atalaya hemiglauca and Ptilotus obovatus. Numerous tussock grasses present, but all are very small and grazed closed to the ground, making identification very uncertain. There are numerous stock pads running through the site, with frequent prints and dung away from the pads. Fire history – no evidence of past fire.

The site is homogenous but is mainly confined to the plot. Vegetation changes with slope to the north (samphire transitioning to Senna and Eremophila) and south; to the east there is more senna, and to the west it continues for up to 400m but is more impacted by grazing. Nearest infrastructure is a fenceline access track 90m northeast of the NE corner. The stock watering point is located 400m WNW of the NW corner. The Stuart Highway is 1.1km NW of the NW corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Cattle removed- regeneration in grasses. No recent fire. Rains 9 days ago- 30-40m. Minimal presence of introduced plant species.
