North East corner of the site abuts main Calvert hills road. Old cut line/track through northern boundary of the site which has reclaimed by Acacia shirleyi. Weed impact nil. 2+ months since previous rain. Homogeneity- South eastern boundary borders on a more dense Acacia shirleyi thicket with Triodia pungens dominating the hill crest above this.   Community continues 100m to the west, 20m on other side of road to the north and 50m to east.
location_description: Soil pit in NE corner and subsites 1 - 5 in SE corner. No soil subsite samples taken due to lack of soil throughout site. Some coarse fragments in A1 horizon consist of charcoal. A1 colour probably due to heavy traces of charcoal. Sandstone outcrops throughout site. Very little or no soil on slopes. Very little soil at bottom of site.

description: Calvert Hills Station. 16 km West South West of Calvert hills homestead.  160 km south east of Borroloola
comments: Flat, gravelly site at the base of a low range of hills.  Some small undulations and occasional larger stones. Homogeneity- the site extends  50m to south ( over road) and the same to the East. To the western edge is borrow pit for road. North of the site grades into a Terminalia sp. shrubland. Termites minimal. The site appears to have been burnt approximately 2 years previous- no fruit under Eucalyptus  and Corymbia would seem to indicate this. Grazing impact low- some pats but no pads. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Soil pit in SW corner. Soil pit taken from side of old scrape. Stopped by rock and gravel at 85cm.

description: McArthur River Station. 14km South East of McArthur River Homestead 5km West of Kilgour river. 80km South West of Borroloola
comments: Swamp on the edge of unnamed tributary of the Kilgour river. Weed impact low- some Stylosanthes hamata.  Grazing impact low. Some pads in the site. Long unburnt- no standing litter and no scorch marks on trees. Slight slope to the south east towards a small river 200m away. Homogeneity- Community continues 20m to the west. The south west corner borders a track and the community continues another 50m on the other side.  On eastern  and northern boundaries the community begins to grade into a Eucalyptus  pruinosa Mallee woodland
location_description: Soil pit in SW corner. Pit to 50cm, stopped by unconsolidated rock. McArthur River Station. 14km South East of McArthur River Homestead 5km West of Kilgour river. 80km South West of Borraloola

description: McArthur River Station. 14.5km South East of McArthur river homestead 5km West of Kilgour river.  80km South West of Borroloola
comments: Rocky site between two ranges. The main Abner range to the south and an unnamed range to the north.  Site slopes down to shallow creek on southern edge continues up the other side. A shallow drainage line runs more or less due east to west. Grazing impact low with one or two pads within site. Long unburnt- no scorch marks on Melaleuca stenostachya  and tussock grasses dense. A Recent  Fire on other side of track hasn’t crossed into the site. A drainage line runs through southern edge more or less west to east. Site continues up the slope on other side. Homogeneity- the community is more or less contained within the site. At the North East corner is a track. To the south the community grades into a Eucalyptus  leucophloia and  Triodia bitextura open Mallee woodland. Introduced plant species impact minimal- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.
visit_notes: One Bulk density (0.00-0.10m) taken.
location_description: Soil pit and subsites 1-5 in SE corner. Pit to 35cm. Stopped by unconsolidated rock. Exposed rock throughout site. Rill erosion throughout site. Small gully washes throughout site.

description: McArthur River Station. 14 km South East of McArthur River Homestead 5km West of Kilgour River. 80km South West of Borroloola
comments: Rocky site on a low rise. Site is almost convex with the high point where photo point is and sloping down on all 4 sides.  Homogeneity- community extends 50m to the West, 20m to the South.  To the east is a Eucalyptus Pruinosa sparse Mallee woodland. To the north the site borders a diversion track which bisects the line between the Eucalyptus leucophloia and Eucalyptus pruinosa communities. Weeds- Nil. Grazing impact low. 2+ years since last fire with no standing litter and scorch marks on Eucalyptus leucophloia . Somewhat  difficult to tell however with the absence of a  shrub layer but some recruitment in Eucalyptus leucophloia.
visit_notes: No bulk density collected, too rocky.
location_description: Soil pit in SW corner. Pit to 40cm. Stopped by rock. Sandstone outcrop throughout entire site. Little soil throughout site. McArthur River Station. 14 km South East of McArthur River Homestead 5km West of Kilgour River. 80km South West of Borraloola

description: McArthur River Station. 18.km South South West of McArthur River Homestead. Top of Abner Range. 95km South West of Borroloola
comments: Sandplain on the top of the Abner range. Access via  newly upgraded mining exploration track. Homogeneity- site extends 50m to the west, east and north. To the south the site borders a track with the community continuing another 50m across the track. Community likely extends beyond this but the thickness of the vegetation dictates a more conservative figure. Weeds impact nil. Grazing impact nil. Some pig tracks close to quadrat.  No evidence of fire within 3+ years. Scorch marks on Eucalyptus setosa but difficult to tell how old.
visit_notes:
No bulk density taken.
10/07/2024 Plot is inaccessible, track that was used in 2012 has not been maintained, advice from land manager (2024) is access to these sites on top of the range would only be by helicopter or by foot.
location_description: Soil pit in SW corner. Pit to 55cm. Stopped by unconsolidated rock. Rounded shot type gravel throughout pit. Not concretions or nodules. description: Limmen national park. 25km South South West of Ranger Station. Western Edge of Eastern creek, North of Dulurru waterhole. 100km west north west of Borroloola

To the west the community grades into a more open Grevillea striata shrubland and to east, beyond the site, it drops quickly into the main channel of the river. location_description: Soil pit and subsites 1 - 5 in SE corner. Pit to 35cm. Auger to 1.2m. Signs of pig activity (wallows) throughout plot. Upper west bank of river.

description: Limmen National Park. 12km South South East of Ranger Station. 99km north west of Borroloola
comments: Site is at base south west facing range. Creek running south east to south west just beyond the southern boundary of the site. Drainage line off road runs just through the northern edge of site. Grazing impact low though dead cow within the site. Fire- scorch marks on trees from 2-3 years previous. Dead Acacia hammondii in South West corner where fire has come in. Homogeneity Community continues  50m to west, 30m to the South and 20m North. To the East borders the road. Low impact of introduced plant species- Stylosanthes hamata low cover.
location_description: Soil pit in NE corner, too rocky in SW corner. Subsites 1-5 in SW corner. Pit to 40cm, auger to 70cm, stopped by rock. Drainage line running through Northern end of site.

description: Limmen National Park. 6km South East of Ranger Station. 700m West of Butterfly Spring. 102km north west of Borroloola

The north west corner is close to the track leading to Butterfly spring. Homogeneity- The community only extends to the west by another 20m (up to the track) To east the community is grading into a  eucalyptus miniata/leucophloia  woodland and to the South a Eucalyptus phoenicea sparse woodland. Grazing impact- low. No evidence of cattle. Burnt 1-2 years. Scorch marks on trees. Weed impact low- some Stylosanthes hamata present as trace cover
visit_notes: Minimal soil taken due to lack of soil on site.
location_description: Soil pit in NW corner, Subsites 1-5 in SW corner. Pit to 85cm, stopped by rock.

description: Limmen National Park 6km North West of Ranger Station. Edge of Catfish waterhole. 112km north west of Borroloola

Homogeneity- community continues another 50m to the north west and to the south east. Fire- 2+ years. location_description: Soil pit SW corner, pit to 30cm, stopped by unconsolidated rock. Limmen National Park 6km North West of Ranger Station. Edge of Catfish waterhole. 112km north west of Borraloola

description: Owen Springs Reserve. 55km south west of Alice Springs

description: Owen Springs Reserve. 55km south west of Alice Springs
comments: Site in main channel of Hugh river, north of Waterhouse Range. Long unburnt- no scarring on any trees + sparse ground cover. Some grasses grazed likely by kangaroos, overall effect low. description: Soudan Station. 83km West south west of Camooweal.
comments: Site is in broad drainage depression. Grazing effect is low at present- 2km from water point but no grazing since end of previous dry season. Introduced plant effect low- none noted. Fire- long unburnt with no scarring on trees and low ground cover to carry fire. End of the wet season.  Very little litter other than that from the Acacia georginae. Site is more or less flat. Sloping away slightly at the south west corner rising onto the Mitchell grass. Strew is mostly gravel not much larger than 50mm- mixed metamorphosed strew of sandstone, mudstone etc.

description: Soudan Station,  about 84kms west of Camooweal. Close to Six Mile Creek on western side, north of Barkly Highway.
comments: Site on gently sloping clay plain. Lots of gravel and bare ground. 2 degrees slope to the north east. Site is 100m south of an Acacia georginae community ( site NTAMGD0001). No introduced plants noted. Grazing effect is low-Cattle present but effect is minimal at present. Recent rain with most forbs and grasses fruiting and flowering. No woody vegetation. Fire history difficult to tell- none within last 2 years. Site is homogenous and sited >300 metres from wooded margins of Georgina River.

description: 3.9km north east of Newcastle Waters, 23.9km north west of Elliott
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Gently undulating rise, with ~2 degree easterly aspect. Reasonable amount of ferricrete surface strew and outcropping, with a cryptogrammic crust in places. Small number of rocks >10cm, with most gravel sized. Minimal introduced species and grazing impacts. Clear evidence of fire <10 years ago, with considerable regeneration and recruitment. Nearest infrastructure is the Stuart highway, 1km north of the Newcastle Waters turnoff. Southwest corner closest to
 the road (~130m east of the road). Site is broadly homogenous, with more Acacia monticola in the northern half, and more Senna venusta in the southern half. Community extends 75m from the centre of the plot 


-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Flat Plain with ironstone, exposed by fire in the northern part of the plot. Minimal outcrop. Fire history is patchy- southern section was burnt max 10 years ago. Northern section burnt more recently around 5-6 years. Scarring on Corymbia but no dead upper canopy. Recruitment in Grevillea sp. in the mid layer in the southern section. Grazing effect is minimal- presently not grazed. Introduced plant species effect is low- possibly some Stylosanthes.   60m from Stuart highway on western edge. Homogeneity- Vegetation community is confined to the plot.
location_description: Newcastle Waters Station, 3.8km north east of homestead. 24.5km north west of Elliot

description: 3.7km north west of Elliott, 20km south east of Newcastle Waters
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Site is a plain on a plain. 2% slope, W to E. No major outcrops or surface strew. Introduced plants include Cenchrus ciliaris, which are growing under trees. Grazing evidence minimal. Site is long unburnt, with no evidence of past fire. Site located 5km North of Elliott; between the Stuart Highway and the Elliott airstrip 




-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Flat site. Fire- burnt in last 5 years, dead shrubs and burnt litter on the ground. Grazing effect is low- Cattle have chewed Cenchrus ciliaris but not much else. Introduced plant species effect moderate- Cenchrus ciliaris consistently through the site. Homogeneity- south west corner is 10m from fence with graded line. Old track runs along western edge of site 5m beyond site 50m from Stuart highway. Community is homogenous to 105m from centre.
location_description: Newcastle Waters Station, 20km south east of homestead. 4.3km north west of Elliott

description: 16.6km south east of Newcastle Waters homestead,  12km north west of Elliott
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a plain, with a negligible slope. Introduced plant impact and grazing impacts are negligible. Site appears to have been burnt in the last couple of years, with substantial regrowth evident. The site is to the East of the Stuart Highway, and is located in a road reserve with a fence line along the eastern edge of the plot. The site is relatively homogenous, with the vegetation community extending in a linear strip N-S along the Stuart Highway. 



-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Flat site on a sandplain. Isolated ironstone gravels and occasional cobble. Fire- evidence of burnt grasses and scarring on the trees but grasses and shrubs have come back. Grazing effect is low. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- South west corner is just on the edge of clearing for powerlines and then  the highway is 20 beyond that. North east corner sits 5m from fence line/ station track.

description: Kakadu National Park, 338m south east of Bowali visitors centre. 1.4km west of Jabiru
comments: Plot is on a plain. Broadly flat- some minor digging ( earthworks) within the site especially at the north west corner. Some fine ironstone gravels, no outcrop. Plot is unburnt in current dry season except for a small patch at the north west corner where a fire has just trickled into the corner of the plot exposing the substrate. Homogeneity- north west corner is about 10m in from main highway, slightly further away at the south west corner.

description: Kakadu NP. 5.8 north north east of Jabiru. 5.9km north west of Jabiru Airport.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Minimal Context information collected on 1st visit. Introduced plant impact is minimal - Melinis repens present but very low cover.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is plain on plain. There is a gentle one degree slope to the west. Surface lithology of ironstone gravel scattered through the site (5-15mm) and no outcropping. The site has been burnt in the last 2 years, there is recent scarring on most trees and limited litter. Grazing impact is minimal, some trees have a fungus on them and some vines have insect damage. Buffalo and horses are known in the area but no evidence of them. Introduced plant impact is minimal. The site is largely homogenous, with a slight transition in the NW corner to a swampier, grassless area. The community extends from the centre 100m to West and East, 300m to the South and 200m to the North. Closest infrastructure is an access track 30m W of SW corner, currently closed.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------

description: Kakadu National Park, 11.3km north of Jabiru. 11.4km north west of Jabiru Airport.
comments: Landform element and pattern is plain on floodplain. Site has a gentle 2 degree slope to the South. No outcrop but a lot of surface strew of ironstone and quartzite less than 15mm in diameter. Introduced plant impact minimal. Grazing impact low but evidence of past pig rooting, macropod scat and buffalo are grazing in the area. Very recent burn in the past two days with some logs still smouldering. Site is homogenous, community extends 70m south to a drainage creek line and 200m to the north, 150m to the East and West. Nearest infrastructure is an access track 190m East of NE corner.

description: As Previous
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Site is on a dune crest on a longitudinal dune. The eastern side is most steep, with a slope of approximately 30 degrees, while the western side is less steep, with a slope of approximately 5 degrees. No surface strew or outcrop.

Introduced plant species impact is minimal. Grazing impact is minimal. Fire history – site was last burnt in 2011. Site is not entirely homogenous, as there is more canegrass on the eastern side of the dune and more Triodia on the western side of the dune. The tussock grass and forb layer is consistent throughout. The vegetation community is confined to the deeper sand of the dune and extends at least 200m northwest and southeast from the centre of the plot, but not east and west into the dune swale.

Nearest infrastructure is the Colson Track, running parallel to and approximately 35-65m from the eastern boundary.

description: as per previous
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is located on an alluvial plain, with a shallow drainage channel running through the middle from northwest to southeast. The site slopes towards the southeast by a degree or two.

Introduced plant species impact is minimal. Grazing impact is light, with old cattle dung and tracks still visible in the site. Astrebla pectinata, Sporobolus actinocladus and Tripogonella loliiformis tussocks have been modified. Fire history – no sign of previous fire. The site is not homogenous, with vegetation changing in association with the drainage line to support more sedge species and aquatic plants such as Marsilea. Sclerolaena bicornis is also growing more densely near the drainage line. The dominant vegetation community extends at least 100m from the centre of the plot in all directions. Nearest infrastructure is a fenceline 220m northeast of the NE corner. A vehicle access track is located 500m north of the NE corner.

 


-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Shallow rill running from north west to south east. Site otherwise flat.
 Long unburnt. Weed impact nil. Some cattle pads but grazing impact minimal. Evidence of long haired rat burrows. Closest Acacia peuce- single tree 50m north of quadrat

Grazing impact is low, evidence of scrub bulls in and around plot. Site is homogenous, extending 75m in all direction from centre (although community is quite extensive). 40m to the North of the site is a Telstra telephone exchange. Access track is 30 west of NW corner.
visit_notes:
SN1 pt 42 termite mound.
SN5 pt 46 termite mound.
NS4 pt 75 termite mound.
Basal area not recorded.
location_description: Singleton Station, 8.2km north - north west from Singleton Station homestead. 6.7km south of Wauchope

description: Singleton Station, 8.5km west of homestead. 119km south of Tenant Creek
comments: Flat plot on a sandplain. No surface strew.  At least 5-10 years since the last fire. There are a few old burnt tree stumps, but fairly strong regrowth with the Acacia spp. Introduced plant species effect is low-  there is a small amount of Cenchrus ciliaris mainly under the Corymbia. Grazing effect is low-  a few old cattle scats throughout the site. Homogeneity: The community continues for 75m from the centre of the plot. Plot close to corner of two tracks. There is a approximately 30m to the south and 25m to the east
location_description: Singleton Station, 8.5km west of homestead. 119km south of Tenant Creek

description: Singelton Station, 48.4km south west of homestead.  145km south south west of Tennent Creek
comments: Shallow dune slope on a sandplain. Slope and aspect is a 2 degree slope to the south west.  No surface strew or outcrop.  The site is relatively long unburnt-  at least 5 years. Grazing effect is minimal with a evidence of camels present. Introduced plant effect species is minimal- none recorded.  Homogeneity is 100m from centre in all directions. In terms of infrastructure, there is a very old fence and track approximately 60m to the South. ,
location_description: Singelton Station, 48.4km south west of homestead.  145km south south west of Tennent Creek

description: Singelton Station, 47.1km WSW Singleton Homestead. 39km south west of Wycliffe Well
comments: Dune slope in a dune field - 1 degree slope to the west. No outcrop or lithology present. Introduced plant impact is minimal - non recorded.  Grazing impact is low, camel seen near plot. Site recently burnt within last year. The majority of the vegetation was burnt except for the crowns of the Corymbia sphaerica. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 30m South of the south west corner. Plot is homogenous and community extends over 100m in all directions.
visit_notes: No basal collected
location_description: Singelton Station, 47.1km WSW Singleton Homestead. 39km south west of Wycliffe Well

description: Umbrawarra Conservation Park. 9 km north east of Jindare homestead, 23km south west of Pine Creek
comments: Grazing effect is low to minimal. Fire- some scars on Eucalyptus tetrodonta and Eucalyptus miniata. Check with Bushfires NT plot data (site is Co-located with Bushfires Leaf fall plot). No introduced species noted. Site slopes more steeply to SW corner averaging 3 degrees through the site and 5 degrees at south west corner where gully is forming. Surface strew is a mix of cobbles and boulders mostly sandstone but possibly also some granite. Climate: At the end of wet season but soil surface is quite dry. On a plateau above Daly River Basin which drops away to the west.
location_description: Umbrawarra conservation park. 9 km north east of Jindare homestead, 23km south west of Pine Creek.

description: Litchfield National Park. 27 km south west of Bachelor.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
No slope or aspect. No outcrop. Gravel present, either ironstone or quartz sandstone. Plain on a plateau. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
No surface strew apart from some ironstone gravel. Fire a few years ago with scorch marks 1/3 of the way up the trees. No introduced species noted. Grazing effect: nil. Homogeneous plot in a vegetation community that extends south, west and east for >200m from centre of plot and north to the adjoining road reserve.
location_description: Litchfield National Park. 27 km south west of Bachelor.

description: Powell Creek Station. 800m south west of Homestead. East of Lake Woods
comments: Small swamp/ Drainage depression. Adjacent to a creek and site goes partially onto levee of a creek ( 10%) other side is 10% on the slope of metamorphic hill. Rest of the site is alluvial. Seepage off the hill. Running water in the site. Long unburnt- 5+ years since fire. Introduced species effect low- some Cenchrus ciliaris close to creek on the levee. No surface strew and very little bare soil. Lots of leaf litter.  No surface strew. An old track cuts through northern part of site. Introduced plant species effect is low- Cenchrus ciliaris present.
visit_notes:
Notes on point intercept:
Surface water covered parts of the site. The following substrate records were covered with water:
Bare: 85 x points covered
Cryptogam: 1 x point covered with water
Litter: 5 x points covered with water
Gravel: 1 x point covered with water
location_description: Powel Creek station. 800m south west of Homestead. East of Lake woods

description: 4.4km West of Powell Creek Telegraph station
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Plain on a plain. Negligible slope. No surface outcropping. No signs of recent fire. Introduced plants include C. ciliata, and Achyranthes aspera which is restricted to underneath B. cunninghamii. Grazing is minimal, with C. ciliaris grazed most heavily. Evidence of cattle, with scat throughout the plot. Nearest infrastructure is Powell Creek telegraph station. The community is relatively homogenous, albeit patchy, with patches of Triodia pungens in the Northwest and Southeast corners. There is a creek line in close proximity to the southwest side of the plot
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------

Site is on a broad plain above heavy clays of the Mitchell grass downs. No grazing at present. Introduced species- ground layer dominated by Cenchrus ciliaris. Site burnt within 5 years-evidence of re-sprouting on canopy as well as burnt grass clumps.  Site is flat with only small contours for relief. Vegetation community continues 50m to the north and west and east. To the south borders the road and the community continues 50m beyond that. Site is sandy so no real surface strew.
location_description: Powell creek station. 4.5km west of Homestead. East of lake woods

description: Powell Creek station. 2.2km west of homestead. South East of Lake Woods
comments: Site is a flat sandplain with the sand in the soil at depth. Termite mounds prominent.. Fire- some scaring but 5+years since last fire. Introduced species effect moderate- Cenchrus ciliaris common through the site. Site has been grazed but no cattle at present. Trees to 8m. Grass layer to 50cms. No surface strew- lots of bare soil and cryptogam.
location_description: Powel Creek station. 2.2km west of homestead. South East of Lake Woods

description: Newcastle Waters station. 10.6km north north west of homestead, 67km south of Dunmarra roadhouse
comments: Grazing effect is low- no evidence of cattle. Probably heavily grazed at other times. Introduced species-some Stylosanthes but effect is low. Fire: long unburnt- no scaring on trees. Slope to the north west of about 1 degree down to Newcastle creek. Mix of metamorphosed rock sandstone gravel etc. likely washed down from surrounding hills. Homogeneity: North west corner is where water currently extends too. Site extends to the south 100m, east is edge of gas line track, 100m to the north and west.
visit_notes: Only 447 east west points ingested.
location_description: Newcastle Waters station. 10.6km north north west of homestead, 67km south of Dumarra roadhouse

description: Manton Dam Conservation Reserve. 22km north east of Bachelor, 56km south east of Darwin
comments: Low hills surrounding Manton dam. Roughly 5 degree slope to the south east. Gets steeper to the south east corner where it dips into a gully. Subsurface damp. Recent fire possibly in last dry season. Check with Bushfires NT plot data (site is Co-located with Bushfires Leaf fall plot) Introduced species- none noted. Grazing effect: nil. Strew is mostly gravels with some boulders at south west corner probably granite- check soil sheet. Smaller strew is a mix of quartz and mudstone likely washed in from hill above site.
location_description: Manton dam conservation reserve. 22km north east of Bachelor, 56km south east of Darwin

description: Hayfield Station. 27km north west of homestead, 15 km north west of Dunmarra roadhouse
comments: Termites mounds prominent. No surface strew or lithology.
location_description: Lots of dead wood. No sign of recent fire -5+ years. No introduced plant species noted. Grazing effect- minimal. Recent rain with soil very damp.

description: Goonderoo Reserve, 1.7km east of homestead. 15km. South of Gindie Gindie, 29.2km north north east of Springsure.
comments: Landform element is plain, landform pattern is a sandplain. Very sandy minimal surface strew. No outcrop. Gentle 2 degree slope to South. Site is long unburnt. Previous selective logging, currently a lot of fallen logs. Grazing impact is low. Introduced species is low, Cenchrus ciliaris present. Community is confined to plot. The SE corner is 10-15 in from the track. Northern edge 30m in from the track to the north. Grading of the track has created some disturbance, pushing fallen debris towards the site.

Soil pit in SE corner
WE2 Termite mounds pt 9,18.
WE3 Termite mounds pt 30.
WE5 Termite mounds pt 61,62.

description: Carnarvon Station Reserve, 11.5km ssw of homestead. 151km north east of Augathella
comments: Burnt in December 2017. It has been previously cropped with sunflowers and other crops, but has regenerated with native grasses. A lot more bare ground compared to the QDABBS0001 grassland. Site is flat, no discernible slope. No outcrop or surface strew apparent. Site is 500m from a windmill with a dam, unsure if still in use. Grazing impact is low, no formal grazing, but stray cattle from neighbouring property have grazed in the site. Site sits in an extensive grassland plain, extending East 700m, South 200m to base of a rise, West 1km, North 700m. Nearest infrastructure, old pipe line track (overgrown) 80m from SE.

description: Carnarvon Station Reserve, 4.7 north north east of homestead. 93km south west of Rolleston.
comments: Landform element and pattern is a plain in hills. Site slope is relatively flat along the southern edge with gradual 5 degree slope to the NNW. No outcrop apparent. Surface strew present, pebble to cobble size; mostly basal in the south-western end of plot and ironstone/sandstone in the north-eastern end. Homogeneity is confined to plot. Site burnt within last 2-3 years. Nearest infrastructure is vehicle track 60m South of SE corner.

description: Abattoir Reserve, north of Dalby Gun Club. 4.3km north west of Dalby.
comments: Site is located on Crown Land 4.3 km north west of Dalby that was set aside for a town abattoir that was never built.  Site doesn’t seem to have been previously cleared. There is evidence of the odd tree cutting and fallen debris. Introduced plant species is low, Opuntia stricta is present. Site is long unburnt, no scarring on Eucalyptus populnea. The neighbouring property does put cattle in the reserve sometimes. There is a hot wire along part of the boundary, presumably to keep cattle in. No surface strew or outcrop. Cenozoic sediments. A narrow quad bike track runs NW to SE just inside the NE corner.
location_description: Abattoir Reserve, north of Dalby Gun Club. 4.3km north west of Dalby

description: Saint Ruth Reserve,  16.4km South of Dalby.  7.2km north north west of Tipton
comments: Saint Ruth conservation area. Site on a plain. Slope and aspect- flat with no slope. No surface strew. Grazing- low, some evidence of kangaroo and wallaby. Introduced species impact- moderate with Pear trees throughout. Site recently burnt, controlled burn previous few years. Closest infrastructure- track 30m south of SW corner. Homogeneity- community extends 150m north from the centre of plot. It extends 30m from western edge of plot where it hits the track but continues another 300m beyond that. Some evidence of selected logging throughout site.
visit_notes: Basal- Eucalyptus half bark actually angophora
location_description:
Dalby, 16.4km South
Tipton, 7.2km NNW

description: St Ruth Reserve, 16.6km south 350m south south west of reserve entrance gate. 16.6km south of Dalby
comments: Site is flat, the general slope of the landscape is SW towards Condamine River. Some corn husks, cotton and Sorghum has washed into site from neighbouring farmland. Landform element drainage pattern. No surface strew or lithology. This site has been burnt 3 times by the local council to control Lippia sp. Grazing impact is low, some kangaroos present. Introduced species impact moderate, Opuntia tomentosa and O.aurantiaca , Urochloa panicoides and Phyla canescens. Plot is homogenous, community extends 150m North, 100m West, 100m South, 60m East into denser E. populnea with farmland  90m to East.

description: Myall Park Private Reserve. 11.km WWN of Oakey, 2.7km. SE of Jondaryan.
comments: Surface strew and lithology, none apparent. Site is flat, no slope. Introduced weed impact moderate, Bryophyllum x houghtonii, Sonchus sp., Opuntia spp.. Site is homogenous, community extend 100m East, 70m North. Nearest infrastructure is Jondaryan-Mount Tyson Rd, 60m W from SW corner. Site is long unburnt. There has been selective logging in site, not for some time though.
visit_notes: In basal area observations, Geijera and Alectryon are grouped with Pittosporum.

description: Irongate conservation park. 12.9 km north west of Pittsworth, 58.6 km south east of Dalby.
comments: Landform element and pattern is a hillslope on rises. Slope is gentle, approx. 2 degrees to the south west. No outcrop. Minimal surface strew, very sparse basaltic cobbles present. Site is very long unburnt, with no evidence of scarring on trees. Very old wood cutting seen on southern edge and in north of site, but not common. Remaining stumps are almost rotten. Some suckering of Brigalow along the north west corner, likely as a result of past clearance. Some die-off Casuarina cristata, likely due to drought, and crowns of many trees have died back. Less crown die back in Brigalow. Minimal grazing effect, some potential pig sign observed in a small area.  Malvastrum americanum var. stellatum  is common in the site, and there are several other weed species,- Bryophyllum delagoense, Opuntia tomentosa, Opuntia tomentosa, Megathyrsus maximus var. pubiglumis also present in the ground storey. Lycium ferocissimum also present. Dead prickly pear scattered throughout looks to have undergone control treatments. Need to check with Pittsworth Group what works have been done on site (flagging tape and pickets are common). Community is confined to the plot. To the east of the plot is more softwood and less Brigalow. The NW corner is approximately 15m in from the reserve boundary, which is the nearest infrastructure.
visit_notes:
set up in north west corner

basal wedge: in book is "exocarpa" at 5/9 points. Entered as N. broombush/ E. two spine leafless shrub'. In book is "glandy leaf/soft" entered as 'velvet leaved shrub'.

point intercept: SN5, 80m: unknown substrate is ant nest
location_description: Irongate Conservation Park. 12.9 km NW of pittsworth, 58.6 km SE of Dalby.

description: Lochern National Park, 125km SW of Longreach . Site on top of existing QPWS monitoring site

location_description: 125km SW of Longreach on Lochern National Park. Site on top of existing QPWS monitoring site.

description: Noonbah Station, 133km south west of Longreach
comments: Shallow drainage line from eastern boundary to southern edge. At South westerly angle. Weed impact minimal. Long unburnt. Lots of coarse woody debris- Acacia cambagei that have fallen over but no scarring on tree or shrubs. Grazing impact low.-Paddock destocked. Very dry. To the west of the site 400m away is low hill. More low hills to the north of the site/ low rise.

description: Diamantina Lakes National Park. 16km north west of homestead. 165km south east of Boulia.
comments: On outer reaches of Diamantina River floodout. Recent rain 1 month previous, soil damp but little vegetation response. To the east of site is main channel 700m away to south is smaller channel/Anna branch. rises to east to low levee before dropping to main channel. Grazing effect low- Evidence of Kangaroos and some cattle. Introduced species impact minimal. Fire- long unburnt by age of Chenopodium and lack of scarring on surrounding trees.

description: Hope Vale, 15.3 km east north east of Hope Vale Community. 21.3 north of Cooktown
comments: Neofabricia myrtifolia and Jacksonia thesioides mixed heathland on a dune slope. No surface strew or lithology. Deep sand. Landform element is a dune slope in the pattern of an irregular dune field. The dunes are almost parabolic at times but generally not too linear. Dunes are very well vegetated. Slope is 10 degrees to the south. Site is long unburnt, a few scattered dead shrub but no real evidence of past fire. Minimal grazing impact. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Homogeneity is 80m from centre. The road is >30m from south west corner which mark the edge of the heathland.
location_description: Hope Vale, 15.3 km east north east of Hope Vale Community. 21.3 km north of Cooktown

description: 8.7km East South East of Hope Vale Community. 21.5km North North West of Cooktown.
comments: Landform element is a swamp with a pattern of alluvial plain. Site is predominately flat with a few drainage lines and water holes through it. Soil is very clayey with no surface strew or lithology. Evidence of previous fire (scaring on bottoms of Melaleuca trunks), likely 2-3 years ago. A lot of regeneration, but not in this dry season. No evidence of grazing or grazing animals. Homogeneity- Site sits on an extensive wood/shrubland of Melaleuca viridiflora although some areas have been burnt more recently than others.
location_description:
8.7km East South East of Hope Vale, 
 21.5km North North West of Cooktown.

description: Hope Vale, 18.9km east north east of Hope Vale Community. 21.8km north north east of Cooktown.
comments: Site is in a swale. NE corner rises up into a dune but does not intersect any other transects. There is a creek channel that runs roughly south easterly through the site. The slope is a 2 degrees in a south easterly direction. Some scattered sandstone gravel is present through the middle of the plot. Along the channel is a very thin banned of riparian vegetation. Two isolated pockets of Eucalypts one is the south eastern corner and along the eastern boundary with a more extensive patch occurring just past the south west corner.The community is confined to the plot.
location_description: Hope Vale, 18.9km east north east of Hope Vale Community. 21.8km north north east of Cooktown.

description: Crystalvale Station, Cape York Peninsula.Eucalyptus tetradonta Woodland
comments: Slope and aspect- 2 degree slope to south west. Homogeneity- community extends 75m from centre of plot. Distance to infrastructure- SE corner 40m in from access track to Crystal Vale station. Fire- scarring on trees. Possibly burnt early last dry season. Introduced species effect- high, dominated by Hyptis suaveolens. Grazing- presently low. Cattle on property but doesn’t appear to be many through site. No surface strew or outcrop. Some low termite mounds to maximum of 1m. Holroyd River, Yarraden & Crystalvale are an aggregation of leasehold grazing stations managed by Corporate Carbon as part of Savanna Fire Management project.
visit_notes: No data for EW 2 points 46-48 and NS3 points 98-100
location_description: Eucalyptus tetradonta Woodland

description: Crystalvale Station, 7.5km south south west of homestead. 32.5km South West of Coen

Homogeneity, 75m from centre is same community. Evidence of past fire, likely 1-2 years ago. Low impact of grazing although there is a cattle pad running through the north eastern corner. Introduced plants impact is low with some small patches of Mesosphaerum suaveolens in south west and north east corners. Closet point of infrastructure is Crystalvale Station access track 30m from southeast corner. Holroyd River, Yarraden & Crystalvale are an aggregation of leasehold grazing stations managed by Corporate Carbon as part of Savanna Fire Management project.

description: Holroyd River Station, 42.6km south west of Coen.

Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. North east corner is 25m in from Holroyd River Station access track. Holroyd River, Yarraden & Crystalvale are an aggregation of leasehold grazing stations managed by Corporate Carbon as part of Savanna Fire Management project.

description: Yarraden Station, 13.5km South of Coen, 28.9km North East of Yarraden.
comments: Complex slope, there is a low rocky ridge that runs through the middle of site in a westerly direction. Site slopes by 3 degrees in all directions from the centre of the plot. Surface strew is granite as cobbles. Site is long unburnt. Some scarring on tree, but a lot of leaf litter and a diverse forb layer. Grazing effect is low, cattle pads run through eastern edge of the site. Introduced plant impact is low with some Mesosphaerum suaveolens and Stylosanthes scabra present . Homogeneity is confined to the plot. North west corner is 5m in from the main development road. Holroyd River, Yarraden & Crystalvale are an aggregation of leasehold grazing stations managed by Corporate Carbon as part of Savanna Fire Management project.

Homogeneity- confined to plot but continues 1km east and 300m south. There is an access track, Telegraph Road, 50m from the western edge, where the Themeda is thickest. The Peninsula Developmental Road is located 700m north east of the plot and the Piccaninny homestead is 4.5km south of site. Site located 100km north North West of Coen.

description: Piccaninny Plains, 9.6km south west of homestead.

Introduced plant effect is low, some Stylosanthes scabra, Mesosphaerum suaveolens and Themeda quadrivalvis. Homogeneity extensive community extends over track. South west corner is 30m in from fence line access track. 100m in all directions is the same community.

description: Steve Irwin Reserve, Bertiehaugh sublease. 4.9km south east of Bertiehaugh homestead.

In terms of homogeneity the community is extensive, but the South West corner is 20m from the road to the Coolabah out station and the other side of the road on the Western edge is a denser thicket of another community. 20m beyond the plot is the same community.

location_description: Introduced plant species impact is high, with extensive introduced Stylosanthes hamata as well as some Stylosanthes scabra, Urochloa mosambicensis and Melinis repens. Grazing effect is moderate from cattle, the site is in paddock 4 of the Wambiana grazing trial. Site was burnt at a high intensity on October 31st 1990 and again on October 27th 2011. The site is paired with QDADEU0001 in a neighbouring paddock, which is less heavily stocked it is in what would have been the same vegetation community.

location_description:
Wambiana Station,  2.8km east north east of homestead. 54km south-south west of Charters Towers. No pit description, pit soil samples or bulk densities taken for this site. Only subsites and metagenomics taken. See QDADEU0005 for soil description. 100k detailed geology mapping has site mapped as TQc/TQr- Campaspe formation. Site mapped BO2n in Land Resources of the Dalrymple Shire, and probably matches the Wambiana soil profile class.

Current effect of grazing from cattle on the plot’s grass is low due to recent rain. Introduced species impact is moderate with some Indian couch and some stylo in the plot. Wambiana’s fire history includes two known fires. A very hot one on 31 October 1999, and another hot but less intense fire on 27 October 2011. There is little evidence on the site of the last fire. Site is homogenous.
