There is a considerable amount Carissa and other increaser species that indicate that the site has heavily grazed previously.

description: Fletcherview Research Station, 1.1km south east of homestead. 22.4km north west of Charters Towers
comments: Landform element and pattern is a plain on relictual floodplain of the Burdekin river. Surface strew is a mix of gravel and cobbles, largely covered by the grasses. Unconsolidated unidentified material from old river wash. Plot is flat.
visit_notes: WE2 transect has missing points at 16m-22m. no plants are recorded and substrate is Unknown.
location_description: Introduced plant impact is high with the ground layer dominated by Bothriochloa pertusa and Cenchrus ciliaris with Stylosanthes hamata,Urochloa mosambicensis and Stylosanthes scabra and other grasses and forbs present . Has been cleared in the past, some regeneration of trees and only a couple of mature Eucalyptus brownii.  Grazing impact at present is low as there is a lot of ground cover but evidence of heavy grazing from cattle in the past with cow pats and uneven surface. Site appears long unburnt. Site is homogenous.

description: Fletcherview station 1.1km south east of homestead. 21.9km northwest of Charters Towers
comments: The element is a hillslope and the pattern is a rise. The crest of the rise would be about 60 metres away, with a 4 degree slope to the south east. The surface strew is mixed, with mainly quartz gravels.
visit_notes: All unknown substrates are termite mound.
location_description: Introduced plant species effect is moderate-  the ground layer is dominated by Bothriochloa pertusa, Urochloa mosambicensis, Cenchrus ciliaris and other introduced grasses. There has been light grazing at this site, however there are still inflorescence on most of the grasses.The site looks long unburnt with scarring on trees. The plot is homogenous, with a slight increase of Carissa to the bottom of the slope. There is a very large pit 10m to the NW corner, and the station track is another 40m beyond that. There is also evidence of wood collection with a few trees that have been cut down.

description: Dutton river station 35km north north west of homestead. 110km north west of Richmond
comments: 5+ years since last fire. Introduced plant effect minimal- none noted. Grazing impact moderate. Homogeneity- west 20m 50m to the south north of sites grades into Acacia shirleyi woodland. 50m further to the east.
location_description: Dutton river station 35km north north west of homestead. 110km north west of Richmond

description: Dutton River Station about 46 northwest of homestead and 110kms northeast of Richmond.
comments: Erythrophleum chlorostachys low woodland with Eucalyptus microneura and emergent Corymbia spp. on a sandplain.
location_description: Dutton River Station about 46 northwest of homestead and 110kms northeast of Richmond.

description: Dutton river station, 20km west north west of homestead. 90km north east of Richmond
comments: Very dry. At south west corner of site is track running off to north east. Homogeneity- 50m to east and south. To the north borders Acacia tephrina woodland. Track to west but community continues another 50m beyond. Introduced plant effect- moderate, some Cenchrus ciliaris and Stylosanthes scabra. Grazing effect- severe, most palatable species gone. Long unburnt, no scarring on trees/age of canopy.
location_description: Dutton river station, 20km west north west of homestead. 90km north east of Richmond

description: Saxby Downs Station about 5kms north of Saxby Downs homestead. 110kms northwest of Richmond.
comments: Lysiphyllum cunninghamii low woodland with Terminalia aridicola subsp. aridicola on Sandplain.
location_description: About 5kms north of Saxby Downs (110kms northwest of Richmond). Bauhinia woodland on sandplain

description: Saxby downs station. 9 km north of homestead. 115km north west of Richmond
comments: Long unburnt 10+ years. Introduced plant effect- minimal. Grazing effect moderate- little feed for cattle. Homogeneity- 50m in all directions- difficult to see beyond that.
location_description: Saxby downs station. 9 km north of homestead. 115km north west of Richmond

description: Saxby Downs about 15kms north of homestead and about 80kms north of Maxwelton.
comments: Ground layer mostly bare, heavily grazed. Heavy leaf drop due to dry conditions. Site is homogenous and part of an extensive community.
location_description: Saxby Downs about 15kms north of homestead and about 80kms north of Maxwellton. Woodland of Lysiphyllum cunninghamii on sandplain.

description: Crowfells Station, 100kms north of Julia Creek.
comments: Aristida latifolia low tussock grassland with Panicum decompositum var. tenuis and other tussock grasses on clay plain.
location_description: Crowfells Station, 100kms north of Julia Creek.

description: Millungera station. 50km west of homestead. 100km North East of Julia Creek.
comments: Long unburnt- some old scarring on Grevillea striata. Grazing effect low, some cattle. Introduced plant effect low- some Cenchrus ciliaris.
location_description: Millungera station. 50km west of homestead. 100km North East of Julia Creek.

description: Millungera station, 40km east of homestead. 97km north north east of Julia Creek
comments: To the north of site across track has been burnt in previous year but site is long unburnt. Introduced plant effect low, a few Stylosanthes in plot. Homogeneity, community continues 1km to the north, south and west. To the east 200m. Grazing effect is low, site not recently grazed though a few scattered cattle prints in the site.
location_description: Millungera station, 40km east of homestead. 97km north north east of Julia Creek

description: Millungera station. 30km east south east of homestead. 83km north north west of Julia Creek.
comments: Sandplain. Very dry conditions. High grazing impact evident in ground layer. Site is homogeneous and part of an extensive community. Significant leaf drop in mid- and upper-storey species. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Millungera station. 30km east south east of homestead. 83km north north west of Julia Creek.

description: Millungera Station, 30km south east of homestead. 80km north north east of Julia creek
comments: Site very long unburnt-  scarring on larger trees. Introduced plant effect- low, small patch of Cenchrus ciliaris. Effect of grazing - low, some cattle tracks in sites. Homogeneity- grades in and out Melaleuca and Lysiphyllum through landform. Community extends 50m beyond site in all directions. Very light rain previous night but not enough to stimulate vegetation response.
visit_notes: Basal wedge: Add one x dead at northwest (factor 0.1).
location_description: Millungera Station, 30km south east of homestead. 80km north north east of Julia creek

description: Boomarra station 5km south west of homestead. 150km north of Cloncurry.
comments: Alluvial plain with mixed surface strew lithology. Some drainage depressions 10m wide by 20cm deep where water would pool in wet season. Grazing effect is currently low but close to bore so likely more heavily grazed in past. Introduced plants- some Cenchrus ciliaris but cover is low. Site long unburnt- no scarring on Eucalyptus pruinosa.
location_description: Boommara station 5km south west of homestead. 150km north of Cloncurry.

description: Boomarra station. 36km North west of homestead. 160km North north west of Cloncurry.
comments: Time since last fire difficult to tell. Not burnt within last two to three years. Introduced plant effect minimal. Grazing effect is high- some distance from water point but most grass heads chewed off or pushed over.  Homogeneity- community continues to the west 600m where it joins a Gidgee woodland, 1km to the south with scattered Atalaya, 1km to north and east.
location_description: Boomarra station. 36km North west of homestead. 160km North north west of Cloncurry.

description: Magowra station. 52km South south west of homestead. 70km south west of Normanton.
comments: Astrebla squarrosa low tussock grassland with Sarga timorense, Eulalia aurea, Panicum decompositum var. decompositum and Chrysopogon fallax on a clay plain. Lightly grazed.
visit_notes: No Basal area measured. No woody material.
location_description: Magowra station. 52km South south west of homestead. 70km south west of Normanton.

description: Magowra station. 55km South south west of  homestead. 74km South west of Normanton.
comments: Older inactive alluvial plain. Grazing effect is low- grasses more or less intact. Introduced plants- minimal inside quadrat but rubber vine close by the southern boundary of the site.  Fire - difficult to tell but not in last 3-4 years. Subsoil damp. Homogeneity- community continues 1km to east and west and 2km north and south.
location_description: Magowra station. 55km South south west of  homestead. 74km South west of Normanton.

description: Magowra station. 53km south south west of homestead. 72 km south west of Normanton.
comments: On broad drainage depression. Clay soil with loamy surface. Few weeds, little evidence of grazing, no evidence of fire.
location_description: Magowra station. 53km south south west of homestead. 72 km south west of Normanton.

description: Mutton Hole Conservation Park. 3.5 km north east of Normanton
comments: No slope but site interspersed with shallow drainage depressions. North east corner of site borders a lagoon some 20-30m wide by 1km long. Homogeneity- community is more or less confined to the site but extends 50m north and south beyond the site. To the west grades into more dense Excoecaria shrubland, to the east is the lagoon. Grazing effect low- some kangaroos and pigs. Introduced plant effect- low. Unburnt for previous 3-4+ years. Recent fire through Excoecaria shrubland south of the site.
location_description: Mutton hole CP. 3.5 km north east of Normanton

description: Mutton hole Conservation Park.  3.2km North east of Normanton.
comments: Alluvial terrace along side drainage of the Norman River system. No evidence of cattle grazing or fire, some pig digging. Site is relatively homogeneous. Eucalyptus microtheca more common on northern side but occurs throughout. Introduced plant effect low - Passiflora foetida.
location_description: Mutton hole Conservation Park.  3.2km North east of Normanton.

description: Mutton hole conservation park. 5.7km north of Normanton.
comments: Gently undulating site but overall site is flat. Shallow waterhole in north of the site. Large patches of salt scald/crust through the site. Dry but subsurface still wet. Grazing effect- low but some evidence of pigs in the site. Long unburnt. Introduced plants minimal. Homogeneity- community continues 30m to the north where it borders a mangrove lined creek channel. To the south and west 600m. To the east 50m where it merges into mangrove channels
location_description: Mutton hole conservation park. 5.7km north of Normanton.

description: Delta Downs Station. 38km West of Homestead. 74km north north west of Normanton
comments: Grassland of Sporobolus virginicus with patches of Tecticornia indica low shrubland and bare saline soil. No weeds, some grazing by cattle and some pig digging.
visit_notes: No woody veg on site for basal area or LAI
location_description: Delta Downs station. 38km West of Homestead. 74km north north west of Normanton

description: Delta Downs Station. 34km west of homestead. 56km north east of Karumba
comments: On relic dune. Site is on a drainage line on crest of the dune. Dam wall about 50m south of the site. Homogeneity- community is more or less confined to the site. Grazing effect- heavily impacted by pigs and kangaroos. Close to dam but cattle haven not been present in large numbers for quite some time. Effect of introduced plant species high- Cryptostegia grandiflora dominants in mid and upper canopy. Also some Hyptis and other annuals. Long unburnt- recruitment in Corymbia and Atalaya. Site is convex with eastern and western edges rising slightly and the centre being close to the lowest point.
location_description: Delta Downs Station. 34km west of homestead. 56km north east of Karumba

description: Delta Downs station. 28km west of homestead. 57km north north east of Karumba
comments: Marine plain. Grassland of Xerochloa imberbis with Tecticornia indica, Tecticornia pergranulata and patches of Sporobolus virginicus and bare soil. Cattle hoof prints common and pig digging across site.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody veg for LAI
location_description: Delta Downs station. 28km west of homestead. 57km north north east of Karumba

description: Delta Downs. 30 km west of homestead. 56 north north west of Karumba
comments: Fire history difficult to tell but not burnt in previous 2 years. Grazing effect is moderate mainly from cattle. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community continues 50m to the west as far as a relic dune then continues on the other side. Subtle change starting just north of the site with more termite mounds corresponding to a very small rise in elevation. To the south community continues 1km and to the east 500m where there is another relic dune.
visit_notes:
transect w2 to e2 should be called w1 to e1
transect e1 to w1 should be called e2 to w2

Structural summary not allowing sedge life forms to be entered. 

Structural summary should be

Oryza v. 4719
Fimbrisylis v. 4693
Cyperus  v. 4727
location_description: Delta Downs. 30 km west of homestead. 56 north north west of Karumba

description: Karumba holdings. 3km North north east of Karumba.
comments: Vegetation is patchy, with much bare soil - typical of these coastal salt flats. Surface soil is covered in saline crust and soil is damp. No evidence of weeds or feral animals. Agile wallaby tracks across whole site.
visit_notes: Samphire tidal flats.
location_description: Karumba holdings. 3km North north east of Karumba.

description: Karumba Holdings. 3.5km north of Karumba
comments: On relic dune. Centre of the site is on a very low relic dune. Western edge is a drainage depression with heavier soil where Cryptostegia grandiflora is more concentrated. Dune running more or less north south. Grazing effect- heavily impacted by wallabies. Weed effect severe- rubber vine, neam and Chinese apple spread through the site.
location_description: Karumba holdings. 3.5km north of Karumba

description: 2.3km north north east of Karumba
comments: Relic dune  with shallow drainage running through its centre with scattered mangrove shrubs. High component of woody weeds - Ziziphus mauritania, Azadirachta indica, Cryptostegia grandiflora and some Cenchrus ciliaris.
visit_notes: Transect west3 to east3 is incomplete.
location_description: 2.3km north north east of Karumba

description: Delta Downs Station. 45km south south west of homestead. 38 km north east of Karumba
comments: Terminalia has mostly lost its leaves so cover is subsequently lower. 2 shallow drainage lines 10cm deep running north to south through the site. Homogeneity- difficult to tell beyond site due to thickness of vegetation. Eastern edge of site is edge of the community. 50m to the south, north and west. Grazing effect is low- cattle present but little feed. Long unburnt- trunks black but from fungus rather than fire. Introduced plant effect minimal. Check soil sheet for info on surface strew- possibly lateritic.
location_description: Delta Downs Station. 45km south south west of homestead. 38 km north east of Karumba.

description: Delta Downs Station. 36.5 km south west of homestead. 42km north east of Karumba.
comments: Very dry, little evidence of fire and weeds. Some grazing by cattle and wallabies. Homogenous site but this community is restricted to outer margins of broad drainage lines on alluvial plains in the lower reaches of northern Gulf rivers.
location_description: Delta Downs Station. 36.5 km south west of homestead. 42km north east of Karumba.

description: Staaten River NP, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead. Low woodland of Melaleuca viridiflora. QPWS monitoring site.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The landform and element is a plain on a plain. The site is flat so no notable slope or aspect. There is no surface lithology. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
QNPWS monitoring site.

Plain with pale sandy earth in shallow valley between lows and ridges. Site is homogenous. Pig digging common across site and grazing by cattle and horses. No weeds. Recent fire has scorched south and west facing side of tree trunks to height of about 3 to 4 metres. Termite mounds present on site. Site is fenced by QPWS to exclude pigs, cattle, horses. Adjoins site QDAGUP0030 (horse, cattle exclosure) and QDAGUP0031 (control, open to grazing). Site dimensions modified slightly to accommodate fence (101x99m).

description: Staaten River NP, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead. Low woodland of Melaleuca viridiflora. QPWS monitoring site.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The landform and element is a plain on a plain. The site is flat so no notable slope or aspect. There is no surface lithology. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
QNPWS monitoring site.

Plain with pale sandy earth in shallow valley between lows and ridges. Site is homogenous. Pig digging common across site and grazing by cattle and horses. No weeds. Recent fire has scorched south and west facing side of tree trunks to height of about 3 to 4 metres. Termite mounds present on site. Site is fenced by QPWS to exclude pigs, cattle, horses. Adjoins site QDAGUP0030 (horse, cattle exclosure) and QDAGUP0031 (control, open to grazing). Site dimensions modified slightly to accommodate fence (101x99m).
visit_notes: All unknown substrates are termite mounds
location_description: There is no evidence of grazing or introduced species as it is in the exclosure. There is no evidence of fire, though there was a cooler burn the year prior. The site is mostly homogeneous in the tree layer, although most of the Melaleuca citrolens are on the western side of the plot. The ground layer is very patchy with some areas dominated by grasses and others by forbs and sedges.

description: Staaten River National Park, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element plain and pattern is a plain. No discernable slope. No apparent outcrop or surface strew. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is fenced by QPWS to exclude horses and cattle and is alongside QDAGUP0029 (pig exclosure) and QDAGUP0031 (control site).  Soil is pale earth. Shallow depression running up to low sand ridge with hard pan at about one metre. Pig digging occurs throughout site. Termite mounds present. Fire scars present on southwest side of trunks. Site is more open in northwest corner otherwise homogenous.
location_description: Staaten River NP, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead. Low woodland of Melaleuca viridiflora with M.citrolens and mixed trees.

description: Staaten River National Park, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a Plain on a Plain. There is no lithology to note and no surface strew, there is a high presence of cryptogam. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Pale earth soil in shallow depression and seepage zone between low sand ridges. Evidence of fire in past 2 years with scorch marks on southwest side of tree trunks reaching to canopy. Significant pig digging and horse and cattle scats present. Weed free. Site is the control for two adjoining sites set up with QPWS as feral animal exclosures (QDAGUP0030 and QDAGUP0029)
location_description: Staaten River NP, about 35kms west of Bulimba Homestead. Melaleuca citrolens low woodland.

description: Staaten River National Park, about 35kms west of Bulimba homestead.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site is a Plain on a Plain. There is no lithology to note and no surface strew, there is a high presence of cryptogam. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Pale earth soil in shallow depression and seepage zone between low sand ridges. Evidence of fire in past 2 years with scorch marks on southwest side of tree trunks reaching to canopy. Significant pig digging and horse and cattle scats present. Weed free. Site is the control for two adjoining sites set up with QPWS as feral animal exclosures (QDAGUP0030 and QDAGUP0029)
visit_notes:
Platyzoma microphylla not in site

Basal wedge done incorrectly and data unable to be used.
location_description: It rained recently in the past month. The soil is dry. In terms of grazing, there is some evidence of cattle and pigs but the impact would be low. There is no evidence of introduced species in the site. There was a low intensity fire late last season in 2021, but the is no evidence of that now.

description: Rungulla National park near ranger outstation
comments:
ONLY SW point coordinate. FOLLOW UP OTHER SITE POINTS

The landform and element. It is a plain on an alluvial plain, the site was very flat with no discernible slope. There was very little outcropping with a gravel top, otherwise no surface strew.
Bush Blitz expedition standard site.
location_description: In terms of introduced species, there are a few weedy grasses and forbs but the impact is low. The site is in an exclusion so minimal to no impact from cattle, with the possibility of rabbits and kangaroos. Outside of the site, it was very heavily grazed by cattle. The site doesn’t seem to have burnt for a while with no obvious scarring.

description: Rosebank Station, 9km south south east of Longreach.
comments: Outer floodplain. 1km to nearest watercourse. Weed impact low -some Cenchrus ciliaris as isolated clumps. Grazing impact low. Lots of forbs and other perennials. Significant rain 1 month previous with follow up showers.
location_description: 9km SSE of Longreach on Rosebank station

description: Rosebank Station.7.5km South west of Longreach
comments: Homogeneity- contained north and south- coming out of river channel. Drainage line running from east to west- curves through site. Eastern edge of site is a waterhole.  Introduced plant effect high- Cenchrus ciliaris- Bathurst burr and other species. Grazing effect high. Cattle, kangaroos and pigs.  Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and recruitment of younger trees. Slope is broadly to the west but drainage ditches to 2m through the site.
location_description: 7.5km South west of Longreach on Rosebank station

description: Rosebank Station.10kms southeast of Longreach
comments: Undulating clay plain. Some growth from rainfall about 6 weeks prior to visit. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus cillaris present.
location_description: Mitchell grassland on undulating clay plain  about 10kms southeast of Longreach

description: Rosebank station. 10km South of Longreach
comments: Weed impact low- some Cenchrus ciliaris in small clumps .
location_description: 10km South of Longreach on Rosebank station

description: Rosebank Station. 10.5km south east of Longreach.
comments: Swamp. Straddles channel and in floodplain. Combination of channel and flood out.  River channel winds through plot on southern edge. Introduced plant effect high- Cenchrus ciliaris dominant in ground layer.  Community  opens up more outside the site to the south and north east. Grazing effect high- cattle, Kangaroos and pigs. Fire impact- long unburnt- no scarring on trees. Rainfall one month previous.
location_description: 10.5km SE of Longreach on Rosebank station

description: Whitehill Station, 5kms east of homestead. 30km south of Longreach.
comments: Grazing impact moderate. Some cattle and kangaroos. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- some Cenchrus ciliaris.
location_description: About 5kms east of Whitehill Station, south of Longreach. Mitchell grassland

description: Whitehill station. 30km SW of Longreach
comments: Fire impact difficult to tell- no scorch marks on gidgee. Slight drainage line running due south close to south west corner. Coolabahs to South of site in drainage line. Introduced plant effect- moderate- some Cenchrus ciliaris but not really dominant. Grazing impact moderate. Grasses chewed but still intact.
location_description: 30km SW of Longreach on Whitehills station

description: Whitehill Station, about 30kms south of Longreach.
comments: Fire- Long unburnt some very old dead fallen litter. Low impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris low cover.
visit_notes: Panicum decompositum not collected on site- used Annual Grass in the point intercept.
location_description: On Whitehill Station, about 30kms south of Longreach. Mitchell grassland

description: Lochern National Park about 3kms west north west of Ranger station.
comments: This site received no rainfall in previous year however a flow down the adjoining Thomson River flooded the site and caused growth of vegetation. Site QDAMGD0009 and all other sites in this vicinity e.g. MGD0012 did not receive summer rain. However this site was inundated by a major flow down the adjacent Thompson River that occurred after significant rain 100kms upstream.
location_description: Lochern National Park about 3kms west north west of Ranger station. Bluebush swamp.

description: Lochern National Park, edge of Thompson river. 117km south west of Longreach.
comments: Slope- Broadly to the South. Several smaller channels. Older channels in site with main channel abutting the NE corner at large waterhole. Introduced plant effect.  Grazing effect low- no cattle but Kangaroos. Some impact from pigs seen on levee that is above high water mark on western boundary. Fire Long unburnt. Climate- where water has got to everything is growing. Dry elsewhere on levy and beyond. No recent rain.
location_description: Edge of Thompson river 117km SW of Longreach on Lochern National Park

description: Lochern National Park, about 8kms north of ranger station. Approximately 117km south west of Longreach.
comments: Grassland of Astrebla spp. on cretaceous sediments. Very dry.
location_description: Lochern National Park, about 8kms north of ranger station. Mitchell grassland

description: Idalia National Park 10km north east of ranger station, close to entry gate
comments: Acacia tephrina low open woodland with scattered Acacia harpophylla with shrub stratum of Eremophila mitchellii with Senna artemisioides subsp. alicia and a sparse ground stratum of Sida spp., chenopods and Cenchrus ciliaris on plain. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris and Opuntia stricta present but low cover.
location_description: idalia national park 10km north east of ranger station

description: Bladensburg National Park, 1km east of Bladensburg Homestead. 15km south of Winton.
comments: Shallow drainage line running 40m south of site. Sloping to south west 1 degree and a little more at south west corner. Strew mostly 5 to 50mm with larger cobbles. Strew lithology mixed- sandstone, mudstone as well as possibly some lateritic elements. check soil sample for more detail. Overnight rain light but no vegetation response. Grazing moderate- kangaroos in large numbers. no introduced plant species of note. Long unburnt- no scarring etc. on nearby coolabahs
location_description: 1km east of Bladensburg Homestead. 15km south of Winton

description: Bladensburg National Park, about 1kmSW of ranger base.
comments: Astrebla squarrosa low open tussock grassland with scattered Astrebla pectinata and Astrebla elymoides. on Cretaceous sediments.
location_description: Bladensburg NP about 1kmSW of ranger base. Mitchell grassland on cretaceous sediments.

description: Bladensburg National Park, 11km south of Bladensburg homestead. 26km south of Winton
comments: Swamp. Drainage lines in site, main one from south east to north west curves through site. .5m deep sandy base. Denser E. coolabah in channels sparser on flat areas. No evidence of fire. No scarring in trees and also recruitment in E. coolabah. Grazing impact from kangaroos and also pigs. Introduced species- Cenchrus ciliaris dominant though sparse in ground layer. Also Sida spinosa. Little strew or outcrop. Light shower previous day.
visit_notes:
mid acacia cambagei qda 001589

eucalyptus coolabah qda 001565



ground layer cenchrus ciliaris qda 001571

sida trichpoda qda 001577
location_description: 11km south of Bladensburg Homestead. 26km SSE of Winton

description: Bladensburg National Park about 14kms east of ranger base.
comments: Acacia cambagei low woodland with scattered Eucalyptus coolabah and a mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum gilvum with some Santalum lanceolatum and a very sparse ground stratum of Cenchrus ciliaris. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris moderate cover.
location_description: Bladensburg NP about 14kms east of ranger base. Gidgee-coolibah woodland

description: Daintree Station. Approximately 40km north of Winton.
comments: Astrebla lappacea low open tussock grassland with scattered Aristida latifolia on clay plain derived from Cretaceous sediments. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.
location_description: Daintree Station north of Winton. Mitchell grassland

description: Daintree Station. 40km north of Winton
comments: On Cretaceous sediments. Very little relief for several kilometres. Very gentle slope to the north west. Vegetation community continues at least 500m in all directions from the plot. Introduced species- some Cenchrus ciliaris in scattered clumps particularly in north west corner. Grazing effect low- cattle present but site some distance from water point. Time since last fire unknown.
location_description: daintree station 40km north of winton

description: Cathedral Hills Station 8.7km south south east of homestead. 61km SE of Kynuna
comments: On an alluvial plain. Homogeneity- continues 500m to the south, same to east 1km to west as far as low hill. North is edge of Acacia cambagei community. Very few species. Introduced plant species- none seen. Grazing effect- moderate approximately 1km from bore. Fire- long unburnt. Strew mostly 2 to 10mm ironstone check soil sheet. Some larger mudstone pebbles/cobbles.
visit_notes: structural summary: no upper or mid ground: astrebla lapacea, astrebla squarosa and aristida latifolia
location_description: Cathedral station 8.7km SSE of homestead. 61km SE of Kynuna

description: Cathedral Hills Station about 10 km south of homestead.  59km south east of Kynuna
comments: Acacia cambagei low woodland with ground stratum of Cenchrus ciliaris on alluvial terrace. Moderate impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.
location_description: Cathedral Hills Station about 10 kms south of homestead.

description: Mackunda Downs Station. 1km east of homestead. 26km West of Middleton.
comments: Fire- long unburnt no scaring on trees close by in river. Introduced plant species- low- some scattered clumps of Cenchrus ciliaris. To the west of quad slope is down to a creek which runs north to south. Some scalded areas in quad, denser patches where there is micro relief. Grazing effect low- some cattle present. Historically heavier. Some rain 2 months previous but vegetation mostly dry. Homogeneity- Community continues to the east 500km and 15m to west where there is a Coolabah flood out. 500m to north and 1km to south
location_description: Makunda Downs Station. 1km east of homestead. 26km West of Middleton

description: Mackunda Downs Station, 500m east of homestead.  26km west of Middleton.
comments: Astrebla pectinata / Cenchrus ciliaris / Astrebla elymoides low open tussock grassland on alluvial plain adjoining creek. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris and Xanthium occidentale present.
location_description: Mackunda Station, north of Middleton.

description: Diamantina Lakes National Park. 16 km north west of ranger station. 160km south west of Boulia.
comments: Swamp. Some grazing from kangaroos and evidence of pigs, impact minimal. Likely heavily grazed historically- less than 1km from old yards. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and little standing litter. introduced plant species- minimal. Shallow channels running north to south through the site.
location_description: Diamantina Lakes National Park. 16 km north west of ranger station. 160km south west of Boulia.

description: Diamantina National Park .15kms northeast of ranger station.
comments: Acacia cambagei low open woodland with ground stratum of Eragrostis xerophila and scattered Astrebla pectinata on a plain on Cretaceous sediments. Has much bare soil with gravel and cryptogram.
location_description: Diamantina National Park,  15kms northeast of ranger station. Low open woodland of Acacia cambagei with ground layer of Eragrostis sp and Astrebla lappacea

description: Dutton River Station 11km North of homestead. 87km North east of Richmond
comments: Rapidly eroding toe slope of hills. Close to the basalt escarpment. Slope is broadly to the south away from the ranges. In south west corner is severely eroding gully creeping in on southern boundary and along western edge. Dry- only a few green tussock grasses in gully. Grazing effect is high, pads and scats. Long unburnt 10+ years. Introduced plants- only one small clump of Cenchrus ciliaris. Strew Lithology mixed. Larger cobbles basalt.
location_description: Dutton River Station,  11km North of homestead. 87km North east of Richmond

description: Dutton River Station, 4kms north of Dutton River Homestead and 83kms northeast of Richmond.
comments: Acacia cambagei low woodland with sparse mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum carronii and bare ground stratum. Ground layer is heavily grazed. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.
visit_notes: Acacia tephrina woodland.
location_description: 4kms north of Dutton River Homestead and 83kms northeast of Richmond.

description: Wiliyan-ngurru (Camooweal Caves) National Park. 17.4km south south west of Camooweal
comments: Clay plain with limestone surface gravel. No introduced species. Long unburnt. Grazed- some cattle but effect low. Dominant species are all in full growth. No trees or shrubs. Limestone substrate and would have water over the site in wet periods. Melon hole Gilgai’s- 1m across and 30cm deep
visit_notes:
Insufficient woody vegetation for basal wedge measure.
Soil pit in SW corner
location_description: Camooweal Caves Conservation park. 17.4km south south west of Camooweal

description: Camooweal Town Common. 3.8km South west of Camooweal.
comments: Site is on a very gentle slope down to Georgina river and would occasionally get flooded. Slope is 2 degrees to the east. Long unburnt. Some grazing from horses and cattle though overall effect is low. Strew is mostly gravel and pebbles- some boulders. Limestone at depth. Alluvial clay in the subsurface and gravel wash at the surface. No shrubs or trees on the site. No introduced species noted.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measures. No soil description. Pit barcodes QDA052804, QDA052805, QDA052806, QDA052807 - no depths recorded on site sheet. Pit in SW corner.
location_description: Camooweal commonage. 3.8km South west of Camooweal.

description: Boomarra Station. 15km west north west of homestead. 136km north north west of Cloncurry.
comments: Fire in October 2012 affected most E. pruinosa which are re-shooting from base and killed most Acacia holosericea. Ground layer is also fire affected. Cenchrus ciliaris is low and re-shooting. There is also Eulalia aurea, Enneapogon avenaceus and Aristida spp. Sandplain with some metamorphic rock outcrop. Boomarra Station. Site is open to grazing by cattle.
location_description: Boomarra station. 15km west north west of homestead. 136km north north west of Cloncurry.

description: Camooweal Caves Conservation Park. 10.5km south west of Camooweal.
comments: Stony plain Fire history difficult to tell- within last 5 years- maybe a little bit longer. Within the site are some deep holes to 40cms deep- possibly caused by trees burnt in last fire Introduced species effect- nil. Grazing effect is low- some old cattle scats in the site. Surface strew is mostly gravel and pebbles up to 50mm, some larger cobbles. Substrate is a mix of laterite, quartzite, and mudstone Homogeneity- site continues to the west 60m, north is road. To the East grades more into Eucalyptus leucophloia woodland, 50m to the south. Site is slightly elevated from clay plains. Slope is flat with no real discernible slope. Flat in visible vicinity.
visit_notes:
North to south transect 3 points 69 to 80 missing.
Soil pit in NE corner and subsites 1-5 in SW corner.
location_description: Camooweal Caves Conservation park. 10.5km south west of Camooweal.

description: Idalia National Park. 15 km North of Ranger Station.
comments: Acacia aneura woodland with emergent poplar box and Ironbark. Acacia cambagei low woodland with sparse mid-stratum of Lysiphyllum carronii and bare ground stratum. Ground layer is heavily grazed. Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Cenchrus ciliaris.
visit_notes: Acacia aneura woodland with emergent poplar box and Ironbark. Atop broader plateau 7km distance from edge. Grazing impact low. Mainly Echidna and possibly bettongs. Long unburnt- no scarring, very old trees. Some selective clearing. Eucalypts and mulga have been cut for timber in places. introduced plants effect low. 1 clump of Cenchrus cilliaris. Auger unable to pick up soil as it was too powdery. Too hard to penetrate with auger. Micro relief - digging by bettongs, Echidnas and possibly pigs. Pit and prime subsites at south east corner.
location_description: 57km SE of Issiford on Idalia NP

description: Northern section of Idalia National Park in Acacia shirleyi woodland on tertiary remnant.
comments: Woodland / closed forest of Acacia shirleyi with no understorey and bare ground. Idalia NP about 20 kms north of ranger base.
location_description: Northen section of Idalia NP in Acacia shirleyi woodland on tertiary remnant.

description: Idalia National Park, 61km SE of Issiford
visit_notes: Acacia aneura woodland. Rising a little more to the NE corner where it becomes rockier. Site is on Plateau above Mitchell grass downs 10km to the north. Grazing impact low- lots of echidna diggings in the site plus kangaroos. Weed impact low. Very long unburnt- no scarring on Ironbark or Mulga and a varied cohort with old trees and younger shrubs.
location_description: 61km SE of Issiford on Idalia NP

description: Samford Ecological Research Facility, 250m south east of barracks, 1.8km south-south west of Samford village.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Site is not aligned to the grid, with NW corner the most northern point. Slope is an average of 5 degrees, to the south east (135 degrees), flatter near the top and steeper towards the bottom of the site. No surface strew or outcrop, only lots of leaf litter. Grazing impact is low, mainly kangaroos, no grazing by stock. Site is long unburnt, with no anecdotal evidence or scarring on trees. Introduced plants numerous but cover low- Ochna serrulata and and Asparagus plumosus bing the most abundant.  Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot, as vegetation becomes denser at the bottom edge in proximity to the creek. Nearest infrastructure is the access track to the barracks, 15m away. To the north of the site is a droughtnet shelter and infrastructure associated with the super site (litter fall traps). Most trees are tagged and marked at 1.3m for DBH measurement.
 


-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Limited data from first visit Plant voucher and leaf tissue sample Barcodes only collected by TERN Ecosystem Processes team
visit_notes: Samford Supersite
location_description: Limited data. Herbarium id's and barcoded leaf tissue samples only.

description: Russell Reserve Bunya Mountains, 3.2km south east of Mt Mowbullan. 48km north east of Dalby
comments: Landform element and pattern, hill slope in mountains. 20 degrees slope to SW. Basalt outcrops present, mostly along western edged and SW corner. Basalt boulder surface strew also present. Long unburnt, no evidence of past fire, quite a lot of thatch. Grazing impact minimal. Introduced plant impact is low,  Bidens pilosa, Cirsium vulgare, Gomphocarpus physocarpus, Lantana camara, Opuntia tomentosa present is small numbers. Nearest infrastructure is Bunya Mountains Rd, 15m east of NE corner.
visit_notes:
E3-W3 point 95 and 98 are Cryptogam on rock
No LAI or Basal.
location_description: Landform element and pattern, hill slope in mountains. 20 degrees slope to SW. Basalt outcrops present, mostly along western edged and SW corner. Basalt boulder surface strew also present. Long unburnt, no evidence of past fire, quite a lot of thatch. Grazing impact minimal. Introduced plant impact is low, Conyza sumatrensis, Bidens pilosa, Cirsium vulgare, Gomphocarpus physocarpus, Lantana camara, Opuntia tomentosa present is small numbers. Nearest infrastructure is Bunya Mountains Rd, 15m east of NE corner.Russell Reserve Bunya Mountains, 3.2km south east of Mt Mowbullan. 48km north east of Dalby

description: Samford Ecological Research Facility, 455m south-south west of Barracks. 2.3km south-south west of Samford Village
comments: Site is not aligned to the grid, with north west corner the most northern point. Landform pattern and element is slope on hill. There is a 4 degree slope down to the north north east of the plot. No surface strew or outcrop, only lots of leaf litter. Site sitting over granite. Grazing impact is low, mainly kangaroos, no grazing by stock. Site is long unburnt, with no anecdotal evidence or scarring on trees. Introduced species impact moderate- extensive control of Lantana camara undertaken but still some throughout the site. Asparagus plumosus and Ochna serrulata and other introduced species also present but cover low. Vegetation community is confined to the plot, with denser vegetation in gully below the site and a Lantana control line above the site. Nearest infrastructure is an access track 10m from the North of the site.
visit_notes: Basal wedge notes: ironbark used as a proxy in app for all ironbark species, lumped together for counting in the field. Paper leafed acacia used as proxy for all acacias. Alphitonia used as proxy for all pale barked softwoods. 'Clove smelling tree/fine leaved melaleuca' used as a proxy for Melaleuca (salicina?), which was accidentally not collected at this site (but was at SEQ0001).
location_description: Samford Ecological research facility, 455m south-south west of Barracks. 2.3km south-south west of Samford Village

description: Samford Ecological Research facility, 312m south south west of Baracks. 2.1km south south west of Samford Village
comments: Landform element is hill slope with a pattern of rises. No surface strew or outcrop, site is sitting over granite.  4 degree slope down to the creek in the North East. Introduced plant species impact is moderate with Lantana camara forming dense thickets and  Asparagus plumosus, Ochna serrulata  and other introduced grasses and forbs common throughout the site. Predominately native in upper storey. Grazing impact is low but a hare and a kangaroo were spotted nearby. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Small scale cutting down of trees in the past. Community is confined to the plot. The community continues 75m northeast from the centre down to the creek. The nearest infrastructure is the walking track which is 15-20m from the west side of the plot.
visit_notes:
basal wedge: corymbia tessellaris hits are a lumping of all corymbia sp. in plot. Alphitonia hits are a lumping of small pale barked trees. 

point intercept. SN3 point 56: unknown substrate is moss.
location_description: Samford Ecological Research facility, 312m south south west of Baracks. 2.1km south south west of Samford Village

description: Triodia basedowii hummock grassland with a sparse mid layer of Grevillea stenobotrya
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Triodia hummock grassland
Dune slope, SW corner on crest, NE corner on stand of Acacia georginae woodland
Dominated by Triodia, little bit of Grevillea stenobotrya very occasionally.
Rain earlier in year, spinifex heads up and looking like flowering, not much evidence of seed set but lots of green in leaves of Triodia
Trachymyene glaucifolia green with very occasional flowers
Eriachne aristidea sparsely common
Not much else, not a lot of bright flowering things
Dune has had destocking since 2004, no evidence generally of extra grazing although camels are present in area
No introduced plant species that we see regularly at this site
Soil crust and sand looks good, signs of light rain in last few days but nothing major
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Triodia basedowii hummock grassland with a sparse mid layer of Grevillea stenobotrya.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
no change
Dune slope- South west corner is just over the crest of the dune and North east corner is just bordering the a stand of Acacia georginae. Dune is running to the north east. Site is across the slope of the dune. Long unburnt- at least 20 years but probably longer. No grazing impact. Camels around site but no evidence within the site. Minimal rabbits. No introduced plant species seen. 6 degree slope, slightly uneven through the centre where it flattens out somewhat. Aspect is to the North East ( 45 degrees).

Ausplot 1 25/6/2021  A18
Sandune near maincamp
North east corner borders a stand of gidgee, no physical disturbance since last survey, long unburnt Spinifex grassland T basedowei, no sign of extra grazing since destocking in 2004, no signs of camels although they are in the region.

description: ethabuka reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Blue mallee near SS
Eucalyptus gamophylla (blue mallee), sparse mallee woodland
Mixed Acacia ligulata and other shrubs, some Grevillea stenobotrya on nearby crest but the plot is down in the swale
Ground cover dominatd by Triodia basedowii, looking very healthy and green, plenty of flowering heads up and what look like potentially seed heads.
Some other grasses had a good rain and have flowered on.
very long unburnt site. Evidence of camels (fresh) throughout the plot
Site is relativey flat, crust looks pretty intact in most places, had some recent rain
A. ligulata not flowering but there’s shrub of Eromophila and that is in flower, need an update on fruiting of gamophylla but nothing looking great
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Eucalyptus gamophylla sparse Mallee woodland with a mixed mid layer of Eremophila longifolia, Acacia ligulata and other scattered shrubs and a ground layer of Triodia basedowii and Eragrostis sp.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Swale amongst dunefield. Very long unburnt, At least 1970’s possibly 1950’s since last burn. Evidence of camels- some scats on track and tracks through the site. Cattle removed in 2004 with a big surge of camels and rabbits at this time. Site is flat. South west corner rise slightly at the base of a dune. Close to an existing LTERN nutrient testing plot.

Ausplot 2 30/6/2021 C15
Mallee woodland, E pachyphyla, low stature open woodland, mid stratum A ligulata scattered with E longifolia and other shrubs, ground layer of Triodia and A.hol and Eragrostis, big round hummocks have die back in the centre, burnt in sections in south west, hummocks have old seed heads but  no signs of current flowering or seeding, seed heads abundant when present and available, no sign of cattle but some signs of fresh camel prints directly through the plot, open areas of bare or with cryptogam crust, mallees have reasonable foliage but not in flower , A. ligulata has good cover of foliage.
 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Swale amongst dunefield. Very long unburnt, At least 1970’s possibly 1950’s since last burn. Evidence of camels- some scats on track and tracks through the site. Cattle removed in 2004 with a big surge of camels and rabbits at this time. Site is flat. South west corner rise slightly at the base of a dune. Close to an existing LTERN nutrient testing plot.

description: ethabuka reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Triodia basedowii hummock grassland, very scattered individuals of Grevillea stenobotrya, 1 Acacia georginae. The dune slope is gentle and the spinifex is showing post-rain response of flowering heads up (but looking empty, so not real evidence of seeding throughout the plot but occasional patches would need a check. Some flowering of Ptilotus polystachyus in the understorey, a few things have germinated on since post rain – some grasses, a bit of native parsnip (Trachymene glaucifolia), Salsola kali. Not looking like a huge flush post rain with fields of wildflowers so would’ve been just a moderate response. Still not stock on here although it is near Carlo property boundary so some get through occasionally. Long, long-unburnt, sitting right on DERG weather station.  

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Triodia basedowii hummock grassland with isolated Dodonaea viscosa subsp. angustifolia and Acacia ligulata and 1 isolated Acacia georginae in northwest corner of site.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
 
Very long unburnt- 1970’s or 1950’s. Across track was burnt in previous year. No introduced plant species noted. Grazing effect is low- some cattle tracks through the site, camels also present. Homogeneity- site is on a swale with relic dune to the north east corner with gentle slope to the south west of about 2 degrees. Community continues to the north 100m, to the south is burnt, continues 100m to the east across shallow dune. Close to LTERN weather station and fauna plots.

Ausplot 4 24/6/2021 E16
Spinifex grassland, no physical change since last survey , long unburnt , one gidgee tree isolated scattered stenobotrya scattered ligulata, pterocaulan and ligulata patches, a.hol mostly hayed off scattered schleroleanas, boerhavia and tribulopis, nothing obvious in flower, spinifex heads old, no sign of recent flowering or seeding

description: Ethabuka Reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Eucalyptus coolabah open woodland with a sparse mid layer of shrubs mainly Eremophila longifolia and a Eulalia aurea tussock grassland understory.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
revisit-no change
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Swamp- south west corner is just in the channel of the Field River. Site is more or less flat with only some gentle undulation. Very long unburnt- at least 20 years since last fire but possibly not since 1970’s or 1950’s. Recent fires close by but not into plot. No introduced plants noted. Grazing effect is minimal- likely some camels in the area but no noticeable effect. Homogeneity: Site is in a swale between dunes running to the north west. Community continues to 100m to the south. North east corner is on the edge of the community at the base of lower slopes of sand dunes.

location_description:
Ausplot 7 28/6/2021 E24
Eucalyptus coolabah woodland, adjacent to creek, open woodland no other trees in canopy, Eremophila longifolia common, some Chenopodium desertorum ground cover open and recent rain sprouting Trachymene, Acacia sp., Ptilotus polystachys. ¾ plot is open bare sand patches with scattered leaves from E. coolabah, no other signs of grazing apart from fire that went through since plot was set up.

description: Cravens Peak Reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Acacia georginae open woodland with mixed understory of Chenopods and short tussock grasses dominated by Dactyloctenium radulans.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Acacia georginae open woodland, with a mix of chenopods and grasses in understorey. Acacias are healthy but not recovered from grazing with a browse line still evident. Evidence of pastoralism in the past but no new signs of disturbance or fire.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Revisit-no change
Grazing effect is low- some camel tracks within the plot though historically heavier. Cattle removed in 2004. Introduced plant effect- none noted. Very long unburnt. Homogeneity: Community is in a swale between north westerly trending dunes. Continues 100m to the north west and south east.

Ausplot 11 22/6/2021 D1
Gidgee open woodland,, understorey mixed chenopods of schleroleanas, some grasses but have hayed off, dominants gidgee, schleoleana, mairenana, dry tussocks and forbs not responding to recent rain, wide swale community between dune, previously had cattle and some ongoing signs including a browse line but there is some recruitment of smaller gidgee apparent since destocking in 2006, substrate mix of sand and stony gravel and clay areras and evidence of standing water.

location_description:
Ausplot 11 22/6/2021 D1
Gidgee (Acacia georginae) open woodland, understorey mixed chenopods of Sclerolaena bicornis, Sclerolaena lanicuspis, Sclerolaena glabra, some grasses but have hayed off, Maireana triptera. Wide swale community between dune, previously had cattle and some ongoing signs including a browse line but there is some recruitment of smaller gidgee apparent since destocking in 2006. Substrate mix of sand and stony gravel and clay areas and evidence of standing water.

Revisit
Large swamp framed by dunes on either side. Introduced plant effect minimal- none noted. Grazing effect is low though historically likely higher. One or two old scats. Cattle removed 2004. Many shallow depressions containing forbs to 30cm wide through the site. Very long unburnt. Some scattered gravel- mixed wash.

Ausplot 12 23/62021 E9
Lignum swamp, large swamp with dunes on the east and west, canopy of Coolabah with dominants being lignum,  no obvious flowering, lignum dominant in mid storey and ground dominants include Portulaca and variety of grasses which have seeded and now hayed off, Bergia and Indigofera also common.

description: Cravens Peak Reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Acacia sibirica open shrubland with Aristida holathera var. holathera tussock grass understory, isolated emergent Corymbia terminalis and a sparse mid layer of Eremophila latrobei subsp. glabra and Senna artemisioides subsp. alicia scattered through the site.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Healthy mulga woodland with scattered Corymbia that have lost their canopy and are resprouting. No extra signs of disturbance of fire or additional grazing after the property was destocked. Mulga and Senna artemisioides showing signs of reproduction/fruiting
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Revisit-no change
Site is flat with minor undulation. Some outcrop- mostly sandstone and mostly red earth substrate. Some of the shrubs appear to have been pushed over by camels or cattle though nothing recent. At least 10 years since last fire. No introduced plant species noted. Homogeneity- site abuts road at the north east corner. Community continues to the south 100m on the western edge 100m and 60m to the north.
Ausplot 13 22/6/2021 E1
No change since 2014 or 2018 most flat with a little undulation, some sandstone outcrop and rocky parts, dead shrubs on the ground dead course woody debris looks to have been on the ground for a while, mostly homogeneous, dry no recent big rains, dominant grasses have hayed off Aristida has a little bit of green at the bases, dominant A.s ibirca open woodland with some S. artemisoides  and E. latrobei, and few Hakea reaching into canopy. No extra signs of grazing from cattle or camels, mulga open woodland

description: Boolcoomatta Reserve, 9km north west of homestead
comments: Plot sits on broad flat plain. 1 degree slope to the south east. Very long unburnt- minimal grass cover to carry fire. Introduced plant effect is minimal at present- possibly Carrichtera annua ( not sited) and Medicago ( probably minima) is present. Flecks of gravel but minimal surface strew. Homogeneity- community confined to plot. South east corner opens out into chenopod shrubland. Community extends in valley to west of the site. North of the plot is more open but Acacia carneorum present  in smaller groves.
location_description: Boolcoomata Reserve, 9km north west of homestead

description: Boolcoomatta Reserve, 9km north west of homestead
comments: Plot sits on broad flat plain. 1 degree slope to the south east. Very long unburnt- minimal grass cover to carry fire. Introduced plant effect is minimal at present- possibly Carrichtera annua ( not sited) and Medicago ( probably minima) is present. Flecks of gravel but minimal surface strew. Homogeneity- community confined to plot. South east corner opens out into chenopod shrubland. Community extends in valley to west of the site. North of the plot is more open but Acacia carneorum present  in smaller groves.
visit_notes: No soil data or samples collected.
location_description: The site remains relatively unchanged since previous visit. There is a small amount of surface strew throughout the site, possibly quartzite. Homogeneity only extends approximately 20m from plot and is surrounded by chenopod shrublands. The grazing pressure is low, with some evidence of kangaroos and possibly goats. No fire for many years. No indication of invasive species.

description: Boolcoomatta Reserve. 4.5km south west of homestead. 91.7km west of Broken Hill
comments: The landform is a plain with no slope. Surface strew predominately quartz with some flecks of ironstone and sandstone as well. Mostly gravel 1mm to 50mm. Plot is long unburnt. Low impact of grazing by roos and possibly goats.Check IDs/point intercepts for introduced species impact. Homogeneity confined to plot. Site exist in a patchwork of more open chenopods and then smaller groves of Casuarina pauper occurring in pockets throughout plot. Some C. pauper are present outside the plots by the southern edge and more 60-70m away. South east corner is 5m from Noon Flower Track.
location_description: Boolcoomata Reserve. 4.5km south west of homestead. 91.7km west of Broken Hill

location_description: Relatively unchanged since last visit. Surface strew present as gravel quartzite and covers most of the site. The SE corner is about 20m from the road. No issue with invasive species. Grazing is low, some kangaroo or goat activity possible. No fire for many years.

description: Boolcoomatta Reserve, 2.8km north of homestead. 86.4km west of Broken Hill
comments: Plot on the slope of low granite hill. Some lichen on patches of outcrop ( called cryptogam in Point intercept data). Large sheets of Granite through much of the site.  8 degree slope to the north. Fairly consistent slope but some raised granite patches. Grazing effect is low- mainly from Kangaroo and Euros. Recruitment  in Mulga since rabbits numbers reduced. Very long unburnt. Small scale cutting of mulga but very old- check with Bush Heritage Australia for more detailed history. Introduced plant effect is low- Carrichtera annua, Echium plantagineum and Medicago minima present but cover low.  Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- Northern edge of plot is a granite outcrop. Community extends to the south over hill. Northern edge is 15m from turn around from Gnamma hole track ( very narrow). Main track 1km to the west.

location_description: The site is a granitebhillslope and remains unchanged from previous visit, though somewhat drier. Grazing pressure is low, though some kangaroo and goats are present. Low to no impact from invasive species. The site has not been burnt in many years.

description: Boolcoomatta  Reserve, 5.9km south west of homestead. 89km west south west of Broken Hill.
comments: Landform element is a stream channel in a floodplain.Eucalyptus camaldulensis woodland in river channel. The plot has an aspect of 1 degree to South in direction of river flow. Oonartar track 50-60m from south west corner. Plot is long unburnt, with no evidence of previous fire. Grazing pressure is low, mostly by roos and emus, potentially goats. Introduced species impact is low with some Xanthium spinosum, horehound and Lycium ferocissimum present. Community is confined to plot. Three distinct channels through plot. Deepest is on the eastern side. The Eucalyptus camaldulensis woodland is homogenous throughout the site, extending only a metre or so from the banks.
location_description: Boolcoomata Reserve, 5.9km south west of homestead. 89km west south west of Broken Hill

Introduced species impact is low with some Xanthium spinosum, horehound and Lycium ferocissimum present. Community is confined to plot. Three distinct channels through plot. visit_notes: No soil data or samples collected.
location_description: In river channel, no water flow for many years. The grazing pressure is low, possibly some goats and kangaroos, though most have died off in the past few months. No fire for many years. As for invasive species, there are a few dying/dead Lycium ferocissimum. The site is located approximately 60m from the road.

description: Boolcoomatta Reserve, 40km west of broken Hill. 2km south of Boolcoomatta homestead
comments: Open plain.Small surface gravel, covers entire site. Homogeneity extends for at least 1km in either direction. Grazing has been heavy by kangaroos, but they have all died off in the past few months. A pipeline and road 20m from NW corner. Overall very severe drought conditions, no rain for many months.

description: Located approx. 55 km NW from Innamincka township, approx. 1.5 km from Moorpark WH
comments: Landform element and pattern is a floodplain gilgai/ crabhole with puffy scalded grey clay loam with fine sandy surface layer. Along fringes of the broader area there are lower sandy rises with sparse saltbush and Coolibah.
visit_notes:
Note: point intercept was started from W5 to E5, but recorded as the startpoint S1 to N1 which is incorrect. On voice recorder 
S1 - N1 = W5 - E5
N2 - N2 = E4 - W4
S3 - N3 = W3 - E3
N4 - S4 = E2 - W2
S1 - N1 = W1 - E1
location_description:
Site is long unburnt, last fire unknown.
Some large scald with no vegetation present, mild cracking occurring.
Minor scalded small mounded soils and small crabhole gilgais forming.

description: located approx 55NW, approx 1.5km from Moorpark WH, 1 km along boundary fence on North side of fence from SAACHC0003
comments: Landform element and pattern is a floodplain minor occurrence of crabhole with puffy scalded grey clay. Framed by minor low white sand rises.
location_description:
No recent evidence of recent fires of known fire history. 
Minimal evidence of crabholes, higher litter cover. Sclerolaena intricata 0.15m Dactyloctenium radulans 1cm. Patchy areas of Euphorbia parvicaruncula, Eriochiton sclerandroides and Atriplex spp. sparsely present. Of note lots of large clusters of what looks like Eragrostis butts and pugging indicative of past heavy grazing.
Eriochloa australiensis picked up in species list which is indicative of water flow and lower lying areas which hold water for extended periods. In support of this evidence of site function is that there are sandy rises with coolabah on them 200-300m from the quadrat.

description: 50km NW from Inna. Site located 1.5km East of main creek line, divided from 0006 my deeply cut access track, which redirects water from rains.
comments: Landform element and pattern is a floodout on floodplain of major creek system. Scalded grey cracking clay loam with sand film on top.
location_description: Evidence of some past cattle grazing.

description: 50km NW of Innamincka
comments: Site located approx 50km NW from Innamincka, 1.5km east of Cooper creek North Branch. Mudrangie paddock.
visit_notes:
From SW corner NNE bearing at 30 degrees
From SW corner East boundary 120 degrees
Site has been marked using Google Locus Pro
location_description: Lots of open bare ground, leaf litter mostly restricted to around Eucalyptus coolabah and Duma. Of note, clayey pads with Dentella pulvinata and Sclerolaena spp. areas with large scalding.

description: Coongie Lakes NP, 5km north west of Kudramitchie camp. 72.1km north west of Innaminka
comments: Site is located on the edge of the Tiwari Swamp. Element is a plain, pattern is a flood plain of the Cooper Creek. Surface is undulating, mainly windblown dunes. No surface strew or outcrop.
visit_notes: Site selected for Innamincka Regional Reserve Veg productivity project. Paired with SAACHC0009.
location_description: Site is very long unburnt. Grazing impact is low, but cattle are not entirely excluded. Minimal weed impact. Tribulus is likely to be native species, only seeds are present.
a_s_c: 3 SO AD ES EX BEKO- NR

description: Coongie Lakes NP.5.3km north west of Kuderamitchie WH camp. 72km north west of innaminka
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a floodplain, on the northern edge of Tirrawarra Swamp in Malkumba-Coongie Lakes National Park. The slope and aspect of the site is flat, with no discernible slope. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
location_description: There is evidence of grazing, with cattle impact observed throughout the site. Minimal introduced plant species. Tribulus is present but it is likely to be a native species. Site is very long unburnt with no evidence of past fire.

description: Innaminka RR, 12.5km South South west of Kudramitchie camp. 62.4km north west of Innaminka
comments: Element is a plain, pattern is a flood plain. Site is flat, no discernible slope. There is a very shallow drainage line along the western edge, towards the north and anabranches of the Cooper Creek.
visit_notes: Site selected for Innamincka Regional Reserve Veg productivity project. Paired with SAACHC0011.
location_description: Site is long unburnt, with no evidence of fire. Grazing effect is low but cattle are present as it is a regional reserve. Minimal introduced plant impacts. Site is homogenous.

description: Innaminka Rr, 12.6km south south west of Kuderamitchie campsite. 62.2km northwest of innaminka
comments: The site landform and element is a plain on a floodplain, close to an anabranch of the Cooper Creek. There is no discernible slope. No surface strew or lithology, however there are shallow gilgais present.
visit_notes: Pit only dug to 35cm for bulk densities and not sampled. Soil description for SAACHC0010 can be used for this site
location_description:
Site selected for Innamincka Regional Reserve Veg productivity project. Pit only dug to 35cm for bulk densities and not sampled. Soil description for SAACHC0010 can be used for this site. TERN/ Landscapes SA Arid Lands

The site is grazed, with cattle dung throughout and some very old camel scats, but impact is low and cattle have not been present recently. Chenopodium is mainly intact. Site is very long unburnt with no evidence of past fire. Minimal introduced plant impact. The site is homogenous. To the north east is the channel with denser red gums and Eucalyptus coolabah.

description: Innaminka Rr, 6km North west of Scrubby camp yards. 40.3km north west of Innaminka
comments: Landform element and pattern is a dune crest in a small dunefield. To the north east is a large lake system. There is no surface strew, soil is hard at depth but nothing at the surface. The site is straddling both sides of a low dune that runs north south, with a 3-degree slope to the east and west.
visit_notes: Site selected as a random dune site, to pair with SAACHC0007. No basal wedge data; too low.
location_description: There is slightly greater density of grass tussocks along the crest of the dune, but otherwise the site is homogeneous. The swales either side of the dune are dominated by Eucalyptus coolabah. Grazing impact is moderate to high, with a lot of cattle sign and moderate breaking up of the soil surface. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Site is very long unburnt, with no evidence of past fire.
a_s_c: 4 RE AA JL AR EKK- NR

description: Strez creek, innaminka Rr
comments: Landform element and pattern is a flood-out on a floodplain, as the site is located on the floodplain of the Strzelecki Creek. Site is flat with no discernible slope, however it does run to the north. No surface strew or outcrop.
location_description: Site is very long unburnt, with no evidence of past fire. The site is grazed as it is part of the Innamincka Regional Reserve, but impact is currently low. Introduced plant impact is minimal.

description: Goose Island Conservation Park. 1.6 km north of Wardang Island settlement.12km north west of Port Victoria
comments: Lycium ferocissimum shrubland with Chenopods. Goose Island Conservation Park. Weedy, little bare ground. No evidence of fire. No evidence of grazing. Evidence of penguins and mutton birds (burrows) and snakes. Site not homogeneous due to deliberate treatment of Lycium on northern half of site by Scotch College. Dead Lycium shrubs present. No basal wedge taken due to insufficient woody vegetation.
visit_notes: Active Little Penguin nests in plot.
location_description: Goose island. 1.6 km north of Wardang Island settlement.12km north west of Port Victoria

description: 12.3km south of Warooka. 31.9km west south west of Edithburgh
comments: Undulating plain. No outcrop or surface strew. Large patches of semi bare ground with patches of moss and lichen and herbaceous plants.   Very long unburnt 40+ years. Grazing effect is mainly from Kangaroos with numerous bedding sites under trees and shrubs with introduced plant species  Lysimachia arvensis, Sonchus oleraceus and Galium murale common in these. Cover of introduced plants is very low.  Grazing effect is noticeable on orchids. Emus also present. Homogenous to 80+ metres from centre  but dominance of Eucalypt species varies around the plot. North west corner is slightly denser than south east corner.. 350m from main road on eastern edge and 320 south of paddock boundary on northern edge.

description: Warrenben Conservation Park. 14.1km south west to Marion Bay, 34.5km north east to Warooka.
comments: Flat calcarenite plain.  Minimal introduced plant species – Lysimachia arvensis, Lagurus ovatus, Sonchus oleraceus and Galium murale present but at very low cover. Extensive moss cover- very few areas of bare ground. Grazing effect is from Kangaroos and emus. Very long unburnt. Homogenous- some heterogeneity at a sub 1ha level. South west corner is very dense while centre and north have more open areas with calcrete outcrop but typical of patterning across broader landscape. Fire access track 10m from south east corner of plot, highway beyond that.

description: Northwest portion of Warrenben CP, approx. 150 m south of access track and 2.5 km south of Ilfracombe Road.
comments: Plain. Calcarenite outcrop and gravel strew. Slope of 3 degrees to the north. Very long unburnt. Northern section of the part of park burnt in 2013 but didn’t burn into plot.  Lots of evidence of kangaroo activity  with introduced grasses and forbs common around disturbed areas.  Higher density of introduced plant species in open areas- Hypochaeris sp., Trifolium campestre and Euphorbia peplus being the most common  Emu scat with broad bean growing in it. 1 mature Allocasuarina verticillata in north west corner – underneath is 1 lone grazed seedling. Some Eutaxia microphylla but heavily grazed as are orchids and Gahnia with native grasses grazed or only found under protected shrubs. Plot is heterogenous at a sub 1ha level reflective of broader landscape patterns- large areas of open ground with moss cover over calcrete. Acacia triquetra/Acacia rupicola dominant in some patches and Melaleuca decussata in others. Most open in centre and south west of plot. North east on north west are denser.  Community extends 100m from centre of plot. 120m north of plot is park access track.
visit_notes:
All "unknown" substrate records in point intercept data are moss as substrate 

Date of soil pits and subsites: 8/09/2020
location_description: Northwest portion of Warrenben CP, approx. 150 m south of access track and 2.5 km south of Ilfracombe Road.

North of plot has less soil and calcrete outcrop which is more open and devoid of trees- has low shrubs and thick cover of moss and forbs. Elephant ( Boundary track) is 30m from east of plot- highway beyond that. Community extends 300m in all directions.

description: Innes National Park, 100m east of Pondalowie road. 53.4km south west of Warooka
comments: Plot rises to a shallow calcrete ridge in the middle of the plot. Nominal 1 degree slope to the south but site is almost concave due to ridge in middle. Mix of cobbles and gravels with isolated patches of very low calcrete outcrop.  Introduced plant effect is moderate to high in ground story- Anagallis arvensis, Melilotus indicus and other grasses and forbs.  Denser patches of forbs confined to moss cover are mostly introduced plant species. Some patches of Asparagus asparagoides.  Mid layer is all native.  Some patches of moss broken by kangaroo beds and tracks- grazing on perennial native grasses, Eutaxia very heavily grazed. Long unburnt, minimal scarring - very old fire scars on old Mallee. Mallee fowl mound beyond south east corner of the site- inactive.  Homogeneity- vegetation is consistent through the site but a  limestone ridge through the middle of the plot is a little more open. Plot is between from the Walk the Yorke’s track and main Pondalowie road. 80m east of road and 10m west of walking trail

description: Southern Yorke Peninsula, 5.6km north of Marion Bay, 46.5km south west of Warooka
comments: Plot sits on a low calcareous rise. A 2-degree slope to the north north-west. There is quite a lot of exposed outcrop/sheet limestone in patches through the site as well as quite a lot of soil cover. The substrate consists of calcarenite exposed outcrops and calcarenite gravels, cobbles and some boulders for the surface strewn.  There is also a lot of moss cover in the ground layer in open areas rather than bare soil. The community is heterogeneous at a sub-hectare level; there are some quite open patches and then some really dense thickets of vegetation. However, at a sub-hectare level there are a few of those open patches scattered throughout the site consistent with the surrounding communities generally corresponding to the heavier limestone sheet outcropping close to the surface where there is little soil.
location_description:
McAvoy property.
The effect of grazing is quite high - minimal tussock grasses due to kangaroos. Many scats throughout the site (no evidence of sheep). Emus also present. The site is very long unburnt with a very dense understory and no scaring on any trees. The introduced plant effect is low to moderate. The understory is dominated by some introduced grasses and forbs including Moraea sp., Melilotus indicus, Briza minor and other forbs but cover is fairly low. There was also one African boxthorn (Lycium ferocissimum) found towards the center of the site.

description: Secret Rocks. 49km south east of Kimba, 65km south west of Whyalla.
comments: Landform element and pattern is a hill slope in a sand plain. Gentle 3 degree slope down to the north west corner.  Recently burnt in Jan 2020, intense fire with most shrubs burnt, some on eastern edge less burnt. Surrounding veg also burnt, except to the NE a shrubland pocket is unburnt including the Callitris. No stock on property for 20 years. Evidence of lots of kangaroo grazing with scats, tracks and the grasses (Austrostipa and Rytidosperma) in the open are munched. Minimal impact from introduced plant species. Erigeron bonariensis and Carrichtera annua present but minimal cover.  Vegetation community is homogenous, extends about 30m to the north, 20m to the west, 40m to the east, under 100m to south, then becoming Mallee on all sides with a patch of Callitris to the NE. Nearest infrastructure is small access road about 40m NE of the NE corner. Main access road 300m to the NE.

Grazing impact is low with only a small amount of old kangaroo scat found in the plot. The plot is inside the secret rocks exclosure fenced area. description: Secret Rocks, 45km east of Kimba. 21.6km north east of Sheoak Hill
comments: Landform element and pattern is a plain on a plain with minimal slope. No surface strew or outcrop. The cryptogam crust is extensive, more than bare ground through most of the site. Minimal evidence of introduced plant species- Schismus barbatus present but very low cover.  Grazing pressure from kangaroos. Westringia rigida and grasses have been particularly effected. Goats on property but no evidence of them in plot. Very long unburnt with no evidence of scarring on trees, potentially over 100 years since last fire. Community is confined to the plot. Mallee becomes denser beyond western boundary of site. Site is largely concentrated in the Myoporum and shrubland, community extends 75m from the centre. Nearest infrastructure is the main access track to the property dam, which is 20m from the NE corner.

description: Fowler's bay CP, 5.9km west south west of Fowler's Bay. 124km west north west of Ceduna
comments: Landform element and pattern is a lake. Site is flat. Surface strew is comprised of shell grit deposited throughout the site. No outcrop.
