description: Waite Conservation Reserve, 6.8 km south east of Adelaide CBD
comments: Plot straddles sandstone ridge top. Some sandstone cobbles and gravels. Any gravels have been covered by leaf litter.  Complex slope-  Plot slope broadly to the west- 9 degrees- but steeper gully at north west corner and also to a gully running east west on west edge of the site. Flat on eastern edge on top of ridge. Walking track along ridgeline cuts through the very eastern edge of the plot. Very long unburnt- 1 big burnt tree in the middle of the site but no scarring on any of the trees. Grazing by Kangaroos and Koalas- noticeable effect of the latter on the Eucalyptus leucoxylon  subsp. leucoxylon within the site. Homogeneity-  Community is more or less contained to the plot though it does continue along the ridgeline for some distance. High impact of introduced plant species- Briza maxima high cover, Avena barbata and Trifolium campestre low cover.

description: Happy Valley Reservoir, North eastern edge of lake. 16km south south west of Adelaide GPO.
comments: Sloping plot on eastern edge of reservoir. 3 degree slope to the south west. Dominated by introduced species. Plot is bounded by access tracks at the south west and north east corners.
visit_notes: No soil samples collected, no characterisation of soil pit made at first site visit.
location_description: Sloping plot on eastern edge of reservoir. 3 degree slope to the south west. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees. Heavy grazing pressure from kangaroos. Introduced species effect is high in the ground stratum - dominated by introduced plant species. Mid stratum has some Olives but has been treated. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot- denser patches of Casuarina and Acacia paradoxa at a subsite level. Plot is bounded by access tracks at the south west and north east corners.

description: Telowie Gorge Conservation Park, 9.5km east of Port Germain. 20km north east of Port Pirie.
comments: The plot is located on the western slopes of Telowie Gorge Range. Nearest infrastructure is the western edge is about 10m in from the Western Boundary Track, but it’s no longer used and there is a fence line there. There is an old fence line that runs about length of transect EW4, but it hasn’t been used for a very long time and there is no discernible difference on either side. Surface strew is mostly cobbles with some boulders and gravel and some small course sandtone outcrops. Substrate is mostly sandstone, with some calcareous sandstone present (present in soil pit). Site was severely burnt in the 2015 Bangor fire, with the exception of the North East corner (it’s in the same community, but it seems the fire didn’t creep into the gully or the other side of the ridge). The rest of the site is regenerating. Grazing impact is low. Unsure if there are goats present, but there are kangaroos and wallabies. Introduced plant species impact is high, mostly Carrichtera annua with some Bromus rubens. Slope is relatively even to the West, it does get steeper to the North East corner where it starts to drop down into the gully to the North. The predominant slope is to the West, 17-18 degree slope steeper up the top. Just North of South West corner is an area that has possibly been cleared previously, that has largely regenerated with Sida petrophila. In terms of homogeneity, community is confined to plot. On the Northern edge it drops down into the gully where is gets thicker and is also gets into thicker scrub on the Eastern boundary up the rocky slopes. The substrate across the site is a mixture of closely cropped moss, lichen and cryptogram.

description: Yappala Indigenous Protected Area, 2.2km north east of Yappala Homestead. 8.9km east of Wild Dog Glen
comments: Site landform and pattern is a Hill slope in hills. Metamorphic sandstone outcrops through the site and surface strew of cobble ranging 20-200mm, but mostly 50-70mm. Site is long unburnt, no clear evidence of past fire. Slope is 5-6 degrees, sloping down to the North. Introduced plants species effect is moderate, quite a lot of Carrichtera annua (mostly dead) and there’s likely to be other annual not currently present. Grazing impact is moderate, presence of cattle and kangaroos on property. Site is homogenous. Community extends to the top of slope (100m South of plot) and out to the East and West 50m. Nearest infrastructure is the road 30m North of site. Yappala homestead is 2.8km South East of plot.

description: Bon Bon Station Reserve, 49 km.south south west of Homestead,12.9 km west of the Stuart Highway.
comments: Lunnette dune slope in sand plain on lake edge. Southern edge of the site is up higher onto the dune. Slopes down 5 degrees to the north east, undulating to the south east corner. Surface strew minimal but some soft gypsum outcrops spread throughout the site otherwise sandy. Grazing effect is low, Kangaroos present - Camels present in low numbers. Previously grazed by sheep, but not is last 30 years. Introduced plant species effect is minimal.  Long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees and large amount of leaf litter.  Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. Transitions on the southern edge of the plot as it becomes more sandy. Vegetation community extends along lake edge 100m east and west. Site slightly changes to more an Acacia aneura shrub land to the SW. Site is long unburnt. Nearest infrastructure is 600m NW of Old Stuart Hwy. There is an old unmaintained fence line the runs WNW through the very northern edge of plot.

Stokes Bay Station, 2.4km SSE

Introduced plant impact low, there is some Urtica urens and Lysimachia arvensis present. Grazing impact is moderate, there are quite a few macropods such as Macropus eugenii.

description: As previous
comments:
Landform and pattern, the site is in a gully in low hills. Surface strew is sandstone, quartz pebble size, small sandstone outcrop. Community is confined to plot. South of plot stand of E. cladocalyx with sparse understorey. To the North community transitions to an Allocasuarina verticillata woodland. Nearest infrastructure is a walking trail, 50m West of South West corner and then the Stokes Bay Rd 100m to the South. Evidence of fire scarring on some of the Xanthorrhoea semiplana (on the 2-3m grass trees) and Eucalyptus cladocalyx. Last fire possibly 5-8 years ago. Small sandstone outcrops present in the South West corner. There is an old fence line intersecting along the Western edge of plot.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
visit_notes: Eucalypts combined for basal wedge. Melaleucas combined for basal wedge.
location_description:
Lathami Conservation Park,  2.4km SSE Stokes Bay Station.

The site was recently burnt (~9 months prior) in the January 2020 wildfires. The impact of introduced plants is high with Arctotheca calendula dominating in the ground layer and  significant cover of Trifolium glomeratum and Galium murale with Cerastium glomeratum, Carduus tenuiflorus, Urtica urens and weedy grasses such as Vulpia bromoides, Briza minor and Aira cupaniana also present. The impact of grazing is low to moderate with evidence of macropod grazing on the grasses.

description: Parndana Conservation Park,  7.1km East South East of Pioneer Bend. 29.3km West South West of Kingscote.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Site burnt in 2020 fires. Introduced plant species effect is low with a small amount of Arctotheca calendula,  Briza minor and Cerastium glomeratum  through the site. Grazing effect is low, with some signs of Kangaroos. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is on a hills slope in low hills. There is a small gully the run long the western edge of the plot and enters the site just by the South West corner. There is a shallow gully that run through the middle North to South. The site slopes 30 degrees down to the South and plateaus out at the Northern end of the plot. Site is long unburnt, there is a lot of course woody debris, little evidence of fire, last fire about10~ years ago. Grazing impact is low but macropods present. Introduced weed impact is low. Community extends 30m North of plot, 100m West of plot 40m South of plot, doesn’t extend East of plot. Closet infrastructure in Kookaburra Track 30m North of North West corner. Sandstone surface strew present, pebble size and a small patch of outcrop North West corner.

description: 6.2km East North East of Yakilo,60.8km West South West of Kingscote.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
 Site is within the Western River Refuge’s predator proof fence constructed after the 2019/2020 summer fire. Quite a bit of quartzite surface strew.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The surface strew is more visible this visit due to the loss of leaf litter post-fire. The vegetation community is homogenous and confined to the plot.  The nearest infrastructure is an access track ~50m from the north west corner. The site is also now enclosed within a predator exclusion fence which was installed post fire. This fence also excludes macropods so the impact of grazing is minimal. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Surface structure is composed of ironstone  surface strew ranging in size from pebbles to cobble, with no outcrop, but some quartzite along the eastern side of the site. The land form and pattern around the site is complex. The slope has a spur that goes down the middle of the site with the highest point along the northern edge of the site, after winch the slope runs south at approximately 2 degrees. There is a little gully in the middle of the western edge that goes 3 degrees to west, and 2-3 degrees to the east from the crest. The closest point of infrastructure is a un-named private track which runs 70m from the NW corner of the site. The site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community confined to the plot.
visit_notes:
basal:
the eucs are mixed; obliqua and baxteri

point intercepts,
Transect SN4 points 6 & 7 have substrate charcoal
Transect N3S3 point 42 has substrate charcoal
Transect S1N1 point 36 has substrate Moss & point 82 has substrate charcoal
location_description: The time since last fire is about 10 years with the last burn in 2008. There are burn marks on all the older Eucalyptus and Xanthorrhoea, but not on any juvenile Eucalyptus. Although there is evidence of kangaroos in the form of trails and scats, the grazing impact appears to be minimal. Introduced goats and deer have been removed successfully, with one deer remaining on the property. The introduced plant species impact is also very low.

Homogeneity -  the community is confined to the plot-  vegetation begins to change as it runs down the slope.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
The site is situated on a hill crest plateau in the highest region of Kangaroo Island. NE to SE slope drops off down the plateau. The aspect is predominantly to the SE at its steepest, a 5 degree slope. The surface structure is composed of latterite surface strew ranging in size from pebbles to cobble some quartzite and sandstone rocks scattered throughout. There is some outcrop in the NE corner of the site as well. The closest point of infrastructure is the west end highway 40m from the NW corner of the site. The site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community continuing to the highway, after which there is a cleared fire break as well as this the vegetation community extends at least 100m to the north and south and 50 to the east.

description: 8.8km east of Hawks Nest, 28.7km south south west of Kingscote.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The site hasn’t been burnt since the previous visit. Grazing effect is low, with a few animal tracks through the site, but no scat visible. Minimal introduced plant  species, with scattered Arctotheca calendula, Hypochaeris glabra, Vulpia myuros f. myuros with one lone Pinus radiata cone ( probably brought in by birds) The Banksia ornata seems to be suffering some die back, but does not seem to be impacting the Banksia marginata.
Homogeneity- community extends 75m from the centre. The NW corner is 5m from the properties access track.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Surface structure is sandy with no outcrop. The land form and pattern around the site is composed of dune fields, with a slope to the east at 2 degrees, which drains into the lagoon to the east. The time since last fire is about 20 years with the last burn in the 1990's. The vegetation appears stable and to have recovered fully. Although there is evidence of kangaroos in the form of trails and scats, the grazing impact appears to be minimal. The introduced plant species impact is also extremely low. The closest point of infrastructure is a private road which runs 20m from the SW corner and 5m from the NW corner of the site. There is also a power line with runs parallel 25m from the eastern edge of the site. The site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community extending to the road on the western edge and to the power line on the eastern edge. This strip extends approximately 500m north and 200m south.
location_description: 8.8km East of Hawks Nest, 28.7km South South West of Kingscote.

description: Seal Bay Conservation Park. 41.8km east of Riverdale, 42.7km south west of Kingscote.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The introduced plant effect species is minimal- Galium murale present but low cover. Grazing is low, with some evidence of macropods. The site is long unburnt.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Surface structure and lithology: there is sand and gravel with intermittent lichen cover. A limestone outcrop intrusion runs along the western edge of the site. The land form and pattern around the site is composed of low hills but is close to flat across the site with a minimal southerly slope. The time since last fire is approximately 10 years, with the 2008 fires likely having been the most recent.There is recruitment in the Eucalyptus. Although there is evidence of kangaroos and other marsupials, the grazing impact appears to be minimal. The introduced plant species impact is also extremely low. The closest point of infrastructure is a National Park-owned road which runs east 20m parallel to the northern edge of the site. Overall, the site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community extending to the north about 20m (to the road), to the south about 200m (to a creak after which the vegetation changes) and 500 m to the west and east respectively. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
visit_notes: Eucalyptus species are combined for Basal area
location_description: Seal Bay Conservation Park. 41.8km east of Riverdale, 42.7km south west of Kingscote.

description: 16km south of Penneshaw, 31.8km south west of Kingscote.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Some weedy forbs and grasses including Avellinia festucoides, Galium murale,  Rostraria cristata, Aira cupaniana and Cerastium balearicum but cover low. Some evidence of kangaroo but grazing effect is low. Very long unburnt- some very old scars on old Mallee. Lots of fallen debris.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Surface structure is composed of limestone surface strew ranging in size from pebbles to cobble, with outcrop along the eastern side of the site. Throughout the site there is a lot of moss and cryptogam as well as litter and bare areas. The land form and pattern around the site are complex. The site is a swale in a dune field with a slope running toward the SE corner at 2 degrees. The site is long un-burned with evidence only in the form of charcoal in the soil. Although there is evidence of kangaroos in the form of trails and scats, the grazing impact appears to be minimal. The introduced plant species impact is also low. The site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community extending 30m to the west until it intercepts a track and 10m to the north.
visit_notes:
Eucalyptus species combined in Basal area obs.
Annual forb Correa sp. ( not recorded)

Eucalyptus albopurpurea ( Collected in 2018 visit) and Eucalyptus oleosa subsp. ampliata ( collected in 2020 visit) may have been miss-identified in the transects in both visits

description: Lashmar Conservation Park, 13.6km South East of Penneshaw.  19.3km South of Cape Jervis.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Surface structure is composed of mica-rich sandstone cobbles with some boulders and isolated outcropping. The site slopes about 15 degrees to the north east with gullies on the northern and western edges of the plot. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues for another 20-30m in all directions from the edges of the plot. The site is long unburnt with no visual evidence present. Hazard reduction burning has occurred the previous day to the east of the access track and plot. Track clearing has also taken place but has not intruded into the plot. The nearest infrastructure is the access track about 5m from the south east corner. Some introduced species are present including Asparagus asparagoides f. asparagoides,  Aira cupaniana and Vulpia bromoides but cover is low. The impact of grazing is very low due to the sparsity of the understorey.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Surface structure is composed of metamorphic sandstone and sandstone surface strew approximately 200mm in diameter, with some outcrop. The site is mostly covered with litter, but pockets of cryptogram persist. The site has an 15 - 20 degree slope to the NE corner, with gullies on both the northern and western edges. The time since last fire is indeterminable, with no visual evidence present. There is evidence of macropods in the form of trails and scats, but the grazing impact appears to be low. The introduced plant species impact is moderate, with Asparagus asparagoides being very common and at risk of out-competing other plants to a significant extent if not controlled. The closest point of infrastructure is an un-named old track which runs 5m west from the SW corner of the site. The site is homogeneous, with the vegetation community confined to the plot. There are termite and ant mounts present.
location_description: 13.6km South East of Penneshaw,  19.3km South of Cape Jervis.

description: 18.8km south south east of Penneshaw, 32.5km south south west of Cape Jervis.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
There is a drainage line along the western edge with Melaleuca lanceolata. Site is long unburnt, with no indication of any fire.Introduced species effect moderate- Sonchus oleraceus common with some Lysimachia arvensis in the drainage line. Galium murale, Melilotus indicus and Rostraria cristata are also present.
Minimal grazing impact, with some evidence of kangaroos.Slope and aspect,- a slope to the south/south west at a 10 degree angle, but undulating through the site. The closest infrastructure is an access road 15m to the left of the SE corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Surface structure and lithology:obble and outcrop perched on an underlying limestone sheet. The land form and pattern is composed of a dune slope in a dune field with a slope of 10-12 degrees in a southerly direction (approx. 190 degrees). A gully cuts through the western boundary of the site where the same species dominate but grow higher, enabling forbs to proliferate under their canopies. There is negligible grazing impact. Few introduced species are present, with the possible exception of introduced grasses and daisies. There is limited evidence of past fire, suggesting the site has been unburnt for at least 30 years. However, die-back is evident in the dominant mid stratum with some dead old-growth Eucayptus. The closest point of infrastructure is a private track which runs along the eastern boundary of the site. The south east corner is about 15 metres to the west of the road. Overall, the site is homogeneous with the vegetation community extending past the track to the east for approximately 200 m, to the south for approximately 100 m, to the west approximately 150 m but ends approximately 10 metres beyond the crest of the northern end of the site.

description: Kangaroo Island. 11.1km south west of Snug Cove. 8.2km west north west of Yakilo. De Mole River Catchment - private bushland area in partnership with Australian Wildlife Conservancy and Kangaroo Island Land for Wildlife.
comments:
ONLY SW point coordinate. FOLLOW UP OTHER SITE POINTS

The site is a plain, with some undulation, on a plateau. There is a slight 1 degree slope to the south (aspect 180 degrees). There is some ferricrete (ironstone) pebble-sized surface strew apparent. The site is very long unburnt, with the last fire in the 1950s. The impact of grazing is low but there is disturbance from echidnas with diggings present throughout the site. Possibly goanna diggings as well. Indtroduced plant effect is low.  There are some scattered individuals of Arctotheca calendula, Romulea sp. and Hypochaeris glabra throughout the site, but overall the cover is low. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues 85m from the centre of the plot in all directions. There is a creek further to the south beyond the plot. The nearest infrastructure is 30m from the north west corner and is an access track which follows the boundary of cleared cropping area.

description: Yalata IPA, 7.7km south east of Nundroo
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element is a plain. Vegetation community is mainly confined to the plot, and extends 50m east, 10m north, 10m south, and 0m west. Beyond the north west edge ground slopes upwards to a low rise, grass cover is sparser and Carrichtera annua more abundant. No outcrop, but there is a small amount of pebble sized surface strew, calcareous/limestone origin, possibly dug up by wombats over time. Site is long unburnt. Current grazing pressure is very low on tussock grasses. Palatable chenopods (Maireana sp. and/or Enchylaena sp.) are very heavily browsed, but are resprouting. Grazing is by wombats and kangaroos, property previously also stocked sheep. Some wombat diggings are present at the edge of the south west corner, with others further up the slope to the west and north west of the site. Introduced plant species dominated by mainly dried-off Carrichtera annua from last season, and Marrubium vulgare, limited to around wombat diggings. Nearest infrastructure is a property access track approximately 5m East from the SE corner.

comments: Big Toolunka- Mid Plot. Plot is on a swamp on a low lying island with the main channel of the Murray river to the south and an older channel forming a billabong to the north.  Site is more or less flat with some small rises through the site and the south west corner rising up to the levee of the main channel of the river. Plot is patchy at a site level with bands of Duma florulenta and Eucalyptus largiflorens alternating through the site. Some evidence of pigs. Surface strew minimal- lots of leaf litter. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species minimal- some Sonchus and other forbs but cover is low.

description: Murray River National Park, Katarapko Island
comments:
Landform element and pattern is a levee on a floodplain, being on the bank adjacent the main channel of the River Murray. No surface strew or outcrop present, however there is a lot of coarse woody debris throughout. There are undulations within the site but overall it is flat, with no discernible slope. Site is homogeneous to the extent of the plot. To the north vegetation cover becomes, particularly cover of Acacia stenophylla.
Nearest infrastructure is "the splash regulator" 2.7km to the west of the site on the other side of katarapko island or a track 200m to the south on the other side of the river.
location_description: Some evidence of woodcutting, both older and more recent (chainsaw oil can found on site). Grazing impact is limited to kangaroos. Introduced plant species impact is relatively low, limited to weedy forbs. No evidence of fire, site is long unburnt. Nearby fire 14/01/2014.

description: Hamilton Station. 177km south east of Kulgera. Just west of western boundary of Witjira National Park. Drive along fence from boundary gate.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is plain on alluvial plain. Surface strew across 20% of the site, particularly in creek line and depressions. Strew lithology of sandstone, ironstone and quartzite (3-5cm). The site is homogenous, community extends from the centre 70m to the north, 300+m east, 100m south (creek line with gidgee), and 200m west towards floodplains. 
 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
visit_notes: Primary Genetic barcode SAA 000342 recorded in both SAASTP0001 and SAASTP0002, it was only found in the SAASTP0002 leaf tissue box. Have removed SAA 000342 associated with Veg Barcode SAA 000341 from this visit.
location_description: Introduced plant impact is minimal-moderate with Malvastrum americanum and Lepidium sp. scattered through the site. Grazing impact is low, site is on a station so there are some cow pats but grazing evidence is limited. Site is long unburnt.

Site is homogenous and extends; north 200m, east 100m, south 50m, west 150m. Nearest infrastructure is the Mount Dare Rd 400m north of NW corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
location_description: Introduced plant impact is low, Malvastrum americanum present. Grazing impact is minimal, evidence of old cow pats. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Two main channels that pass through the plot along the northern and southern edges.

location_description: Grazing impact is minimal. Introduced plant impact in low with some Lepidium sp. (check species list). Site is long unburnt.

description: Witjira National Park. Finke River Channels. 217km East South East of Kulgera
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element is a plain and the pattern is an alluvial plain. There is no outcrop or surface strew present in the plot. There are some areas of cracking clay with quite deep and wide cracks, and some surface flaking is present. The site is homogenous, and the community is confined to the plot; 100m south and east the community changes to Coolibah and Acacia trees along a creek line. The community ends at the western edge of the plot and becomes mainly bare soil for 300m, and the community extends 200m to the north. The nearest infrastructure is the access track 80m from the northwest corner of the plot. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site located just west of creek channel and south of track with dam and yards approximately 660 m. to the North East . Irregular quadrat layout .
location_description: Impact of introduced plants is minimal, though there is some Malvastrum americanum scattered through the site. Grazing impact is minimal; there are some cattle scats in the plot, but they may have been deposited in a flooding event. There is no evidence of a fire having ever burned through the plot.

The nearest infrastructure is an access track 50m south of SW corner.

Introduced plant impact is low, some introduced malvastrum sp. and lepidium sp. in site. Check the species list. The site is long unburnt.

description: Gibber Plain 10 km NE Dalhousie Springs. 132km South East of Finke Community
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------

The landform element is a rise/slope, the pattern is rises. Site slopes towards the western edge. There is no outcrop in the site, but surface strew of ironstone gravel (3-5cm) is scattered across the site in patches (about 50% cover). There are some larger rocks (10-15cm) of the same material scattered more sparsely through the site. he site is homogenous but there are gullies close to both the northern and southern edges of the plot which have more dense vegetation cover. The community extends to the west 100m before hitting another gully and continues 200m to the east. The nearest infrastructure is the Pernie Bore Track 300m north of the NE corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site located on west facing slope adjacent to Acacia cambagei drainage line. ( approximately 200m. To the west)  Site is low Blue bush slope/rise with stony surface ( crusted-sealed) finer pebble. On calcareous sandy loam gibber plain, intersected by Acacia lined drainage channels.
location_description: No introduced plant species were found in the site; grazing impact is low but there are some old cattle pads tracking through the site and some of the Maireanas appear to have been grazed in the past. No evidence of recent fire in the site.

description: Arckaringa Station, 91km east north east of Cadney Park Roadhouse. Off Oodnadatta Highway, 20km to Goorikiana Dam to Ambitious Dam, then 5.5 km to plateau.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Long unburnt- country unlikely to carry a fire. Site is grazed but impact is low, some scats in the site. No introduced plant species recorded. Homogeneity- 200m in all directions is same community. 200m to old track is closest infrastructure.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Land form element and pattern is a stony plain on a gibber tableland. No outcrop. Surface strew is small gravel size up to rocks of 25cm. Mostly very dense, forming a gibber pavement across 60% of the site. Ironstone and silcrete present. Other areas have very soft puffy cracking clay with little vegetation cover. Little to no introduced plant impact. Grazing impact is low. Cattle have travelled through the site, but no current grazing on Astrebla pectinate or Panicum decompositum. No evidence of past fire, there are no trees on the site to show scarring. Site is homogenous, and community extends at least 300m north, east and west beyond the site. To the south after 400m the slope drops away into more of a breakaway, supporting mulga and eremophila, with rocky outcrop on the surface. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 120m south west of the SW corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------

description: Mumpy
comments:

Land form element and pattern is a dune crest in a shallow dune field, Site is flat overall, with minor sandy undulations throughout. It slopes away at both the eastern and western ends, off the dune and into the gibber plain. No surface strew, but one large ironstone/silcrete boulder has been brought in to the site. No outcrop. Community is confined to the plot. Nearest infrastructure is a station access track 50m from the southern edge of the plot.

description: mumpy, Northern dune site
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Isolated low dune crest, not part of a dune field, with gibber plains either side. Some undulations within the site (sand mounds of 0.3-0.4m around Zygochloa hummocks) but overall relatively flat. Middle of the site has a lot of rocky strew, which appear to include chippings.  Generally homogeneous. Nearest infrastructure is a track which bisects the site along the southern edge, approximately 10m inside the southwest corner. It is either a shot line or pipeline, and has been created since the last visit. It is infrequently used and is regenerating. Previously the road 100m to the southwest of the site was nearest.
 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is on narrow dunefield running north-south, with gibber plain to east and west. Site is homogeneous.
visit_notes: LAI not collected.
location_description: Site is long unburned with no evidence of past fire. Minimal introduced plant species impact, though there is a small amount of Cenchrus ciliaris present. There is some grazing impact, though no cattle around at the time of the visit. Rabbit burrows and scat are also on site. Acacia ligulata and Acacia oswaldii were recorded on the previous visit but no longer appear to be present.

description: mumpy gibber
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Land surface element and pattern is plain on a plain. Site has a 1-degree slope to the north. Surface strew is mainly gravel, with some cobbles, comprising gibber, though not true smooth ironstone gibber, and not forming a gibber pavement. Some quartzite and a mix of other rock types across the site. Site is heterogeneous, with the eastern side more dominated by gibber, and vegetation is sparser. Western edge has more of a sandy overlay and a drainage line running to the south east, and vegetation has more Maireana aphylla and salsola. The gibber community extends a long way east of the plot. Nearest infrastructure is the station access track 10m from the SE corner.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Calcareous plain with gibber and bare ground.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measure. LAI not measured.
location_description: Site is long unburnt, with minimal introduced species. Site is grazed, with old cattle dung present, though little current grazing impact.

description: Bon Bon Station Reserve, 10.9km north west of Bon Bon Homestead. 61km north north east of Kingoonya.
comments:

Landform element and pattern is plain on plain with no discernable slope. Extends from centre picket 250m north, 100m east and transitions into a mulga creek line community 80m to the south, 60m to the west. Flat gibber plain with no rock outcrops. Gibber/ironstone surface strew 2-10mm (buckshot) even across whole plot with siltstone and quartzite. Site is homogenous, although the SW corner does encroach upon a drainage line.

description: Calperum Station, 5.4km north east of Calperum homestead, 0.6km south east of Rotten Lake
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern – refer previous visit. Site is located on a rise, sloping away beyond the boundaries of site to the north, west and the south. Not too much slope within the site itself, 1 degree at most. Aspect is to the north or north west, though the last 20m on the southern side is sloping to the south at 2-3 degrees. No surface strew or outcrop. Surface is clayey, with very good cryptogamic crust over large areas. The southern edge is overlaid with blown in red sand. Some bare areas are present, often in conjunction with large Maireana pyramidata shrubs. Nearest infrastructure is the Pipeline Track, running almost parallel with the western boundary and 10m from the NW corner, and Renmark-Wentworth Road, approximately 70m from the SE corner. The site is mostly homogeneous, except for the south east corner where the aspect and soil surface are slightly different. This area displays a much higher plant species diversity that the rest of the site. The plant community extends 100m from the centre of the plot to the west, north and the east, but to the south it only extends 75m, and less in the SE corner. 

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Plain- slightly elevated  from the main Murray river floodplain. Slightly undulating site- mounds around Maireana and Enchylaena but flat overall. Minimal surface strew- likely Calcareous deeper down. Lots of cryptogam crust. Homogeneity- 75m to the closet road. 100m in all directions is the same community.
visit_notes: Re-visit sampled veg and point intercept.
location_description: Calperum Station. 5.3km north east of homestead. 20km north of Renmark

description: Calperum Station, 2.7km north north east of Calperum homestead, 17.7km north north west of Renmark
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern – south east facing hillslope, between the road and Lake Woolpoolool. Slope approximately 2 degrees, with gentle undulations throughout the site. Slightly hummocked around some Maireana shrubs, likely due to historic soil drift due to low plant cover. No outcrop or surface strew. Slightly sandy surface, with extensive cryptogamic cover. Site is homogenous 75m from the centre. North west of the site adjacent the road there is more large shrub cover due to the change in drainage. To the south east the landscape flattens out towards Lake Woolpoolool. Nearest infrastructure is the Wentworth-Renmark Road, 40m north west of the NW corner, and a fenceline 10m to the south east of the SE corner. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Plot is on gentle slope rising up from the  main river flood plain. 3 degree slope to the south east.  Homogeneity- plot is homogenous. 80m from the centre to the north east is a drainage channel (manmade) from  the road. Main road is just to the north of that. Minimal surface strew and no outcrop. Lots of Cryptogam crust and lots of leaf litter- dead Carrichtera annua and other annual forbs.
visit_notes: Revisit.  Soil pit sampled but subsite soil and Metagenomic samples not collected.

description: Calperum Station 1km west of office and about 20kms northwest of Renmark.
comments: On a sand dune with slope generally to south and north. No evidence of fire, some signs of rabbits, no weeds. Site is not homogeneous - northern side (about 20% of site) runs into  swale of Maireana in a pan. Site is a Callitris rehabilitation site. Site has two photo points. One in centre (photos) and one near northeast corner (photo points and laser scan). Minimal impact of introduced plant species- Schismus barbatus and Carrichtera annua present.
location_description: Shrubland of Dodonaea viscosa with Callitris  and mid layer of Maireana pyramidata, Rhagodia sp and Olearia sp on sand ridge. Calperum Station 1km west of office and about 20kms morthwest of Renmark.

description: Calperum Station. 9.3km north of homestead.24km north of Renmark
comments: Swale in low dunefield. Very gentle slope to the north. Northern edge is just on the edge of dune slope. Fire- south east corner was burnt in January 2014. Rest of the site is long unburnt. Fire has come in 30m at the south east corner. Some scattered surface strew- limestone but low cover. Introduced plant effect is minimal- none noted. Homogeneity- community is contained to the plot at the moment due to effect of fire. Some Eucalyptus gracilis close to the road have been cut for timber but have long regenerated.

description: Mudla Wirra Reserve (Pengilly Scrub), 5.7km north west of Roseworthy. 11.3km north north west of Gawler
comments: Comment from 28/10/2014 - Homogeneous site except small part of northeast corner that drops into the dune swale. The reserve is small (c.2ha) and surrounded by cropping land. No obvious impact from fire or ferals but some evidence (old warrens) of past rabbit impact. Weeds are prominent in ground layer especially Asparagus asparagoides and control program is evident (signage, markers). Site is on dune crest with slope to northeast, east and southwest. Comment from 25/09/2018 - Site is located at Pengilly Scrub. 11km north west of Gawler, 48km north north east of Adelaide. The land was bequeathed to the council 1968 and in 1988, the site had a conservation covenant placed over it. The site has had a fair bit of weeding done to it with the plot situated in the “less good” part of the site. The northern edge is much better in terms of remnant vegetation and native grasses but plot site was chosen due to homogeneity. Site was significantly burnt in the 2015 Pinery fire but has recovered quickly with 25 new species new regenerating, including some thought to be on way out, Westringia, Dodonaea bursariifolia, along the northern edge. Some selective herbicide use to control bridal creeper. Weed impact is high- Avena, Bromus, Asparagus asparagoides, Brassica, Oxalis pes-caprae. Grazing impact medium- hares, kangaroos. Slope and aspect-v complicated slope to north and south. Substrate is sand. Community is confined to plot
location_description: Pengilly Scrub. 11km north west of Gawler, 48km north north east of Adelaide

description: Clements Gap Conservation Park. 920m north west of old Clements Gap school house. North east of Port Broughton, SA.
comments:
Comment from 30/10/2014  Sandplain.  Homogeneous site, community extends >300m beyond site, apart from road to the south. Some disturbance - old track through site, metal waste, weed Carrichtera annua common. No evidence of feral animals or fire.
Comment from 12/09/2018 -  Site was previously set aside as a woodland reserve for farmers to collect wood and use as a dumping ground up until 1960’s. Hasn’t been burnt since then. Grazing minimal- kangaroos. Introduced species impact minimal- Carrichtera annua throughout site. Site is flat with no outcrop. Limestone underneath. Homogeneity- Community extends about 2km south, 1kmwest and north and 300m east. Site located 100m in from main road plus an old track to SW corner. Site located at Clements Gap Conservation Park. 920m North West of old Clements Gap school house. North east of Port Broughton, SA

Nearest infrastructure, Heysen Trail which follows the ridge, 10m from the North West corner moving away from the site. Grazing impact low, kangaroos. Scattered through the site are some Eucalyptus baxteri which have been previously cut and have coppiced.

description: Brachina Gorge Heysen Range Lower. 63km North North East of Adelaide
comments: Grazing impact high- goat tracks and droppings. Rabbit droppings also. Lots of Yellow footed rock wallabies close to the site.  Long unburnt- not much grass to carry fire. Overnight rain. Cheilanthes sieberi subsp. sieberi opening up. Slope uneven, 17- 18 degree slope to the south west.  South west corner almost in creek. Another creek running along southern edge of quadrat. Bottom transect on southern boundary goes through this gully. Weed impact low- some Carrichtera annua. Rocky on the surface, moss where there would be bare ground. Some outcrop at the top of the site. Steep slope on the mid reaches of the Brachina gorge catchment. Very rocky, soil sampling stopped by rock at most sub sites.

description: Warraweena Reserve, side slopes of Mt Hack. 15.3km east of Warraweena Homstead. 37.9km east of Beltana
comments:
Comment from 21/08/2012 visit - On the slope of Mt hack escarpment.  Site heavily grazed. Goat scats and tracks throughout plot. Long unburnt- no scarring on Mallee.  Rocks to 10-15 cm in strew. Top section has a little outcrop. Not much strew bigger than 30cm. Slope to the south but also slightly convex- east to west. Weed impact minimal.
Comment from 21/08/2018 Surface strew is sandstone, as is outcrop. Slope and aspect, the southern edge is flatter increase in slope towards the northern edge up to a 5o slope. Overall aspect is southerly, it does dip away slightly to the south western corner. Site is long unburnt. Introduced species is same a previous visit. Grazing impact is similar to previous visit, moderately grazed by goats and kangaroos.
visit_notes: Site too rocky to get below 10cm soil subsite sampling. No pit or bulk density sampling.
location_description: Waraweena.  Mount Hack. 38km East of Beltana

description: Dutchman's Stern Conservation Park. 7.8km north west of Quorn.
comments:
Close to top of Dutchman"s Stern ridge. Western boundary of quadrat close to ridgetop hiking track. Slope from the north west to the south east. Grazing impact low. Eucalyptus cladocalyx recovering from drought. Dead material in the tops of the canopy. Weed impact low.

AS previous. Site located on hillslope, on Dutchman’s Stern. 25 degree slope with a South Eastern aspect. The NW corner is adjacent to the ridgetop track. Site is unburnt since previous visit. Grazing impact- minimal, kangaroos and goats. Introduced species impact low- Hypochaeris, on area closer to track. Substrate is coarse grain sandstone, not metamorphose. Same or outcrop, which is mainly covered in lichen. Site is Dutchman's Stern Conservation Park. 7.8km north west of Quorn. Homogeneity- Community basically confined to plot. It stops at the northern edge where it drops off the other side of the ridgeline. There is a track at the NW corner along the ridge but closest main track is 600m west from centre of plot and hikers cabin 2km NE.

description: Battery Ridge.Mount Remarkable National Park. 10km North North West of Melrose
comments:
Lower slopes of track leading up to battery ridge. Stony- not much grass cover. Most stones covered in lichen to around 10-15cm. Tracks through the site- probably from kangaroos rather than goats (pers. com with rangers) Fairly long unburnt 5+ years. Slope to creek on southern boundary. Homogenous- northern edge grading into a Casuarina woodland. Eastern boundary is track. To west the community extends a further 50m. Erosion low. Weed impact moderate- Carrichtera annua and Lycium ferocissimum present
No soil pit samples taken due to rock substrate. Metagenomic samples were collected.

description: Radium ridge. Arkaroola station.10.3km north of Arkaroola village.
comments: Slope and aspect 30-40o, two gullies converge at the North East corner, One come down from the south west and one from southeast. Community is relatively extensive, it extends up to the top of the ridge, a little bit more Eucalyptus flindersii on the rockier areas but Triodia irritans trends to dominate. Southwest corner is just next an old disused track that runs along the top of the ridge. Site is long unburnt. Minimal impact of introduced plant species. Minimal grazing impact, euros and possibly goats.

Substrate- Sandstone outcrop with cobbles of sandstone. 15.7km north west of Balcanoona homestead. 15.6km south west of Arkaroola Village. Track 1km to the east. Homogeneity largely confined to plot, starts to thicken as It goes down hill slope

description: Gammon Ranges National Park. 16km north west of Balcanoona homestead. 15km south west of Arkaroola village.
comments: Homogeneity- site is more or less contained. North west corner opens up into Triodia hummock grassland while eastern edge grades into a Callitris glaucophylla. Mix of cobbles and boulders- larger rocks covered with lichen. Site is slightly convex- curving slightly at south east. Some forbs flowering through site, Grazing effect low- goats and possibly some cattle, scats seen. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees. Introduced species effect minimal- some Sonchus oleraceus
visit_notes:
Two mallee species combined for basal wedge. entered as euc intertexta ( mallee form) ( voucher SAT 001784) but includes Eucalyptus dumosa ( voucher SAT 001854) also. 
Younger mallee form Eucalyptus intertexta ( voucher SAT 001784) sometimes difficult to separate from Eucalyptus dumosa ( voucher SAT 001854)
location_description: Gammon Ranges National Park. 16km north west of Balcanoona Homestead. 15km south west of Arkaroola village.

description: Vulkathunha-Gammon Ranges National Park, 9.2km east south east of Nepubunna. 62.5km east of Copley
comments: South Facing slope up to base of low range of hills. Lithology- mix of limestone and dolomite. Grazing effect moderate- Goats and rabbits. Site long unburnt- little grass to carry fire and shrubs spread widely. Weed effect- moderate- Carrichtera annua dominates ground layer although cover is sparse.
location_description: Grazing effect moderate- Goats and rabbits. Site long unburnt- little grass to carry fire and shrubs spread widely. Weed effect- moderate- Carrichtera annua dominates ground layer though cover sparse.DEWNR photopoint # 11731    Shallow drainage lines <20cm. Deep from SW corner. Gentle relief 1-2 m across site. Coarse frags: Abundance: 2. Size:1-2, Shape:R-S. No outcrop. Primarily limestone and dolomite.

location_description: Site is mostly unchanged since previous visit with the exemption of the Zygophyllum aurantiacum subsp. verticillatum which population has dropped significantly. Community is mostly confined to the plot extending only 20m beyond plot. Long unburnt. Grazing impact moderate, kangaroos, goats and horse. Surface strew is calcareous mudstone. Slope is 30 to the South.

description:
Warraweena Reserve, 5.6km north north west of homestead. 17.5km north west of Beltana.
Warraweena.
comments: Very gently north sloping site. Mixed lithology and some other wash from further up the hill slope. Also some dolomite below surface. Mostly pebbles with some cobbles. Site long unburnt. Weed effect moderate to high- Carrichtera annua dominant ground layer as well some other annual weeds. Grazing effect is moderate- some cattle as well as goats and kangaroos. Light rain in morning of site visit as well as some other recent rain.
visit_notes: Pit to 65cm., auger to 100cm. DEWNR photopoint tag # 11730, marked SATFLB0024 in SW corner. No outcrop; coarse frags size 2. Dolomite , limestone, quartzite, shape variable. Flood plain abutting creek. No recent flooding.
location_description: Warraweena Reserve, 5.6km north north west of homestead. 17.5km north west of Beltana

location_description: Site situated on an alluvial plain located 5.6km North West of homestead and 17.5km North West of Beltana. Surface strew- sandstone, calcareous mudstone. Homogeneity- Community more or less confined to plot. There is a creek bed that sits at the NE corner where the community changes as well as a channel not far from the western edge which changes the community. The southern edge sits along the main track where the community stops. Grazing impact low-kangaroos, goats. Introduced species- Carrichtera annua, impact low as mostly died off.

description: Warraweena Reserve, 1.8km south south west of homestead.30.6 km south east of Leigh Creek
comments: Slope is broadly to the south east getting steeper on northern edge of the site. Light rain previous day as well as other recent rain.  Weed effect moderate to high- some thick patches of wards weed and consistent through the site. Some other weedy annual forbs. Grazing effect- low. Some goats through the site. Fire- site long unburnt. No evidence of scaring on trees/ ash on ground. Lithology mostly pebbles- sandstone but some quartzite as well. Some small patches of sandstone outcrop with lichen cover.
visit_notes: Site has casuarina occuring as both tree and shrub.

description: Ridgetop in Montacute Conservation Park, 17kms east of Adelaide.
comments: Steep, Mountainous site. Long unburnt- some old scarring on trunks. Fire close by more recently ( over ridge top) Introduced plant effect is moderate- includes Senecio pterophorus, Genista monspessulana and Briza maxima. Rubus sp. also- more dense in south eastern corner in gully. 45-35 degree slope- varies somewhat through the site. Some boulders and outcrop- check soil sheet for lithology. Grazing effect- some from goats and deer. Tracks and scats within the site.
location_description: Ridgetop in Montacute Conservation Park, 17kms east of Adelaide.

location_description: Site is situated 17km east of Adelaide on ridgetop in Montacute Conservation Park on a mountain landform with hillslope element. Slope is 45 degrees with an aspect of 180 degrees. Outcrop of sandstone with sandstone surface strew of cobble size. Long unburnt, not burn since previous visit. Grazing pressure- moderate, goats. Introduced species- moderate. Rubus sp., Senecio pterophorus Briza maxima, Briza minor, Pinus halepensis, Avena barbata. Homogeneity- band of Acacia pycnantha running along eastern edge of plot. Site straddles creek line with different communities. Community extends 150m west and south from centre of plot. Closest infrastructure is ridge top track at northern edge of plot. Ridgetop in Montacute Conservation Park, 17kms east of Adelaide.

description: as previous
comments:

Plot burnt earlier in the year. Kangaroo grazing however impact is low. High weed impact. Landform element and pattern unchanged since last visit.  Vegetation community is confined to plot. Olives have been poisoned but are resprouting. Homogeneity- site is contained. Drops into the valley at the south east and north east corner of the plot. Track runs just past the south west corner of the plot.

description: Pedler Heritage Block. 5.1km north west of Yacka.
comments: Tall shrubland of Allocasuarina verticillata and Eucalyptus odorata on low hills with numerous gullies. Unburnt since 1960s (Lyn Pedler pers comm, the owner). Evidence of rabbits on site. Ground layer weeds common e.g. grasses, salvia. Not grazed. Remnant vegetation, fenced from grazing. Relatively homogeneous >70m. Site of SA Govt Biological Monitoring photopoint.

description: Mt Billy Conservation Park. 145m west of Hindmarsh tiers road 10.5km north north west of Victor harbour
comments: Mt Billy Conservation Park, 10kms north of Victor Harbour. Eucalyptus leucoxylon woodland on east facing hill slope. No evidence of fire or feral grazing. Substrate dominated by litter and cryptogam. Tree stumps present indicate some past logging but no recent activity. Site is homogeneous, extends  >200m north, south and west. Road to the east. Eucalyptus fasciculosa is more prominent off the site to the west. Old, used track runs through western side of plot. Fallen timber, logs, woody debris common. Moderate impact of introduced species- Vulpia sp. moderate cover.

description: Mount Beevor, About 8kms southeast of Mount Torrens.
comments: Remnant vegetation on private property. Site is on a 12 degree slope to the North east. Shallow gully through the middle of the site. Site was burnt 10 years ago ( according to landholder) Has recovered well- most trees have regenerated. Grazing effect is low- herd of Kangaroos living in patch. Introduced species effect is moderate- some introduced grasses and some Senecio quadridentatus. Some cobbles in a few places- check soil sheet for lithology.

description: Ben Lomond National Park. 1.4km South of Ben Lomond Village. 11.5km East of English Town.
comments: Landform element and pattern. Site is on a hill crest in mountains. Aspect, site is relatively flat, but does slope >1 degree to the North and South. Lithology, there is a lot of dolerite outcrop and boulders, with some gravel. Site is long unburnt, no evidence of past fire. Grazing impact is low, wallaby and wombat scats present. Introduce plant impact is minimal. The site is homogenous and the community does extend 100m East, 60m North, 60m South and changes into a heathland to the west of plot. Nearest major infrastructure is Ben Lomond Alpine Village 1.4km North of plot. The Little Hell Circuit pole line is 100m NE of NE corner.

description: Liawenee Moor. 2.9km south south east of Liawenee, 44.8km south of Deloraine.
comments: Landform element and pattern is a plain within a plateau. Site is on a slight rise with <1degree slope  away to the East and West of site. description: Silver Plains. 32.7km north north east of Bothwell, 30km north west of Oatlands.
comments: Landform and pattern is plain in low hills. Site slopes to south south west ~1 degree. Lithology, some dolerite outcrop along southern and western edges. Site is long unburnt, although fire scars of nearby tree 5-10years?. Grazing impact is high, lots of wallaby and wombat scat. Introduced plant impact is moderate, high cover of Leontodon saxatilis, Anthoxanthum odoratum  and Holcus lanatus. Aira praecox and Trifolium campestre also present.  Site is homogeneous, becoming more swampy south of plot. Community extends 200m North, 80m east, 50m west, 300m south. Nearest infrastructure is a Flux tower 20 north of north east  corner and access track 500m east of south east corner.

description: Tom Gibson Nature Reserve, 22.6km north north west of Campbell Town. 42.3km south east of Launceston
comments: Long unburnt, no recent scarring only very old scaring on older trees and stumps. Site has been logged previously, unsure of how extensive i.e. clear felled or selectively logged. Evidence of logging seen in the number of regenerating stems and large amount of coarse woody debris. Grazing pressure high and largely from kangaroos with a distinct browse line apparent on the banksias, sparse grass in mid-layer and distinct pads through site. Some diggings are also present and could be rabbits or bandicoots. The Eucalyptus woodland community is consistent at least 90 m extending out from centre of the plot. The site is approximately 30 m in from the main access track through the park. In terms of surface strew, there is a lot of leaf litter and coarse woody debris but also just below the surface there are small circular fragments, unconsolidated alluvial, colluvial and talus deposits.
visit_notes: Tom Gibson Nature Reserve, 42.3km south east of Launceston

description: 6.9km west south west of Ross. 73.9km south south east of Launceston
comments: Plot sits on the slope of a low hill with a shallow drainage line running past the south west corner.  Large amounts of course woody debris from dead trees within the site. Grazing effect is moderate- paddock has historically been grazed by stock in low numbers? . Introduced plant effect is moderate- check herb Ids for grasses. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot as the plot forms a denser woodland in a mosaic of open grassland and woodland patches. The nearsest infrastructure is a fence 450m to the west of the plot.
visit_notes: all cryptogam substrates for this site are 'lichen on rock'. Should be 5 all up.

description: 5km West south west of Ross. 79.9km south east of Launceston
comments: The vegetation community is confined to the plot, about 75 m from the centre. The north-east corner is a few metres in from an access track while the southern edge is about 10-15 m in from a rarely-used track that runs up the ridge. The site is situated on a spur or hill crest as the site is almost on the ridge capping. The slope through the middle is about 6-7 degrees with a north easterly aspect. On the northern edge the slope is a little bit steeper at ~8 degrees and tends towards the south east. The site has been disturbed in the past with some timber cutting, unknown as to whether it has been clear felled or not, but there has definitely been some logs cut possibly for firewood. Regenerating. About 30 m north is a mudstone quarry. The site has been set back from the quarry while still capturing the underlying mudstone lithology. Surface strew is sparse with some gravels and cobbles, however, the lithology is predominantly mudstone with some finer grained sandstones. Very long unburnt. One big dead old stump potentially burnt but no recent scarring. Site situated in a conservation covenant – just over the fence the land is more formally grazed. Grazing pressure is high from kangaroos and deer
visit_notes: Transect East to West 5, point 88 substrate is 'lichen on rock'.
location_description: 5km West south west of Ross. 79.9km south east of Launceston

description: 8.9km north of Campbell Town. 53.7km south east of Launceston
comments: The site is flat with the landform element and pattern being a plain. The site is long unburnt with no sign of scorch marks. Timber has been cut in the past likely for firewood and there is a fair amount of coarse woody debris. In terms of surface strew, there is a small amount of cobble sized particles but the substrate is mostly moss and leaf litter. The effect of introduced species is minimal with some Aira present. Grazing is also minimal with a few deer and cattle scats evident but these are over a year old. The nearest structure is a vehicle track about 20-30 m northwest of north east corner and the community is fairly homogenous and extends in all directions for at least 100m from the centre.

description: 17.1km north east of Campbell Town. 56km south east of Launceston
comments: The site is grassland on a hill crest with the landform pattern being hills. The site slopes around 7 degrees to the east with an aspect of 180 degrees. The underlying rock outcrops in several places and there are large rocks and boulders strewn throughout the site. The predominant rock type is dolerite, although there may be some underlying basalt. The nearest infrastructure is the dirt road used to access the site which is approximately 800m to the east of the site. The vegetation community is relatively homogenous and continues in a mosaic pattern (i.e. grassland is interspersed with woodland patches) to the south west and east of the plot. The site has been long unburnt. There is some evidence of fire scarring on older dead trees but none of the living trees show fire scars. The impact of introduced plants is minimal, although there is some Aira and boxthorn present. Grazing is moderate.

description: 5km south east of Ross. 78.4km south east of Launceston.
comments: The site is positioned on a hill slope in a broader landform pattern of low hills. The site slopes 4 degrees to the north east. The nearest infrastructure is an old fence line which is still intact and is situated about 25m from the south west corner. There is also an access track to the nearby dam which is 20m from the north-west corner. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues about 100m along the ridge to the west. The north eastern corner comes down onto the lower slope so the vegetation community changes ~75m from the centre of the plot. The site is long unburnt although there has been patch burning in adjacent areas is recent years. The site is moderately grazed, mostly from native species including wombats and wallabies (active burrows, presence of scats), and the site has likely been grazed by sheep in the past. The ground layer is largely dominated by introduced grasses such as bromus, as well as introduced forbs including Trifolium, Hypercaeris and Cirsium vulgare.

location_description: 5.3km south east of Ross. 78.4km south east of Launceston.

description: Alpine National Park, 5.1 km south of Falls Creek.
comments:
Plot is on a gently sloping plain, 4 degrees to the west sitting on the broader high plains. No outcrop in site but close by is Gneiss. Some very small patches of fine gravels, also likely to have Gneiss in plot. Introduced plant species effect is minimal, some Trisetum spicatum present and some weedy annual forbs. Un-grazed since cattle removed in 2005 but deer increasing. Very long unburnt. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot. North east corner is 15m from Bogong High Plains Road. Western edge is grading more into a grassland.  Corresponds to LTERN Plot: Cope hut unburnt grassland.
some very small patches of fine gravels, likely Gneiss.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 5.1 km south of Falls Creek.

description: Alpine National Park,5.7km south of Falls Creek.
comments: Gently sloping ( 2 degrees) plain from the north to south. A few minor low rocky outcrops of gneiss, one very small quartzite outcrop and a  few very small patches of Gneiss gravels in bare patches.  Very long unburnt. Cattle removed in 2005 but deer increasing more broadly. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community is confined to the plot -  at the south east and south west corner  is more heathy. Beyond the south east corner drops off to more boggy area. North east corner is next to narrow single file walking track. Nearest larger infrastructure is 750m away at the Bogong High Plains Road. Corresponds to LTERN site: Cope Creek unburnt grassland.
location_description: Alpine National Park,5.7km south of Falls Creek

description: Alpine National Park, 3.6 km west of Falls Creek
comments: Alpine peat swamp. Not grazed, (check with Sam Grover- RMIT in terms of grazing effect and fire). Snow gum woodlands that border the site have been burnt but uncertain as to whether it burnt into bog. Introduced plant species effect is minimal. No surface strew but one small outcrop/large boulder of granite. Plot is homogenous but community is confined to the plot. 120m north ( upslope) of the plot is a walking track while 650m south east is fire track that leads up towards Mt Nelse. Plot is within the catchment of the OzFluz Alpine flux tower.
