location_description: Alpine National Park, 3.6 km west of Falls Creek

description: Alpine National Park.2.2km. south of Falls Creek Lake.
comments: Plot straddles the top of a ridge forming a small plateau. Complex slope with a slope down on northern side at a 5 degree slope to but also at south western and eastern sides. Large granite outcrop- 3-4m high in the middle of site. Most of the outcrop is covered by Lichen ( called crypto in PI) No strew apparent due to dense ground cover. Evidence of deer ( pad through site) but grazing effect is low. Long unburnt- plot wasn’t burnt in 2003 fires but surrounding woodlands have. Introduced plant species effect is moderate.  Trisetum spicatum is common through the site at low cover. Hypochaeris radicata, Cerastium vulgare, Taraxacum sp. and Acetosella vulgaris also present. Community is confined to plot due to complex topography.  150m up hill from copehut carpark and track.
visit_notes: Points 0 to 54 on S3-N3 not collected

description: Alpine National Park, 3.7km south east of Falls Creek
comments: Gently sloping saddle coming down between low rises. 2 degree slope to the north west but increasing slightly at the north west corner. Overlooking falls creek ski fields. Cattle removed in 2005, Sambar deer increasingly present. 100m from Maisie’s control plot and another 100m to “fenced” plot. Introduced species effect is low- Acaena and possibly grasses. Fire- Burnt in 2003. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. North east corner is around 25m from Bogong high plains road. Corresponds to LTERN plot: Rocky Valley Burnt Grassland
location_description: Alpine National Park, 3.7km south east of Falls Creek

description: Alpine National Park, 8.4 km south west of Falls Creek.
comments: Plot sits in the saddle of Mt Jim. 3 degree slope to the east, consistent through the site. No strew due to dense ground cover. Some outcrop and larger rocks of Basalt. Most of the rock is covered by Cryptogam with no other cryptogam visible in site. Some horse scats in the site which may explain weeds in site. Long unburnt. Homogeneity- extensive grassland- eastern edge of the site dips down into some slightly more boggy areas. Community extends 80m in all directions. Plot sits among network of hiking trails. Closest point is the north east corner which is 50m from track.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 8.4 km south west of Falls Creek.

description: Alpine National Park, 5.4 km south west of Falls Creek.
comments: Gently sloping plain in the broad valley of Cope Creek. No surface strew or outcrop- metamorphic substrate, possibly granite. Long unburnt. Introduced plant species effect is low. Grazing- less grazing by horses as there are more people.  Homogeneity- Plot is homogenous 90m from the centre in all directions. The north east corner is 80m from Cope Saddle access track. Overlaps LTERN  plot established in 1979.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 5.4 km south west of Falls Creek.

description: Alpine National Park, 5.1km south west of Falls Creek.
comments: Plot with complex slope predominantly to the north west but also to the south east. Outcrop is granite with some sizeable outcrops through the site to 2m. Minimal surface strew due to dense ground cover. Unburnt but surrounded by burnt areas. Some dead trees in plot but died of other causes rather than fire. Introduced plant species effect is low- Acetosella vulgaris present and possibly some of the grass species. Grazing effect is minimal. Homogeneity- community is confined to plot. Community sits on ridge capping with northern and eastern edge transitioning to a heathland. North west corner is 10m uphill from Cope Saddle access track.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 5.1km south west of Falls Creek.

description: Alpine National Park, 5.3 km South East of Falls Creek
comments: Steep sloped plot – 10+ degree slope to the north east to creek. Large granite outcrops which are covered in Cryptogam ( will be Cryptogam in Point intercept), scattered through site. No real surface strew due to ground cover. Plot was burnt in 2003- lots of dead but regenerating Snow gum- have regenerated beyond half way up to previous height. Grazing effect is low- no cattle but deer are present in area. Introduced plant effect is low- some annuals at south west corner close to track . Homogeneity- community is confined to plot- swamp in north east corner. 5ms to infrastructure- Wallace Hutt track.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 5.3 km South East of Falls Creek

description: Alpine National Park, 6.6km east north east of Falls Creek.
comments: Gently sloping plot with a 1 degree slope to the north west. Fire- possibly burnt in 2003- snow gum woodlands surrounding the plot were likely burnt at this time.  Introduced plant species effect is minimal- probably came in from horses. Horse scats and pad in the site. Minimal surface strew and no outcrop. Plot is sitting over metamorphic substrate. Homogeneity-  plot is 1.2 km east from track to Mt Nelse fire track. Vegetation community is quite extensive but southern edge is close to snow gum woodland but west, north and east extends 30m beyond the plot. Corresponds to LTERN plot: “Cultivation” grassland .
location_description: Alpine National Park, 6.6km east north east of Falls Creek.

description: Alpine National Park, 13km south of Hotham Heights
comments: Plot is on a very shallow spur that runs north-south through the middle of the plot. Aspect to the north west but also to the north east corner- 2 degree slope. Plot is sitting on basalt but no gravel or outcrop visible. Homogeneity- plot is homogeneous but Poa hiemata more common at south east corner. Community is confined to the plot- to the south is snow gum woodland and north east is fenced enclosure. Not currently grazed but likely heavy in the past. Introduced plant species effect is high likely due to past grazing- Trifolium repens, Acetosella vulgaris, Hypochaeris radicata and other species present . Fire-  Burnt 2003?- snow gums surrounding the plot burnt at this time. Corresponds to LTERN plot: Lankey’s Plain Grassland.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 13km south of Hotham Heights

description: Alpine National Park, 11km south south west of Hotham Heights
comments: Gently sloping plot with a 1 degree slope to the south. No surface strew due to dense cover but some flat basalt outcrops. Homogeneity- plot sits in extensive community but 15m south west is the Dargo High Plains road. 100m north, 50m to the east and west are the same community.  Grazing effect is lower than other Lankey’s plain site though neither are currently formally grazed. Introduced plant effect is lower as a result- some Trisetum spicatum,  Trifolium repens and others but cover is low.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 11km south south west of Hotham Heights

description: Alpine National Park, 26.9km north east of Licola
comments: Gently sloping plot on a slight spur with a slope to the north east but also slightly to the south east. Fire- burnt in 2003? Grazing- wombat burrows in south west corner and through the plot. Old corner posts of cattle yards but not currently formally grazed. Introduced plant species effect is low – Trifolium, Hypochaeris and a few other species present. Homogeneity- Vegetation community is consistent through the site- some scattered heath shrubs on the eastern section. Celmisia pugioniformis occurs in denser patches through the site.  Community is confined to plot- north of the plot is boggier community. Western edge is 20-60m from woodland. Closest point to track is 300m up the ridgeline but track may have previously run through valley. Sitting on sandstone-  but minimal surface gravels and no outcrop, a couple of fens scattered through the site.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 26.9km north east of Licola

description: Alpine National Park, 27.7km north east of Licola
comments: Gently sloping plot with a 2 degree slope to the east. Burnt 2003? Homogeneity- vegetation community extends 20m in all directions from the centre further to the north, south and east but north west corner is 15m. from old horse yards and more wooded area. Plot borders on old Kelly lane track ( long disused) on eastern edge. Grazing effect is currently low- wombats present ( though no burrows close to plot) deer also present. One lone Eucalypt shrub in the plot.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 27.7km north east of Licola

description: Alpine National Park, 24.9 km north of Licola
comments: Complex topography. General slope is to the north north east but both south east corner and north west corner just grazed the woodlands on either side of the narrow valley. There is also a substantial drainage line that runs along eastern edge where there is a swampier area. Another drainage line also comes in just south of the north west corner but is much shallower and could possibly be an old track. Old disused “A4” track also runs through the site- less eroded than the track closer to carpark south of the site. Long unburnt- woodlands on either side have not been burnt for a long time, fire in woodlands to the south of the site in 2003? Introduced plant effect is low- some Trifolium repens and possibly Poa pratensis/weedy grasses and Acetosella vulgaris in creek but cover is low. Main grazing effect is from deer, hoof prints and scats in creek line. Site was not formally grazed as other sites (VCAAUA0013 and 14) were. Surface strew is sedimentary (probably sandstone) cobbles ( confined to creek where there has been erosion) No rock outcrop.
location_description: Alpine National Park, 24.9 km north of Licola

description: Murray Sunset National Park. South western end of Clay Lake. 28km north west of Underbool
comments: Lake bed surrounded by Mallee dominated sand dunes. Closest Mallee are 5m from the north west corner. Homogeneous plot extends >70m but scalded area in north west corner where water runs in from the main bed of the lake to the north. No signs of fire. No weeds. No Grazing impact was evident. Just to the south of the plot is an old fence line. Roadway at closest is 20m from the western edge of the site. No slope.
visit_notes: No woody species present for basal wedge measures. No LAI recorded. No site markers or pickets left on site as condition of permit. Future visits will need DGPS to relocate plot.
location_description: Murray Sunset National Park. South western end of Clay Lake. 28km north west of Underbool.

description: Murray Sunset National Park, about 26kms north west of Underbool.
comments: Plot is on a plain. Lots of Cryptogam crust. Grazing effect is low at present- bulldozer has been through the site ripping 1 or 2 rabbit warrens. Very long unburnt- at least 10 to 15 years. Introduced plant effect is low- but difficult to tell as forbs are only beginning to shoot. Some Sisymbrium but cover low. No Carrichtera annua noted. Slope- site has a 1 degree slope to the north west but more or less flat though sloping slightly at the corners of the site.
visit_notes: Plot not marked
location_description: Murray Sunset NP, about 26kms northwest of Underbool. Belah open woodland

description: Murray Sunset National Park. 6.5 km north west of Mt Gnarr, 20.5km north west of Underbool
comments: Swale among dune. Litter is significant component of substrate, with Cryptogam and Bare ground. Gentle slope to the west but site generally flat. Long Unburnt. Grazing minimal- macropods using hummocks to lie in. Plot is homogenous >70m with10% on southern side touches on edge of sand dune but doesn’t really affect composition. Community is constricted to the swale- doesn’t extend much beyond the plot. Complex mix of several Eucalyptus sp. (Mallee"s) so basal wedge measures were all assigned to Eucalyptus socialis subsp. socialis. Basal wedge count for Southwest corner was missed.
location_description: Murray Sunset National Park. 6.5 km north west of Mt Gnarr, 20.5km north west of Underbool

description: Unallocated Crown Land, survey site SWA0404A, ca. 61.08km north (6.91°) of Hyden and ca. 54.95km west-northwest (70.85°) of Narembeen.
comments: Flat sandplain of deep yellow sandy soil. Half degree slope to the south. No Formal grazing- Kangaroos present. Introduced species effect is nil? . Long Unburnt- fire to the north of the site. No Surface strew. Homogeneity- South east corner is approximately 10m in from road which is running north easterly away from the south east corner.
visit_notes: Casuarina species combined for basal wedge
location_description: Unallocated Crown Land, survey site SWA0404A, ca. 61.08 km north (6.91°) of Hyden and ca. 54.95 km west-northwest (70.85°) of Narembeem

description: Unallocated Crown Land, survey site SWA0401A, ca. 66.99 km north (3.18°) of Hyden and ca. 54.06 km northwest (63.28°) of Narembeen
comments: Sandplain of deep yellow brown sandy soil. Sloping very gently ( 1-2 degrees) to the south west. ( Relic dune?) Some laterite gravels on the section that rises up to the south west corner. Very long unburnt but canopy noticeably shorter than neighbouring site WAAAVW0001. Not Formally grazed but lots of kangaroo dropping through the site. Introduced plant species effect is minimal ? Homogeneity- to the south of the site there are more Eucalyptus. Track running north to south 30m beyond the western edge of the plot. 75 metres from the centre is homogenous.
visit_notes:
No Basal area recorded. Insufficient woody material

change substrate to laterite
location_description: Unallocated Crown Land, survey site SWA0401A, ca. 66.99 km north (3.18°) of Hyden and ca. 54.06 km northwest (63.28°) of Narembeem

description: As previous.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Introduced plant impact is low. Grazing impact is medium, evidence of echidna diggings, kangaroo and possum scat, grazing evident ofn grasses and forbs. Site burnt in last 3 years, scarring on some trees, some dead burnt trees, all Banksia show scorching. Outcrop present in SW corner. Communtiy is confined to plot. Site has a drainage line down eastern edge, 20-30m in from boundary. ES conrer more open. Banksia ssp. more dominant along suthern edge. Old fence post is SE corner, evidence of selective logginng and traditiional owners are known to collect Xanthorrhoea sp. for traditional uses.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
A complex Hill slope  of low rises.Drainage lines run through the centre of the plot from north west to south east with the plot sloping up from this on the other side. Plot Goes over the capping at the south west corner in the opposite direction. Main slope of 4 degree to the south east. Substrate is Iron Rich sandstone/laterite. Some shallow outcrop at the south west corner.  Minimal grazing. Tree has been cut in site- firewood? but disturbance minimal otherwise. Sandier through the creek channel as well. Very long unburnt. Introduced species effect is low- some Cape weed and other species but cover is low.  Homogeneity- North west corner is 5m in from access track. Community is confined to the plot- south west corner is a little more open with more rock.
visit_notes: SW corner coordinate was sitting in the NW corner, have used the SW corner coordinate from the soil site sheet and updated the Site Points table (CS 26/06/2024)
location_description: Boyagin Nature Reserve, South West of Brookton. North West of Pingelly

description: done.
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
5-7% slope to the SW. Ferricrete gravel (20% cover) and outcrop present. Evidence of echidna and macropod diggings. Grazing impact is low-moderate, grazing on some of the tussock grasses. Introduced plant impact is minimal, Lysimachia sp. present. Nearest infrastructure is the access track, 30m south of SE corner. Community homogeneous, mostly confined to plot. Extend 70m north, 60m NE, changes at SW corner (wetter), denser is SE. Evidence of selective logging. Cultural harvesting of Xanthorrhoea sp. occurs within the reserve. Evidence of past fire on dead trees, estimate ~10years ago.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Hill crest on low rise. Mostly gravels with some larger cobbles. Mostly laterite with ironstone.  Complex slope. 3 degree slope to the south but steeper more to the south west corner. Straddles spur of low hill. South west corner just into creek line. North eastern corner is a tongue of more sandy material from further up the slope. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees but some ash under some of the older trees 10+ years. No formal grazing- kangaroos. Introduced species is low. Aira cupaniana and Cape weed but overall cover is low.
location_description: Boyagin Nature Reserve, 14km South West of Brookton. 14.9km North East of Pingelly

description: Charles Darwin Reserve. 3.5km south of homestead, 103km south east of Morawa.
comments: Landform element and pattern is plain within a plain. No surface strew or lithology present. Surface substrate mostly bare ground with some cryptogam. Site is flat, no discernible slope. Site is homogenous, site sits in a broad expanse >100m from centre in all directions. Long unburnt, quite a few dead trees and shrubs within plot. Possibly burnt more recently to the North of plot, where there is more recruitment. Grazing impact is minimal. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 30m East of SE corner.
location_description: Charles Darwin Reserve, 3.5km south of homestead.  103km south east of Morawa.

description: Charles Darwin Reserve. 2.1km south south east of homestead, 103km south east of Morawa.
comments: The site is an Acacia shrubland located on a granite rise in a larger sandplain landform. The site slopes about 2 degrees to the south. There is an exposed granite outcrop in the centre and towards the western edge of the plot with pebble sized surface strew. The nearest infrastructure is an access track 100m west from the south west corner. The vegetation community is homogenous and continues at least 100m from the centre of the plot in all directions. The site is long unburnt with some old charred stumps present but no fire scarring is evident on any of the living shrubs. There is a decent amount of coarse woody debris around the site as well. The impact of introduced weeds is minimal with some weedy species such as Hypercaeris and Gallium present. The property has been destocked since 2003 and as such the grazing impact is also minimal with evidence of native browsers only, largely kangaroos.

description: Charles Darwin Reserve. 9.6km south of homestead, 106km south east of Morawa.
comments: Landform element and pattern, sand plain within a sandplain. Site was burnt ~2years ago in a controlled burn. Grazing impact minimal. Introduced plant species impact minimal. Gentle slope 1 degree to SE. No outcrop or surface strew present, though some coarse grained sand. Site is homogenous and community is quite extensive, continuing 100m East, 200m to North and South and 400m to West from the plot centre. Vegetation of Eastern side of access track is a similar community if not the same, but hasn’t been recently burnt. Nearest infrastructure is the access track 50m East of North East corner. Existing pitfall line 10m NE of NE corner, perpendicular to access track.

description: Hamelin Station Reserve, 17.6km east of homestead 98.8km south east of Denham
comments: Plot is flat- Sandy at surface but very hard below that. Some evidence of goats outside of the plot- fence seems effective at keeping goats out. Very long unburnt. Minimal surface strew- sandy at the surface. Plot is possibly co-located with Bush Heritage monitoring plot either existing or plan. Check with BHA. Close to old water point but introduced plant species effect is low- mainly Sisymbrium erysimoides. Plot sits in extensive Acacia xiphophylla community but fence line 30m to the south and disused bore to the north west mean community only extends 75m from the centre.   200m north of main Shark Bay road.

description: Hamelin Station Reserve, 10.6km SE of Hamelin Homestead, 24.2km NNW, Coburn Homestead
comments: Landform element and pattern, sand plain in a plain. No discernible slope. No outcrop or surface strew apparent. Sandy soil with some cryptogam crust. Site is homogenous and community is quite extensive, extending >400m East (does pass over a station track), >900m North, >1km South (does pass over a station track), >1km West (does pass over a station track). Introduced plant species impact is minimal, some Sisymbrium erysimoides. Grazing impact is low. Nearest infrastructure is 30m S of SW corner. Site is low unburnt, some scarring on old Mallee Eucalypts.

description: Hamelin Station Reserve, 13.7km south west of Homestead. 86.2km south east of Denham
comments: Plot is on a dune slope in a low  dune field. 2 degree slope to the north west at 45 degrees.  No surface strew- lots of course woody debris. Long unburnt but fire has crept into southern part of the plot 5-6 m. Grazing effect is low-  rabbits and possibly goats but in low numbers. Introduced plant effect is low- Hypochaeris, Sisymbrium and other species- particularly under trees where they are more protected.  Community is quite extensive- extends at least 75m from the centre. Western edge is 20m in from reserve boundary track.

description: 6.8 km. NE of Hamelin Homestead, 24.7km WNW of the Overlander Roadhouse.
comments: Limestone plain, dunes to the east and west. Surface strew and very low outcrop is limestone. Plot is flat. Long unburnt- no evidence of recent fire. Grazing effect is low- some kangaroo scats. Lots of caterpillars present- have been eating forbs. Introduced plant effect is high- Onion weed and Sisymbrium consistent through the site. Homogeneity- community extends 800m to the north east and 70m to the south. North west and south east if a more shrubby community. Station track is to north west about 80m from the plots.

Grazing impact is low, some evidence of cattle but grasses still have heads. 
Introduced plant species include: 3 Stylosanthes sp. The site has not burnt this dry-season but has in previous seasons. Has not been burnt this dry season so a lot more species in the ground-story compared to the last visit.

No surface strew or outcrop on the plot.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Toe slope of low rise, curved over the slope to maximum of 4 degrees to the south west and north east. Highly weathered granite substrate with quartz veins. Some very low outcrops. Some termite mounds through the site.

Homogeneity- community is contained to the plot but extends 30m to the south of the site. 20m from south west corner to a track.

location_description:
Site has been control burned this dry-season with a patchy mosaic of burned and unburned grass clusters. There is some regeneration of grasses but not as much as other burned sites in the region. 
 Grazing evident by Agile Wallabies and Kangaroos but no evidence of cattle pressure. Effect of introduced plants seems negligible, possible due to recent fire. A lot of Passiflora, Bidens spinosa and Cenchrus ciliaris on the last visit. Some Cucumis and Stylosanthes species present this visit.

description: Boodaring Rock in Jilbadgi Nature Reserve. About 30km ENE of Marvel Loch. WAACOO0005 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS4a
comments: WAACOO0005 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS4a. Granite exposure with skeletal soils, reflects basement in adjacent profile. Holding water at points in granite basins. Largely granite flora with adjacent shrubland and Mallee. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: Boodaring Rock in Jilbadgi Nature Reserve. About 30km ENE of Marvel Loch.

description: Jilbadgi Nature Reserve, About 1.5km NE of Boodarding Rock, which is 37km SSE of Yellowdine. Salmon gum woodland immediately south of access track to Jilbadgi NR from Gt Eastern Hwy.
comments:
WAACOO0006 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS46.
Some fire intrusion shown by acacia regeneration and some charred logs. Mostly older understorey. Likely Boorabbin fire 2  to 3 years before visit. Most of the plot was unaffected by recent fire. Older very hot fire across plot evidenced by black charcoal beds where logs once were and by saplings- possibly salmon gums. More recent fire in very small pockets may be about 3 to 5 years. Very rare surface rocks included quartz, iron conglomerate and weathered granite. Rocks may be of colluvial origin. 
Soils were salmon coloured and very hard-setting. The upper profile commonly has termite galleries, mostly old, and low termite mounds were common.
 North east cnr. has 10 x 10 m area of Melaleuca fire scorch death.
visit_notes: Eucalyptus salubris may cover intergrades.based on appearance the likelihood that E. salmonophloia was present cannot be ruled out. There were old fallen fruit from this species in the general vicinity

description: North part of Jilbadgi NR about 0.3 km west of Boodarding Rock.
comments: WAACOO0007 is established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS43a and 0.5 km west of WAACOO0005.This site stands out as having been affected by fire in the last 3 to 5 years. Almost all mature trees were killed and so Mallee resprouts and saplings dominated.  Acacia acuminata (fieldname) dominates on the granite outwash sandier loams on the northeast edge as it does in the wheat belt. Long unburnt, responding to intermittent seasonal rain.
location_description: North part of Jilbadgi Nature Reserve about 0.3 km west of Boodarding Rock . 0.5 km west of WAACOO0005.

description: Northern end of Jilbadgi Nature Reserve. 60km south east of Southern Cross.
comments: Co-located site with WA Museum site BS39.Heavier soils in Woodland. Austrostipa common and forming semi-savannah. Site not affected by more recent fires. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
visit_notes: Jilbadji N
location_description: Northern end of Jilbadgi Nature Reserve. 60km south east of Southern Cross

description: Boorabbin National Park, 4.5 km south of Boorabbin town site. Southwest end of drainage from granite sheets, a basin bordered by Eucalypt woodland including Mallee.
comments:
"Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS11. A shallow composite basin depression.  There is significant granite outwash from the complex to the north. This contributes light pinkish sand. Red sands form a lunette to the east and south. In the plot the SW has heavy grey-green hard-setting sediment at medium depth (decayed granite and/or sump/acidic?); the centre heavy similar sediment; the north-west cracking clays; and the NE light-coloured coarse-grained beach-like sand. 
 The plants suggest episodic and persistent inundation and/or soil saturation. Namely Callistemon, Marsilea, Muehlenbeckia, Juncus. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: 4.5 km south of Boorabin townsite. Southwest end of drianage from granite sheets, a basin bordered by Eucalypt woodland including mallee.

description: Boorabbin National Park, 4km south of Boorabbin.
comments: Northern part of granite complex. Outcrop to 8m. Complex trends south to WAACOO 0009.Soil in north west and south west corners is humic granitic sand and close to source, ne corner is silty sand and se cnr. is clay-sand with Mel. uncinata. Plot dominated by granite dome which sheds shattered material and has been dammed in the mid-east part. The apron has a well developed grassland and herb field. Soils on the edge mainly sandy detritus. In the SE washaway there are clays at depth.  Virtually all the granite area lacks vascular plants and so cryptograms were scored where the cover on rock was 50% or more; note that all such un-vegetated cryptogam points could have equally well have been scored as outcrop. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: granite complex (this is the end).    About 4km south of Boorabin. Northern part of granite complex. Outcrop to 8m. Complex trends south to WAACOO 0009 which is a basin over the

description: Boorabbin National Park, About 6km south of Boorabbin on a large gypsum dune jutting into a lake chain.
comments: Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS5 . Plot on a large gypsum dune on the edge of a salt lake chain. Erosion has affected parts of the surface (terrace and minor gully). There are eucalypt saplings on one side, but quite a number of very old Callitris have died, possibly due to drought and likely due to persistent rabbit warrens and root damage. There are some Callitris seedlings. There were some limited patches of step and gully erosion. Amyema miquelii on older Euc sp., terete mistletoe on Grevillea sarissa. Minimal impact of introduced plant species.
location_description: About 6km south of Boorabin on a large gypsum dune jutting into a lake chain.

description: Boorabbin National Park, 6km south of Boorabbin town site, near track to salt lake. West of track 30m.
comments: Established in same vicinity as WA Museum site BS35a .Open to grazing by kangaroos, rabbits and emus. Likely once partly cut over given proximity to Boorabbin and railway. Site is home to several dragons,  about 40cm, grey with brown striped  tails.  Site is between granite about 200m west and salt lake over 300m east.
location_description: About 6km south of Boorabin townsite, near track to salt lake. West of track 30m. Mixed salmon gum woodland is between granite outcrops.

description: Boorabbin National Park, about 1.2km east of pipeline crossing/haul road on northern side of highway at Boorabbin and then 400m north.
comments:
Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0005.
Likely 50mm or more fell on the site; plenty of recent insect activity and some shrubs flowering. Termites and wasps active. Grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Triodia and Callitris mature in places; !likely 10 - 20 or more years since rain. May have been closely impacted by Boorabbin when occupied, e.g. fire frequency.
visit_notes: Most of the 10 to 15cm "Mesomelaena" may be a Schoenus witha pungent tip and lacking persistent heads.
location_description: About 1200m east of pipeline crossing/haulroad on northern side of highway at Boorabbin and then 400m north.

description: Boorabbin National Park, 4.35km north from Ryan"s find rd. turnoff on Great Eastern Highway; along firebreak that stands in for the road. Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0006
comments:
Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0006.
Late post-fire stage indicated by large or collapsing Triodia, mature and senescent. Callitris and Melaleuca are green. Diverse beetles, ants and termites evident. As at WAACOO0016 site is open to grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Termites active.
.
location_description: 4350m north from Ryan's find rd turnoff on Great Eastern Highway; along firebreak that stands in for the road.

description: Boorabbin National Park, About 500m north of Highway at Boorabbin. East side of haul road.
comments:
Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0008.
Near road culvert. Open to grazing by rabbits and kangaroos. 10+ years since fire, Triodia mature. More strongly Allocasuarina, Borya, Ecdeiocolea,   and such laterite profile Genera.   Many medium-sized acacias dead.  Litter,  esp.  Allocasuarina litter.  Many,  sparse,  Triodia crescents,  and some Callitris senescent.  Several,  10-20+,  years since fire.  Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0008
location_description: About 500m north of Highway at Boorabbin. East side of haul road.

description: Boorabbin National Park, About 5.1km west of Ryan"s Find Rd on track running parallel to the pipeline on its north side; then at junction turn onto ENE track and go about 1.1km east (-north-east).
comments:
Site overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0007. Open to grazing by kangaroos and rabbits. Mature shrubs and Triodia indicate 10+ years since fire. Located between pipeline and major firebreak with high v power line to north. Like 0016, 17 & 18 the yellow sands occur on low rises and slopes, and there is laterite in places as observed when digging SWATT pits.
 At this site,  in contrast to 0016,17, 18, and others,  the highest live part of sedges was recorded (rather than the highest part) - in order to give a better sense of what was alive versus dead in terms of the whole clump/clonal entity. There is a patch of surface laterite gravel in the north-west corner.
visit_notes: Most Allocasuarinas with dead hits were on live plants.
location_description: About 5.1km west of Ryan's Find Rd on track running parallel to the pipeline on its north side; then at junction turn onto ENE track and go about 1.1km east (-north-east).

                                                                                                                                          CANT ADD Species in SWARM!

description: Credo Conservation Park, 2km south of supersite at Credo Station along Coolgardie north road, and then about 3km east.
comments: Co-located site.WAACOO0025 established in the vicinity of a CSIRO Supersite SB. Shrubland surrounded by hills with woodland. Somewhat degraded by regular stock, rabbit and  horse activity. Main grasses are mown flat. Maireana sedifolia is squared-off by grazing in places. Cat scat present. Many cow prints; though duricrust still intact.  Depressions show consistent damp-land elements including Eragrostis dielsii, Cuscuta, Austrodanthonia (edges), Sida "fibulifera", and Enteropogon, and minor patches of raised complex salinity via Frankenia and Tecticornia. High impact of introduced plant species- Medicago minima and Salvia verbenaca high cover, Centaurea melitensis low cover.
visit_notes:
Site overlay with CSIRO CREDO Supersite SB
Many cow pats; plots "unknown" substrate stands in for cow pats. 
Trees identified in basal wedge are well outside the plot to east and mainly west; valley is open.
location_description: About 2km south of supersite at Credo Station along Coolgardie north road, and then about 3km east. Plain with shrubland surrounded by hills with woodland.Site overlay with CSIRO CREDO Supersite SB

Grazing appears to be mainly due to kangaroos. (from end) and there are still black stakes and fire skeletons of Acacias. Plot appears to have been burnt 5 (3 to 8) years before, Acacias, Allocasuarina and Grevilleas are relatively young, Triodia is ~20cm
visit_notes:

description: Credo Conservation Park, 25km west of Credo Homestead.
comments:
Co-located site.WAACOO0028 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0015.
Kangaroos main grazers. Yellow sand ridge on laterite. Surface level termite mounds evident, dragons frequent as at WAACOO0026 and 0027.Slightly down ridge compared to 0026 and 0027. Some small areas of mining excavation, or spoil.. Regenerating after fire some 5 years or more.
visit_notes:
Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATCOO15
Grevillea divided 2 near north 2 12m may be a new collection. 
This site was lower down the western flank of the major north-south ridge on which the sandplain had developed,  than 0026 and 0027. Between WAACOO0027 and 0028 is a mine pit,  which may indicate greenstone influence along the ridge; though the it seems likey the main substrate under the yellow sands and laterite is granite.  Site had gravel at 30cm depth and small amounts of gravel on surface.  May relate to stronger presence of Allocasuarina compared to WAACOO0026, 0027 and 0029. Several old 60-70cm test pits present.  A range of lizards and insects,  see 0029. It was here that the Tiger beetle was observed,  probing other invertebrate holes and moving rapidly on the 40o C plus sand.
location_description: Yellow sand ridge on laterite. @25km west of Credo homestead. Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATCOO15

description: As previous
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is dune slope in a dune field. The site slopes approximately 2 south-east. No surface strew or rocky outcrop is apparent. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. WAACOO0029 overlays with South Western Australian Transitional Transect WATCOO0016.Burnt 5 to10 years. Triodia older? Some patches of mature Callitris persist to east. Some Rabbit diggings and Kangaroo droppings. Dragons common.

This plot is possibly compositionally closer to  WAACOO0026, 0027, though mallees vary.  0028 shows more gravel influence,  and had small test pits.  Grazing likely by kangaroos and some rabbit activity.  Lizards (dragons and Ctenotis) common. All had a range of insects,  incl.  native bees,  thynnids,  sphecids,  diverse ants,  large sedentary cockroaches,  weevils,  shield beetles,  jewel beetles,  brown bombers,  and large spikey predatory? Tiger beetles.  

Time since fire appears a year or two older than 0026, 0027, 0028; as Triodia is slightly more advanced,  though may relate to soil moisture retention,  eg even deeper sands.
location_description: About 25km due east of Credo Homestead. About 1.5km west of a granite outcrop.Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATCOO16

Grazing effect is low but some old cattle scats through the site. Introduced plant effect is low to moderate- Passiflora foetida in some denser patches on northern edge. Acacia nilotica? , Calotropis sp. and Pennisetum sp. also present. Cenchrus ciliaris also present but cover low at present.
visit_notes: site desc. location wrong
location_description:
Site has been control burned this dry-season with a patchy mosaic of burned and unburnt grass clusters. There is some regeneration of grasses but not as much as other burned sites in the region. 
Grazing evident by Agile Wallabies and Kangaroos but no evidence of cattle pressure. Effect of introduced plants seems negligible, possible due to recent fire. A lot of Passiflora, Bidens spinosa and Cenchrus ciliaris on the last visit. Some Cucumis and Stylosanthes species present this visit.

description: Roebuck Plains Station, 19.2km east north east of homestead. 43.5km east north east of Broome
comments: Landform element and pattern, swamp in a flood plain. Located adjacent to Lake Eda. No surface strew or outcrop, quite sandy. Site is flat, no slope. Grazing impact is moderate, grazed this dry season from cattle. Site is inside a recently constructed enclosure, to look at the impact of grazing. Introduced plant impact is low, check ID determinations. Site is long unburnt, evidence of fire present on older shrubs. Site is homogenous although grasses are slightly more prevalent in SW corner. Community extends 200m to the west and east of plot and transitions to the north and south. Nearest infrastructure is access track 5m north of NE corner.
location_description: Roebuck Plains Station

description: Roebuck Plains Station, 17.4km east north east of homestead. 41.5km east north east of Broome
comments: Floodplain of the Roebuck Plains, slightly elevated and seasonally flooded. Homogeneity of the site extends 200m in a westerly direction. The NE corner is about 10m from the lake access track, the community extends on the other side of the track, and becomes sparser to the south. The site is flat with minimal surface strew. Limited grazing with some cattle but now been fenced. Has not been burnt for some time. No introduced plant species note
visit_notes: Transect WE5 not collected
location_description: Roebuck Plains Station, 17.4km east north east of homestead. 41.5km east north east of Broome

description: Roebuck Plains Station, 19.9km east north east of homestead. 44.6km east north east of Broome
comments: Long unburnt site, some recruitment in smaller shrubs. The site is flat, on a sand ridge sloping up from the lake to the west of the site. Homogeneity 75m from the centre of the plot then transitions into melaleuca shrubland. Distance to closest infrastructure is a fence 40m away on the western side of the plot. Grazing is low, some cattle around, some digging from rabbits, wallabies are also present. Introduced species moderate along the western edge, mainly Achyranthes aspera with Cenchrus ciliaris also present. No surface strew.
visit_notes: Centre basal wedge not collected
location_description: Roebuck Plains Station, 19.9km east north east of homestead. 44.6km east north east of Broome.

description: Sheffield Mine Lease, 6 km west south west of Mount Jowlaenga homestead. 99km north east of Broome.
comments: The site is a plain on a sandplain with no surface strew apparent and only a small patch of low-relief sandstone outcropping in the south eastern corner of the plot.  The soil is quite sandy. The site is homogenous and the community extends at least 200m from the centre of the plot to the south, north and east but extends only about 100m to the west where it is stopped by a mining road. This is also the nearest infrastructure, between 75-100m from the south west corner. The site has not been burnt recently, at least not in the past 1-2 years, although there is fire scarring on some of the trees. The impact of introduced weeds is minimal and grazing is low to moderate with evidence of cattle through the site. The nearest water point is 5.9km north of the site.
visit_notes: Basal wedge data on voice recorder and some species cut off for basal on eastern and southern points.
location_description: Sheffield Mine Lease, 6 km west south west of Mount Jowlaenga homestead. 99km north east of Broome.

description: Stirling Range National Park, survey site SWA0201A, ca. 18.75 km north-northwest (26.76°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 27.24 km southeast (137.6°) of Cranbrook.
comments: Flat plot on sandplain of deep white sandy soil. Minimal surface strew. Long unburnt- no scarring on trees and vegetation is very thick. Grazing pressure from Kangaroos is moderate, lots in area. Introduced plant species effect is low-  Hypochaeris glabra,  Sonchus oleraceus and Aira cupaniana present but minimal cover. Homogeneity-  south west corner is 10m from track which runs away at angle away from the site. Difficult to tell extent of community beyond plot due to thickness of vegetation.

description: South Side of track, 10.1km west of abandoned Jigalong mission road on track to Newman via Jimblebar Mine. 36.1km east of Wheelarra Hill. 76.5km east of Newman.
comments: Flat site on Alluvial Plain on a floodplain. No surface strew- lots of Cryptogam. Plot has been burnt since first sampled- regeneration in tussock grasses and scarring on the tree. location_description:
Eurardy Reserve  York gum woodland.
Site is unchanged Eucalyptus loxophleba subsp. supralaevis low open woodland. Mid stratum is a tall open shrubland of Acacia ramulosa subsp. ramulosa,  Acacia tetragonophylla, Acacia acuminata  and other shrubs. Alot of forbs actively growing, Erodium cygnorum appears to be the only species flowering. There is an abundance of cryptogam over sand, grazing impact is low as this property is de stocked and there is some evidence of Emus. Long unburnt, undisturbed and introduced weed impact is low,.

description: Eurardy Reserve. 8.8km north east of homestead, 59.6 km north east of Kalbarri.
comments: The site is a sandplain on a plain. There is no discernible slope and the site is sandy with no surface strew or outcrop apparent. The nearest infrastructure is the station track which is about 60-70m to the north-east. There is also evidence of an old fence line with old pickets but no wire just outside the western edge of the plot.  The plot is homogenous and the Mallee woodland community extends 60-70m to the north, 70-80 metres to the east and at least 100m to west and south. The impact of introduced plant species is low and the impact of grazing is minimal with some evidence of native grazers, like Kangaroos and Emus, through site. The site is long unburnt with leaf litter present around the base of the Mallee Eucalypts.

comments: Acacia rostellifera shrubland with Myoporum insulare, Acacia sp., and Rhagodia baccata. Ground layer of Threlkeldia sp., Carpobrotus and Tetragonia on rolling coastal dunes. Approximately 100m from the beach. Slope is zero but site is undulating throughout. Long unburnt with much dead material- Mostly Myoporum sp. and Acacia sp. Introduced plant effect is minimal. Grazing effect is minimal.

location_description: Nuytsland Conservation Park

description: Nuytsland Nature Reserve, About 28kms south east of Cocklebiddy and 5kms north west of Eyre Bird Observatory.
comments: Very long unburnt- no scarring on any of the trees and no dead standing litter 30+ years. Grazing effect is low- some rabbits and kangaroos. Introduced plant effect- minimal. Dune slope in Dunefield. Wet- recent rain in previous day and also before that.  Homogeneity- continues to the west 60m. Opens up to the north on the dune crest and another 50m to the east where it joins the road. Slope is 2 degree slope through the centre of the site to the north west but site is convex. Rises at the south east corner and the northern slope.
visit_notes: Most of the cryptogam is moss.
location_description: 28kms SE of Cocklebiddy and 5kms NW of Eyre Bird Observatory. Low Mallee woodland on sand.

description: Mount Roe National Park, survey site SWA0101A, ca. 46.47 km west (271.03°) of Mt. Barker
comments: Gently sloping (1-2 degree) plot on a sandplain of deep dark grey sandy soil. No formal grazing- kangaroos. Old track that runs north east to south west through the middle of the site but quite overgrown. Fire through the site at some point in last 10 years- scarring up the trunks of Eucalyptus and Corymbia but thickly regenerated mid layer.  Introduced species effect is minimal- none noted at time of visit.  Homogeneity- plot sits in broad community of Eucalyptus marginata woodland. Plot is 50 in from track at the east and north. 75m. 1 or two of the larger trees in the plot have been cut for timber in the very distant past.
visit_notes: Corymbia and Eucalyptus combined for basal wedge
location_description: Mt. Roe National Park, survey site SWA0101A, ca. 46.47 km west (271.03°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 17.95 km east-southeast

description: Mount Roe National Park, survey site SWA0104A, ca. 36.45 km west (274.84°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 25.4 km east-southeast (113.37°) of Rocky Gully
comments: Gently sloped sandplain of deep grey sandy soil. 3 degree to the south east. Even slope though the site.  South eastern corner where the slope is angled is swampier ( water underfoot at visit) with a slight change in vegetation. The Plot was burnt in 2015 in a controlled burn ( Pers. com- park rangers).  Fire looks to have been more intense towards the southern edge of the plot- most have had the tops burnt out where further into the site the fire hasn’t got so high into the canopy.  Quite a lot of ash mixed in with bare ground on the surface. Looks like cryptogam but not actually crust. Introduced plant effect is low- Hypochaeris glabra, Hypochaeris radicata and Poa annua all present but overall cover is low. No formal grazing- kangaroos present.  Homogeneity- 90m is the same community. Plot is 40m from track to the north and on the other side of this is a grazed/ploughed paddock.
visit_notes: Unkwn substrate is moss
location_description: Mt Roe National Park, survey site SWA0104A, ca. 36.45 km west (274.84°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 25.4 km east-southeast (113.37°) of Rocky Gully

description: Stirling Range National Park, survey site SWA0204A, ca. 24.97 km north (5.38°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 17.13 km east-southeast (134.26°) of Cranbrook
comments: Plot is on a flat sandplain of deep grey sandy soil. No surface strew or outcrop. Plot is not formally grazed but Kangaroos and other native herbivores present. Long unburnt- but one large dead,  burnt Banksia in the plot. None of the other Banksia attenuata have any scarring but some of the older Eucalyptus do.  Introduced plant species effect is low- several species including  Hypochaeris glabra, Sonchus oleraceus, Petrorhagia dubia present but overall cover is low.  Homogeneity- plot is homogenous. Eucalyptus adesmophloia tends to cluster together at a subsite level. South west corner is 20m in from a dirt track and another one to the west. 75m from the centre is the same community.
location_description: Stirling Range National Park, survey site SWA0204A, ca. 24.97 km north (5.38°) of Mt. Barker and ca. 17.13 km east-southeast (134.26°) of Cranbrook

description: Birriliburu middle site
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------

Landform element and pattern is plain on sandplain. Small patch of metamorphosed sandstone gravel up the 5cm diameter. No outcropping. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. FLORA 3 Mulga Tussock survey site(August 2012,May2013,May2014)
Long since fire- 10 - 20 yr. plus, only one old burnt stump of 20cm. Evidence of grazing esp. Rhagodia camel prints old goat droppings or donkey (3cm diam. plate shaped). Prints of dingos, cats and foxes. Digging of either varanidae or bandicoot. Square kangaroo droppings, somewhat atypical. Bull ants present. Yellow abdomen ants. Predatory black beetles. Sphecid wasps. Katydid. Speckled black and orange grasshoppers. Eragrostis largely harvested by ants, post fall, and drying off.
visit_notes:
Plot had not been burnt for quite some years.
Site overlays a Biogeography site FLORA 33 Mulga Tussock(ADJ)
Goanna (Bandicoot?) digging. Camel or donkey droppings. No rabbit droppings. Emus, kangaroos, dingos, fox or cat prints. 

DEAD - WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE LARGE ACACIA RETICULATE ON SOUTH TRANSECT 5 THERE WERE NO SHRUBS THAT WERE DEAD; THAT IS ONLY SMALL PARTS OF ALL SHRUBS WERE DEAD' AND IT IS DEAD PARTS THAT APPEAR ON INTERCEPTS AS DEAD. 

Dead Triodia of 0.01m usually reflects the dead bases that still reflect a collapsed ring. 

Triodia heights are to the top of live hummock leaves only, and do not include the inflorescence. Tussock grass heights include the flowering spike. Same for 0002 & 0003. 

15th May rain overnight from 14th so transects 7 to 10 the tussock grasses are a little shorter due to weight of water. Overcast, steady drizzle overnight. 

There are parallels here to drought death (+/- senescence) of Grevilleas at Boorabbin sandplain, WAT, sites. Many mature Grevillea pinnatifid plants were dead outside the plot. 

There was heavy grazing of Rhagodia 005316 and 005335; the former was cut severely to thick hard wood. 

 With Triodia seedlings at ~10 leaf stage and resprouting bases not yet merged. Aluta seedlings were only small 3-5cm; and in patchy clusters of 5-15 plants. There were significant bare areas. Only the very NW corner on the dune lower slope was unburnt; this appeared to be the case for the dune in general including the fauna pit-line to the southwest of the plot's southwest corner. Western Desert NTS maps indicated the most recent fire was in 2012. Cover will change as Triodia and shrubs increase in bulk.
location_description: 1.5km north of virgin springs camp, Carnarvon Range. Red sandplain. 60m east of track.Site overlays a Biogeography site FLORA 33 Mulga Tussock(ADJ)

description: birriliburru south
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a sand plain. No surface strew or lithology, only deep red sand. There is a DCBA/CALM fauna monitoring plot to the south of the site.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site . FLORA 31 Dune Flat(August 2012,May2013,May2014)
Plot open to grazing by kangaroos, other native fauna, camels. Bandicoot diggings. Dingo and cat tracks. Site burnt within 3 to 5 years except patches near NW and then NW on to Dune. Aluta adults on west absent only scattered clusters of seedlings at 5cm. Some Acacias re-sprouting, and Triodia (many parts of older bases burnt out). Some ephemerals remain Trichodesma and Euphorbia. Lower slope of dune in north west sector into swale.

location_description: Red sandplain 2km west of Carnarvon Range South. Lowerslope of dune in NW sector into swale. Site overlay with Biogeography FLORA 31 DUNE FLAT(ADJ)

comments: Eucalyptus gracilis / Eucalyptus socialis low Mallee woodland with some Eucalyptus oleosa. Mid layer of Melaleuca lanceolata, Eremophila scoparia and Pomaderris and a ground layer dominated by Westringia rigida. Plain with limestone gravel surface strew. Long unburnt. Grazing effect is low-some old camel dung and kangaroos. No introduced plant species noted. Recent rain. Active vegetation growth. Much litter around base of eucalyptus. Flowering in Pomaderris sp. and Eucalypts have buds.

description: Boolardy Station, 15.8km north east of Homestead.  291km north east of Geraldton
comments: Landform element and pattern, plain in a plain. Some limestone gravel, patchy through site. No outcrop. Site is homogenous, continues 100m East, South West and 70m North (to the road). Site is long unburnt, no evidence of fire scars. Introduced plant impact is minimal. Grazing impact is low, but site has been previously grazed (de-stocked ~2 years ago), kangaroos present. Scat of possibly cattle or camel in plot. Nearest infrastructure access track 30m of NE corner. Existing 30mx30m plot situated inside the plot, in line with the centre of the northern edge.
visit_notes: Mulga Acacia species combined in basal as Acacia aptanuera
location_description: Boolardy Station, 15.8km north east of Homestead. approx 291km north east of Geraldton

description: Boolardy Station, 54.6km north of Boolardy homestead. 29.2 km north north west of Murchison Radio Observatory.
comments: The site landform pattern and element is a plain on a plain and therefore flat. There is no surface strew or coarse woody debris. The community is homogenous and broad continuing at least 75m in all directions from the centre of the plot. The nearest infrastructure is a track approx. 30m from the eastern edge. There is also impact from a nearby grader bank in the south eastern corner of the plot. The embankment is situated outside the plot but has altered drainage so that water flows into the plot. The site is very long unburnt and the impact of introduced plant species is minimal (possibly introduced Stemodia species). The site is not currently grazed and has not been for a little while (old cow and horse scats present). There is a small degree of recruitment in palatable shrubs such as the Sennas and Eremophilas, however there is a large amount of dead mulga with no recruitment evident. This is largely due to poor conditions.
visit_notes: Transect EtoW3, point 31, unknown substrate is a termite mound.
location_description: Boolardy Station, 54.6km north of Boolardy homestead. 29.2 km north north west of Murchison Radio Observatory.

description: Boolardy Station, 23.5 km north east of Boolardy homestead. 297km north east of Geraldton
comments: The site is a plain on a plain with sandy soil and no surface strew or outcrop apparent. The vegetation community is homogenous and more or less confined to the plot. The community does extend about 100m to the east and west but transitions to a more open mulga woodland to the north. The nearest infrastructure is an access track which is 20m south of the south west corner. There is also an existing monitoring plot situated within the TERN plot along the southern edge around the 50m mark. This is a 30x30m rangelands plot. The site is long unburnt with no evidence of past fire in the site. The grazing impact is minimal. The site has been grazed in the past (some old cow pats) but the property has been destocked since 2003 and is recovering well. There is evidence of native grazers such as kangaroos. The impact of introduced plant species is also minimal.

Transect labelled WtoE4 is actually transect WtoE1and transect labelled WtoE1 should be WtoE4.

Acacia aneura and A. aptaneura combined as 'mulga' for basal wedge.

description: Wanjarri SWA1003
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The landform and element has not changed since previous visit. The slope and aspect is flat and the element is a plain and the pattern is a sand plain. There is a dune to the SW but no others in the area. No surface strew or lithology.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site.WAAMUR0029 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0007.Longer unburnt. 10-20years. More old hummocks and 2-3m rings, less stumps and charcoal than WAAMUR0028. Kangaroos and emus use area. Just 300m east is Acacia ayersiana and vegetation resembles WAALSD0001. Red sand dune located about 400m west.
visit_notes:
Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR0007
TSouth 1 unknown is termite mound. 
THE CENTRE WAS MOVED TO 51 0270867 6967248 FOR CLEAR IMAGES. 
Termite mounds generally 20-30cm high.  Recent mound building following rain. 
New heads on ocassional Triodia,  shrubs well hydrated after rain and silica saturated rapidly on genetic samples.  FLOWERS ON ALUTA,  DODONAEA,  HALGANIA,  ACACIA,  ANGIANTHUS,  BONAMIA,  ephemerals,  Leptosemma, 
Small chain of sand dunes about 300m westsouthwest.  Minor granite about 400m east.  Patches a few hundred metres to east have Acacia ?ayersiana with T.  basedowii and Eremophila forrestii; vegetation has some common dominant overlap with LSD 0001. 
Several species of wasps,  native bees,  hover flies and jewel beetles visiting Myrtaceous flowers.  Emus feeding and breeding in area.  Termite mounds common on surface,  and galleries evident in profile. Several species of ants,  including Myrmecoides.  Limited evidence of rabbit activity. Limited kangaroo activity. No camel prints observed. 
Most Triodia at mature or advanced hummock/crescent/ring stage (to 3m diam) and much of site likely > 10y since fire (to 20y plus).  Contrasts WAAMUR0028 &  0030 which were burnt 5yr (and less than 10) before,  and more frequently,  given charcoal in soil profile. 
Long ungrazed for pastoral purposes (~> 30yrs) as lease converted to reserve.  Homestead Eriachne grassland in good condition.
location_description: About 3km east of Wanjarri homestead. Sandplain.Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR0007.

description: Wanjarri SWA1003
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
The landform and element has not changed since previous visit. The slope and aspect is flat and the element is a plain and the pattern is a sand plain. There is a dune to the SW but no others in the area. No surface strew or lithology.
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site.WAAMUR0029 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0007.Longer unburnt. 10-20years. More old hummocks and 2-3m rings, less stumps and charcoal than WAAMUR0028. Kangaroos and emus use area. Just 300m east is Acacia ayersiana and vegetation resembles WAALSD0001. Red sand dune located about 400m west.
location_description:
Wanjarri SWA1003
Long unburnt, with no evidence of burning with minimal grazing and no introduced plant species.

description: wanjarri reserve
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a plain on a sandplain. Surface strew has small amount of brittle calcrete gravel embedded in the sandy surface. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. WAAMUR0030 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0005.
Flora typically Eremaean. Red pink sand over more compacted substrate, with finer components. Extensive Triodia savannah/shrubland. Dune or breakaway about 300m east. Drainage very slightly north east. Burnt circa 5ybp to immediate east of plot and on east edge. Body of plot long unburnt with some very old Triodia rings, up to 2 to 3m diam. Open to grazing by rabbits (diggings), kangaroos, and stock (tracks).
visit_notes:
Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR005
NW corner has minor outcrop of decayed granite to calcic material.  This appears to mark WAAMUR0030 out from WAAMUR0031 as the relief suggests a low,  decayed ridge at the former and none at the latter.  Hence,  there was a saprolitic layer at about 80cm and also minor outcropping at WAAMUR0030, whereas at WAAMUR0031 no saprolite was encountered down to 140cm,  nor was outcropping observed. In short WAACOO0031 may have had deeper sand and this may have influenced the presence and predominance of Acacia rhodophloia  and the predominance of Halgania cyanea var. Allambie Station (B.W. Strong 676) at WAACOO0031 in contrast toWAACOO 0030.

On transect south 5 the area to the immediate east, from 50 to 100m, is the limit of fire intrusion and dead A. aneura and of small hummocks (30 - 40cm diam). 

Cant add new records to PI in Swarm!!
Second records of a species were not acccepted by the Application at: Transect east 2 at 0m - which should include A.  basket at 2.5m; Transect west 3 at 43m - which should include E.  gongylocarpa  at 12.5m.
location_description: Wanjarri NR about 10km east north east of outstation.Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR0005

wanjarri reserve. Permeability = 4
No fire since last visit, site is long unburnt. Minimal grazing effect. Minimal introduced plant species.

description: triodia grassland
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element and pattern is a sand plain on a plain. No surface strew or outcrop. Site is flat. 
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Co-located site. WAAMUR0031 overlays WA Transect site WATMUR0008
Long unburnt, 15 - 20years or more. Residual charcoal, and stump pits present. Triodia in rings or crescents often 2 - 3m. Rabbit diggings and old warrens through site. Even and recent, moderate to heavy kangaroo activity. Old stock prints and scats present. Dog or dingo scats and prints present, as at 0030. One of the more open areas in the vicinity, with a lower density of acacias. The breakaway 1km east has coarse weathered granite,  the upper layer of which is ferruginous or slightly lateritised. Some scattered rocks like this were on the plot surface.  There are tens or hundreds of A grasbyi established seedlings,  20cm,  scattered through plot.  There were dingo or dog tracks near the plot,  and there are goannas, and foxes in the area.
visit_notes:
Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR0008
NOTE: Triodia crescents generally had a dead inner rind and this is usually indicated by the presence of litter and dead Triodia at 0.01cm.reflecting mature Triodia.
location_description: About 4km SSE of Wanjarri Nature Reserve shed or outstation, along the gas pipeline access track, and 80m west of the track. 400m west of a breakaway. On red sandplain.Site is co located with a South West Australian Transitional Transect site WATMUR0008

location_description: Site is long unburnt. Triodia is forming very large rings or lines in some places. Grazing effect is minimal. No introduced plant impacts. To the east of the plot there is more mulga.

description: Doongan Station. 20.5km north west of Doongan homestead, 112km south west of Kalumburu.
comments: Plot is flat but sits above drainge line that drops off in the north easter corner and curves around to the N with an 8 degree slope.  Had a cold burn in this dry season with some regeneration visible. No visible scarring from the burn. No introduced plant species recorded   Grazing pressure is low, but horses are present in the area. This plot was chosen to overlap a fauna trapping site. Homogeneity: site sits on a laterite capping, with an eroded embankment that drops down onto the flood plain. The Western edge is relatively open, the SW corners doesn’t have as much exposed laterite, more clay is obvious and the exposed capping is patchy. The plot sits 1.1km east of borrow pit on main Gibb-Kallumbaru Road.
location_description: Doongan Station. 20.5km north west of Doongan homestead, 112km south west of Kalumburu.

description: Doongan Station. 20.2km north west of Doongan homestead, 114km south west of Kalumburu.
comments: Plot is on a plain.  Pebble size sandstone gravel throughout site. Some lateritic outcrop present along western edge. Site is recently burnt in last dry season. Grazing impact is low, evidence of cattle and horses scat. Site is homogenous. Community extend to NW 100m and 75 to E, less T. canescens to the south. Nearest infrastructure is Gibb River-Kalumburu Rd 2.4km WNW of NW corner.
visit_notes: EW5 pt 25 substrate is termite mound.
location_description: Doongan Station, 20.2km north west of homestead

description: Theda Station. 24km west south west of Theda homestead, 72km south west of Kalumburu.
comments: The site is flat, with no surface strew and has a sandy substrate. The site has not been burnt for a few years, though has some old scarring on trees. Grazing pressure is low, possibly some horses in the area. No introduced plant species recoded.  Homogeneity: the site sits to the north of Doongan and Theda monitoring plot. Very homogenous,  and extends 40m in all directions. The SE is 10m in from an old track, and the new highway is 100m to the SE.
location_description: 24km west south west of Theda homestead, 72km south west of Kalumburu.

description: Theda Station. 700m north west of Theda homestead, 56.2km south west of Kalumbaru.
comments: Plot sits in a small swamp at the base of a range of low hills. Burnt almost annually.  The grazing impact is minimal, though some cows present. Introduced plant species effect is high-Themeda quadrivalvis (grader grass) is the dominant species in the ground layer and Passiflora foetida var. hispida is present throughout the site. The site is reasonably flat with a 1 degree slope to the SE. Homogeneity: Community is confined to the plot. The SW does start changing into a plain rather than a swamp. Nearest infrastructure is the Theda homestead, 600m to the SW. There are some boulders in the NE corner which have rolled down off the hill. There is little to no surface strew, very silty soil.
visit_notes: Basal wedge not collected
location_description: Theda Station, 700m north west of homestead. 56.2km south west of Kallumbaru

description: Theda Station. 4.9km east south east of Theda homestead, 57.6km south of Kalumburu.
comments: Site slope is uneven due to the outcrops throughout the site. The general slope is to north at 1 degree. Lots of quartzite outcrops throughout site, particularly along south edge. Boulder size quartzite surface strew. Site burnt May/June 2018.  Grazing impact low, possible scrub bulls. Introduced plant impact minimal. Community confined to plot. Site opens up towards north edge as it moves into deeper soils. Nearest infrastructure Gibb River-Kalumburu Rd, 4.2km West of plot. A very shallow quadbike access track is ~70m south of SW corner. Site is located adjacent to a fauna monitoring plot THS0005.
visit_notes:
Note with basal: Line of sight obstructed by large outcrops at some points. Main along southern edge.
NS4 pt 11 bare is a termite mound.
location_description: Theda Station, 4.9km east south east of Homestead.

description: Theda Station. 24.6km west south west of Theda homestead, 72km south west of Kalumburu.
comments: Flat site on a plain. The site is deeply sandy (down to a metre or so) with no surface strew or outcrop. Plot has not been burnt this dry season. No introduced plant species recorded. Grazing is minimal as the site is not formally grazed. Extensive stand of mixed Eucalyptus miniata/tetrodonta woodland, likely extending to previous site (WAANOK0002). South-east corner about 30m in from main Kalumburu Road and a disused vehicle track is located about 10m in from the south-east corner. .
visit_notes:
transect N to S 3 points 62&63 unsure of species as recorder cut off. heights were 0.2 & 0.16 respectively.

Melaleuca sp. and Perennial chrysopogon not collected.
location_description: Theda Station, 24.6km wsw of homestead

description: Theda Station. 24.6km north east of Theda homestead, 32.1km south west of Kalumbaru.
comments: Black soil plain, just north of a rainforest pocket. Site is flat with a few small undulations.  Part of the site has had a cool season burn on the northern side, possibly in the last wet season. Introduced plant effect is moderate to high with Themeda quadrivalvis dominant in ground layer and Stylosanthes hamata,  Euphorbia hirta, and Mesosphaerum suaveolens also present. Grazing effect is low, though cows are around. No surface strew or lithology.
visit_notes: basal wedge data not included, data missing
location_description: Theda station, 24.6km north east of homestead.32.1km south west of Kallumbaru

description: Theda Station. 900m north west of Theda homestead, 57.4km south south west of Kalumburu.
comments: Plot sits on crest of low hills. Slopes 2 degrees to East increasing to 5 degrees near the eastern edge of plot. Surface strew present- cobble size basalt. Outcrop also present, basalt with the majority on the eastern side of plot.  Grazing impact is minimal. Introduced plant impact minimal, some Passiflora foetida var. hispida present but at low cover. Possibly burnt April 2018.  Site is homogenous and community extends to the 200m to NE and South. Nearest infrastructure is access track 5m south of SW corner.
visit_notes: NS3 pt 81-91 not collected
location_description: Theda Station. 900m north west of Theda homestead, 57.4km south south west of Kalumburu.

description: Arubiddy Station. 9.9km north west of Arubiddy homestead. 40km north west of Cocklebiddy roadhouse.
comments: Atriplex vesicaria Chenopod shrubland with some emergent Maireana sedifolia. Site is in very slight depression about 5 hectares in size. Surrounded by Maireana sedifolia. Some limestone gravel and boulders. Limestone starts at about 20cm below the surface. Long unburnt. Grazing effect low- no sheep but old rabbit warrens within the site. No introduced plant species noted. Site is flat. Some recent rain- active vegetation growth.
visit_notes: Insufficient woody species for basal wedge measures
location_description: Arubiddy Station. 9.9km north west of Arubiddy homestead. 40km north west of Cocklebiddy roadhouse.

description: Arubiddy station.13.6 km north west of station homestead. 44km north west of Cocklebiddy roadhouse
comments: Very flat plain. Mixed of limestone gravel, pebbles and boulders- mostly gravel. Some low limestone outcrop and a doe-line and shallow sinkhole in the north east corner. Grazing effect is very low-no sheep but evidence of some rabbits and the odd cattle scat. Very long unburnt. Introduced plant species- some isolated Sonchus oleraceus and Erodium aureum but cover very low. Homogeneity- community continues 1km in all directions. Wet- recent rain in last few days.
location_description: Arubiddy Station.13.6 km north west of station homestead. 44km north west of Cocklebiddy Roadhouse.

description: Plumridge Lakes Nature Reserve. About 178kms west south west  of Tjuntjuntjara in Great Victoria Desert.
comments: Grazing effect is low- some evidence of camels with older broken trees. Very little surface strew. Site is flat plain. Introduced plant species- none noted. Homogeneity- site is in consistent patch of Acacia aneura / Acacia papyrocarpa woodland with the community extending 200m in all directions with just the odd emergent Allocasuarina pauper outside the plot.
visit_notes: Basal wedge measure difficult due to shrubby nature of site.
location_description: 120kms west of Tjuntjuntjara in Great Victoria Desert. Myall and Mulga woodland

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 15km South of Tjuntjunjara
comments: Acacia papyrocarpa low open woodland with a mid-layer dominated by Maireana sedifolia and Senna artemisioides subsp. petiolaris. Mixed forb and tussock grass ground layer dominated by Craspedia sp., Enneapogon sp. (multiple) Sandy soil with lots of Cryptogam. Long unburnt. No introduced plant species noted. Slope of 1 degree to the south east. Homogeneity- extends 200m in all directions. Recent rain- Fruiting and flowering in ground layer and the Acacia papyrocarpa.
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 15km South of Tjuntjuntjara

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 94km south west of Tjuntjuntjara
comments: Site is a flat, shallow lake or swamp. Lots of holes through the site and some gently undulating low rises. Some limestone wash and some very small limestone outcrops. Introduced plant effect is high- Carrichtera annua and Sonchus oleraceus common through the site. Grazing effect is high- dead rabbits through the site and fresh diggings and droppings. Fire- lots of standing dead litter but unburnt in previous 10 years. Homogeneity- drainage depression and associated community continues 100m to west. 200m to the north. 30m to the south and east
visit_notes: South east of Tjuntjuntjara .
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 94km south east of Tjuntjuntjara

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 98km south east of Tjuntjuntjara
comments: Plot is flat- rises very gently south of the plot .Weed effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua common through the site. Fire- difficult to tell but long unburnt. Very little cover once site dries out. Grazing effect- evidence of rabbits but overall effect is low at present. Homogeneity- community is consistent for 1km in all directions with some very small patches of denser Rhodanthe within that. Mostly limestone cobbles with some smaller gravel.
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 98km south east of Tjuntjuntjara

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve, 102.2km south east of Tjuntjuntjara
comments: Plot is flat but sits in a drainage depression between very low rises. Some limestone cobbles and gravel- larger ones with cryptogam crust. Some very low limestone outcrop- almost at ground level. Very long unburnt but difficult to tell exactly how long. Grazing effect is low- some evidence of rabbits. Introduced plant effect is moderate- Carrichtera annua common throughout the site. Homogeneity- community continues another 50m north of the road which is close to the northern edge of the plot. 20m to the east and 50m to the west where there is a low rise. 100m to the south along the drainage line.
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 114km south east of Tjuntjuntjara
comments: Undulating plain. Strew mostly limestone gravel- some pebbles. Some little pockets of outcrop/ rock.  2 degree average slope but drops away more steeply at the south east corner. Fire- long unburnt. Grazing effect is moderate to severe- big warren on western edge of the site and other close by. All still active. Introduced plant effect is low though Carrichtera annua present through the site. Homogeneity- community continues 200m from the plot in all directions.
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 114km south east of Tjuntjuntjara

description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 35.5km south of Tjuntjuntjara
comments: Plot is on a flat plain. Some limestone pebbles and gravels through the plot. Fire- long unburnt. No scarring on any of the larger shrubs. Grazing effect is low- some camels around but effect is low. Introduced plant effect minimal. Homogeneity- continues in a patchy fashion 100m in all directions
location_description: Great Victoria Desert Nature Reserve. 35.5km south of Tjuntjuntjara

description: Karijini NP. Tom Price 52.7km East
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element is a plain, the pattern is a valley. There is some surface strew of ironstone (1-5cm pebbles) scattered throughout the plot (about 40% coverage), and some less abundant smaller pebbles (1-3mm) of the same material covering about 10% of the plot. The site is homogenous; the community extends 200m N, 200m E, 100m S, and 50m W. where it is interrupted by a dirt track. The nearest infrastructure is a park access track, 50m W of the SW corner.

-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments end ---------------
Site is homogeneous >200m. Road about 30m east of plot.
location_description:
Karijini NP Mount Vigors Road about 3kms south of Karijini Drive
Fire scars on many trees. Numerous dead standing Acacia aptaneura and A. pruinocarpa. Grasses form conspicuous component of ground stratum, including Cenchrus ciliaris. Minimal impact of introduced plant species but  Cenchrus ciliaris present.

description: Karijini NP. Tom Price 52.7km East
comments:
-------------- new visit physicalStatusComments start --------------
Landform element is a plain, the pattern is a valley. There is some surface strew of ironstone (1-5cm pebbles) scattered throughout the plot (about 40% coverage), and some less abundant smaller pebbles (1-3mm) of the same material covering about 10% of the plot. The site is homogenous; the community extends 200m N, 200m E, 100m S, and 50m W. where it is interrupted by a dirt track. The nearest infrastructure is a park access track, 50m W of the SW corner.
